<1ST_LINE>r a AM-GM-Johnson     06-25 0164</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-GM-Johnson,0170</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>GM Executive To Return To Chicago Law Firm, Sources Say</HEAD>
<DATELINE>DETROIT (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Elmer Johnson, executive vice president and a
director of General Motors Corp., plans to leave the automaker and
return to a Chicago law firm, the Detroit Free Press reported in
Saturday's editions.
   The official announcement is expected to come when GM's board of
directors meets Monday, according to GM executives who spoke to the
newspaper on the condition of anonymity.
   Johnson, 56, decided to leave his job because his
often-controversial ideas to change the nation's top automaker have
been ignored, the executives said.
   Johnson was on vacation and couldn't be reached and GM declined
official comment, the newspaper said.
   Dan Vittum, a partner in the Chicago law firm of Kirkland &
Ellis, wouldn't confirm that Johnson was returning to the firm.
   Johnson has remained a partner in the firm since joining GM in
1983. He sits on its management committee, for which he receives
$30,000 annually, Vittum said.
</TEXT>
