<1ST_LINE>r a PM-BurnCamp     06-25 0632</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Burn Camp,0651</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Scarred Youngsters Get Week To Forget Their Burns</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Also in Saturday AMs report.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By ROB WELLS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WONDER VALLEY, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   From a distance, there's no telling
sign that the noisy children and teen-agers romping around a summer
camp share the deep emotional and physical scars that accompany
disfiguring burns.
   ``We try to give them a whole week to be free of their burn,''
said Shirley Turner, who heads the special camp.
   It's called Wonder Valley Ranch, this secluded spot nestled in
the Sierra Nevada Mountains 200 miles southeast of San Francisco.
This week 77 young burn survivors from Mexico to Washington state
frolicked in a swimming pool, rode ponies or cast a fishing line
into a trout pond.
   ``If my mom wouldn't have taken me, I would have walked here,''
declared David, an 11-year-old enjoying the camp sponsored by the
Alisa Ann Ruch California Burn Foundation. ``The counselors are
real cool. They treat you really nice.''
   Mrs. Turner, the foundation's executive director, described the
camp as therapy to help fortify a burn victim's self-esteem. Most
important, it lets them simply be kids free from a society too
often repelled by the disfigurement of burns.
   There is one strict rule: No one can ask the children about
their accident.
   ``That's why camp is so good for them _ they don't have to deal
with the accident,'' said Mrs. Turner. ``We don't want them
reliving that.''
   The children splashing in the pool on a hot summer morning
played as if they never had endured painful skin grafts, worn an
uncomfortable pressure garment to reduce swelling or been cruelly
teased by peers.
   As Corky and Cecily splashed around, Corky stretched her scarred
arm around Cecily's back, proclaiming with a wide smile: ``We're
friends.''
   Mrs. Turner's husband, Jim, a Los Angeles County firefighter and
foundation member, said there's little reluctance among these
summer campers to test new experiences.
   ``They've been through so much pain, they'll try anything,''
Turner said.
   The camp is rewarding for the volunteer counselors, mostly
firefighters and their spouses.
   ``If you come up here for a week, you get enough hugs and kisses
to last a year,'' said Nan Ziegler, a nurse from Long Beach.
   ``I love them. They are just little kids. They can forget what
they look like,'' said Christen Powell, a lifeguard from Clovis.
``I'm going to miss these kids.''
   Mrs. Turner said such a loving and accepting environment isn't
typical for burn survivors. Society is wary of burn victims, she
said. Some gawk at a survivor's blistered and grafted skin, while
others treat them like pariahs. She told of an incident of a
restaurant owner asking a family to leave because the sight of
their child, a burn victim, made his patrons uncomfortable.
   These experiences, along with the fact that many burn victims
remain physically scarred for life, add up to a ``devastating''
psychological effect on the victims and their families, Mrs. Turner
said. Easing such trauma is one of the foundation's goals.
   ``Now that (doctors) have solved the major medical problems and
are able to keep them alive, they are now concentrating on the
quality of life,'' she said.
   She estimated that 4,000 children are seriously burned in
California each year.
   All expenses for the children at the camp are paid by the
foundation's fund-raising efforts and volunteer labor. Mrs. Turner
estimated that the week in Wonder Valley, which ends with a trip to
Disneyland, cost the group about $100,000.
   Judging by the the children's grins, it appeared to be money
well spent.
   ``Today and this week they are just kids,'' said Mrs. Turner.
She said she hopes the camp will help make them ``strong enough
inside to take and handle the pressures their peers and adults give
them.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
