<FILEID>AP-NR-06-25-88 0058EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i PM-France-Colorization     06-25 0224</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-France-Colorization,0232</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Judge Prohibits Broadcast Of Colorized Version Of Huston Film</HEAD>
<DATELINE>PARIS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A French judge has prohibited a private television
station from broadcasting a colorized version of ``Asphalt
Jungle,'' a classic John Huston film.
   The ruling Friday was the first of its kind in France.
   Lawyers for the station, La Cinq (Channel 5), said they would
appeal. The colorized version of the 1950 film had been scheduled
to run Sunday night.
   Judge Huguette Le Foyer de Costil said the ruling affected all
of Huston's films. She noted that Huston, who died in August,
opposed colorization and it was her duty to respect his will.
   The French Society of Film Directors, which representives of
Huston's estate in France, had requested the injunction.
   ``We hope the first blow to the `colorizers' will put a
definitive stop to the surge of profiteering against creativity,''
the group said in a news release.
   Huston was so vehemently opposed to the tinting of his films
that he attended a news conference denouncing the process not long
before his death.
   A spokeswoman for La Cinq said the station had aired colorized
films previously, but none in which the authors had expressed their
disapproval.
   French laws protecting the control by artists of their works are
among the strongest in Europe but it has no specific legislation
dealing with colorization.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
