<1ST_LINE>r i PM-China-Flood     06-25 0214</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-China-Flood,0223</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Floods Kill 62 In East China</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BEIJING (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Floods and landslides caused by more than a week
of heavy rains have killed 62 people in two provinces in eastern
China, official reports said today.
   Six of the victims were children killed when a waterlogged
school building collapsed in Zhejiang province's Longquan County,
the official China Daily reported.
   Heavy rains also fell this week in Jiangxi province on
Zhejiang's western border, causing a landslide that killed at least
17 people, the paper said.
   Reports today did not specify where or how the other 39 people
died.
   The Xinhua News Agency said 212,420 acres of farmland have been
flooded and nearly 6,400 homes destroyed in Zhejiang since the
rains began June 15.
   The rains in Jiangxi have flooded 568,000 acres of farmland and
forced 14,000 people to flee their homes, the China Daily said.
   The report said four to 12 inches of rain fell on various parts
of Zhejiang during a 10-day period ending Friday. Zhejiang normally
receives about four inches of rain during the entire month of June.
   In China, the rainy season generally lasts until mid-July and
more storms are forecast.
   Heavy storms last month in the same area of China killed at
least 131 people and heavily damaged crops.
</TEXT>
