<DOCNO> AP880625-0010 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-06-25-88 0108EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i PM-Soviet-History     06-25 0790</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Soviet-History,0814</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Under Glasnost, School History Exams Give Way To `Discussion'</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Also in Saturday AMs report.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By JOHN-THOR DAHLBURG</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MOSCOW (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Before glasnost, School No. 734 would have looked
like this: 17-year-olds lined up in the hall in the summer heat,
nervously awaiting a grilling on Soviet politics and history by a
panel of teachers.
   That's what lanky, blond-haired Dmitri Predkov and his
classmates at the school in eastern Moscow had been expecting
Friday. But last month, the head of Soviet education, Gennady A.
Yagodin, suddenly ordered the tests canceled.
   The reason: The final exams would have made students in the
final year of school parrot material in textbooks now contradicted
by the revelations of Mikhail S. Gorbachev's drive for more
openness in history and other areas.
   Instead, Dmitri and his 24 classmates, like 10th graders
nationwide, were called into school for a three-hour ungraded
``discussion'' to gauge their knowledge of the past and awareness
of problems facing the Soviet Union today.
   ``We want to be sure that the children can take part in
discussions and are able to to voice their opinion anywhere,'' said
their teacher, Vera F. Zorich, 53.
   Despite that wish, most of the teen-age Muscovites who gathered
at 9 a.m. Friday around four tables in a geography classroom said
nothing during the ensuing ``discussion,'' despite repeated
prompting from teachers.
   Some, however, aired views at odds with official ideology, and
that presumably would have gotten them into trouble only a few
years ago. One even joked about the Russian Revolution.
   Predkov stood up to say that Gorbachev's program for
``perestroika,'' or economic and social restructuring, was not a
natural consequence of the growth of Soviet socialism, and that
people who say otherwise do so ``only because Gorbachev is the head
of our party.''
   ``We don't have any rights. They're just words on paper,''
declared the son of a building engineer.
   Glasnost, Dmitri added, may allow more candor about history, but
it doesn't mean Soviet citizens are getting more information about
current political problems.
   Another 17-year-old, wearing a thin black tie, said Soviets of
all schools of thought, even ``fascists,'' should have the legal
right to form their own political parties to challenge the
Communist Party that Gorbachev heads.
   Gennady Kaztman, whose father works as a printer, made his
classmates and teachers roar with laughter by telling this
bittersweet joke about the legacy of the 1917 Russian Revolution:
   When the Bolsheviks seized power, Gennady said, a Russian
countess whose grandfather had been a 19th-century revolutionary
summoned her maid to see what the shouting in the streets was about.
   ``Why, Madame, it's the revolution,'' the maid replied.
   ``Oh yes, grandfather dreamed of that. Tell me, what do they
want?'' the countess asked.
   ``Why, they want a society where there are no more rich people.''
   ``Strange,'' the countess replied. ``Grandfather wanted a
society where there were no more poor people.''
   ``Four years ago, maybe even a year ago, they would not have
dared speak like that,'' a beaming Mrs. Zorich told a visiting
reporter at the end of the meeting.
   In recent months, Soviet educators and official media have
heaped scorn on the country's history textbooks, which have been
outpaced by criticism in the glasnost-revitalized media about the
crimes of dictator Josef V. Stalin and corruption and stagnation
under Leonid I. Brezhnev.
   ``Frankly, the books are of the `hooray' type,'' said Tatyana
Cherkashena, head of teaching methods in the Moscow neighborhood
where School No. 734 is located. ``In our country, they say,
everything is wonderful _ `hooray.' Those who perished in the
repressions, those who were imprisoned, are not even mentioned.''
   A recent competition was held to select a new generation of
Soviet textbooks, but it is uncertain whether they will be ready
for the next school year in September. In the meantime, many Soviet
teachers have been using articles published in the press as the
basis for their history lessons.
   In years past, 10th grade students taking their final exams were
given a slip of paper that bore two questions on history and
civics. After a half-hour or more to prepare, they were called
before a panel of teachers to speak and answer questions.
   In May, the principal of School 734, Alexander N. Tubelsky, was
informed by the State Committee on Education that the customary
year-end history exams for senior school pupils had been canceled.
   ``We weren't told about how to structure the discussions, so we
decided to use the regular form of our history class, which the
students would feel comfortable with,'' Tubelsky said.
   ``We need to change out textbooks,'' he added. ``They are based
on a Stalinist conception that sees every event, every historical
figure, through the dogma of class warfare.''
</TEXT>
