<FILEID>AP-NR-06-25-88 0112EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a AM-AsbestosComplaint     06-25 0251</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Asbestos Complaint,0258</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Suburban School First In Nation To Be Cited Under Asbestos Removal
Rules</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By LINDSEY TANNER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Unaccredited workers botched asbestos removal at
a high school and exposed students to cancer-causing fibers, the
U.S. Environmental Protection Agency charged Friday in its first
enforcement of new regulations.
   The agency, which proposed a $5,000 fine, said 6,400 square feet
of asbestos-containing floor tiles were improperly removed in
February from a hallway at Thornton Township High School in
suburban Harvey.
   Workers who were not accredited by the EPA ``had sanded, chipped
and cut the tiles, releasing clouds of dust containing asbestos,''
the agency said in a statement.
   The district overseeing the school in southwest suburban Harvey
failed to ``post signs and restrict the affected area to only those
persons necessary to do tile removal and cleanup,'' the EPA said.
   School officials have until July 11 to respond to the complaint.
They can either seek an informal hearing with EPA officials in
Chicago or request a hearing before a federal administrative law
judge, EPA spokeswoman Nancy Sullivan said.
   The school was closed Friday afternoon and officials could not
be reached for comment.
   Ms. Sullivan said school officials did not know the tiles
contained asbestos when the removal began, but suspected they might
and ordered tests.
   The EPA called the complaint its first enforcement action
nationwide under last year's Asbestos Hazard Emergency Response
Act, which specifies procedures for removing asbestos in public and
private elementary and secondary schools.
</TEXT>
