<1ST_LINE>r i PM-BRF--Soviet-Lake     06-25 0152</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-BRF--Soviet-Lake,0156</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Kazkahstan Stops Irrigation Plans, Citing Danger To Lake</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MOSCOW (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Authorities in the Soviet republic of Kazakhstan
have bowed to public pressure and decided to halt two controversial
irrigation projects that would have damaged a vast inland lake,
TASS reported.
   The official news agency said Friday that the projects were
halted because studies showed they would cause the water level of
Lake Balkhash to drop sharply. The lake, located in Central Asia,
covers 320 square miles.
   TASS said the decision was preceded by a campaign of letters and
articles in Kazakhstan's state-run media against the scheme.
   The lake in eastern Kazakhstan helps modify the dry, scorching
climate of the area, home to about 2.5 million people, TASS said.
   Since Mikhail S. Gorbachev came to power in 1985, Soviet
authorities have stopped a number of controversial large-scale
projects that scientists say would have done irreversible damage to
the environment.
</TEXT>
