<1ST_LINE>r i PM-Paraguay-Drugs     06-25 0238</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Paraguay-Drugs,0244</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>DEA Agents, Paraguayan Police Break Up Drug Network</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ASUNCION, Paraguay (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   U.S. drug agents and Paraguayan police
captured three alleged drug smugglers and seized 590 pounds of
cocaine shortly before the drugs were supposed to go to Europe, a
newspaper reported.
   In an attempt to break what U.S. Drug Enforcement Administration
agents called the ``Asuncion Connection,'' police arrested a
Bolivian and two Colombians last Saturday. The trio allegedly were
couriers for the notorious Medellin drug cartel of Colombia, the
daily independent Hoy reported Friday.
   Hoy said 222 packages of 97 percent pure cocaine, worth about
$100 million, were found jammed in nine suitcases at Asuncion's
airport hours before a regularly scheduled commercial flight to
Madrid, Spain.
   It was the largest drug bust in Paraguay since 1982, when 92
pounds of cocaine were found at a ranch, 217 miles northeast of
Asuncion.
   U.S. Drug Enforcement Administration agents have been working
with Paraguayan police since December when they re-opened an office
in the capital to counter the growing drug trade in this landlocked
South American nation
   Investigators say private aircraft registered in bordering
Bolivia were used to drop the cocaine at a ranch in the remote
Chaco region of western Paraguay. From there, the cocaine was flown
to Asuncion in other small planes, the newspaper said.
   U.S. officials say the Medillin cartel sends to the United
States about 80 percent of the cocaine consumed in America.
</TEXT>
