<1ST_LINE>r w PM-FordAmbulances     06-25 0333</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Ford Ambulances,330</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Ambulance Association Asks Probe of Ford Recall</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By TIM BOVEE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Ambulance operators say Ford Motor Co. may
have done an inadequate job of repairing up to 14,500 fire-prone
ambulances, and they are calling for an investigation by federal
transportation officials.
   Ford counters that its recall work on the ambulances has been
more than adequate and that some ambulance operators have been slow
to bring in the vehicles for repairs.
   The American Ambulance Association, a Washington-based
organization representing private ambulance operators, said Friday
in a letter to the National Highway Traffic Safety Administration
that it had received reports of long delays, unavailable parts,
shoddy work and added bills for fixing the ambulances.
   ``It would appear that a significant number of ambulances are
still not fully retrofitted,'' the association wrote.
   Ford recalled about 14,500 of the vehicles, converted to
ambulances by other companies from the 1983-1987 Ford Econoline
E-350 models, after reports of fuel-system problems that caused
fires.
   The recall came in two phases, one in July 1987 for rerouting of
the fuel line and a second in August 1987 for installation of
further safety precautions.
   More than 20 fires were reported and were blamed on
overpressurization of fuel tanks and lines caused by muffler heat.
   ``We feel (the recall) is certainly more than adequate,'' said
Mike Parris, a Ford spokesman in Dearborn, Mich. ``We're concerned
with it. We don't take it lightly at all. We don't drag our feet.
... We've made every effort to try to get these people in here to
get this recall taken care of.''
   He said some 700 Ford dealers had parts available for the recall
work. ``If these people will bring these vehicles in, they can have
it done,'' Parris said.
   Eighty percent of the recalled ambulances were brought in for
the first phase of work, but only 65 percent have undergone the
second phase, Parris said.
   NHTSA has 120 days to respond to the ambulance association's
petition.
</TEXT>
