<1ST_LINE>r w PM-DefenseProbe-Glance     06-25 0419</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Defense Probe-Glance,400</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Latest Developments In Defense Probe</HEAD>
<HEAD>With PM-Defense Probe Bjt</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Here are highlights of the latest developments
in the investigation into allegations of fraud and bribes paid by
defense contractors and consultants to procurement officials in the
Defense Department:
</TEXT>
<HEAD>INVESTIGATORS REPORTEDLY HAVE VIDEOTAPES OF BRIBES</HEAD>
<TEXT>
   Federal investigators have videotapes of defense consultants
allegedly bribing Pentagon officials for inside information, NBC
News reported. The Pentagon officials on the tapes are Deputy
Assistant Secretary of the Air Force Victor Cohen and Deputy
Assistant Secretary of the Navy James Gaines, and the consultants
on the tapes include Melvyn Paisley, NBC reported. Attorneys for
Paisley and Gaines refused comment on the content of the report
while Cohen's attorney was not immediately available for comment.
</TEXT>
<HEAD>COMMITTEE CONSIDERS A BAN ON PAYMENTS</HEAD>
<TEXT>
   The Senate Finance Committee briefly considered a proposal that
would have allowed the government to suspend payments to defense
contractors under investigation in the case. The panel took no
action.
</TEXT>
<HEAD>CONSULTANT'S FIRM PAID WIFE OF EX-NAVY OFFICIAL UP TO $50,000</HEAD>
<TEXT>
   VAMO Inc., a Virginia firm incorporated by William Galvin, a
consultant to defense contractors, paid up to $50,000 in 1986 to
Vicki Paisley, the wife of the Navy's then-procurement chief,
Melvyn Paisley. Federal investigators have searched the offices of
both Galvin and Paisley, who left government service in 1987 to
become a defense consultant.
</TEXT>
<HEAD>SENATOR SAYS RE-NEGOTIATIONS MAY BE NEEDED</HEAD>
<TEXT>
   In a television interview, Sen. John Warner, R-Va., a former
Navy secretary, said that if a substantial number of contracts turn
out to have been tainted, they will have to be renegotiated. ``And
that's a tough, tough problem, because those contracts are
producing essential goods to our national defense today,'' Warner
said.
</TEXT>
<HEAD>MEESE COMMENTS</HEAD>
<TEXT>
   Attorney General Edwin Meese III, asked about the probe's
status, said he did not know ``whether it will expand at all,''
adding: ``It's at the normal stage of an investigation ... where
you're collecting information, you're analyzing information and
then you're determining what the next steps might be.''
</TEXT>
<HEAD>COMPANY WANTS TO SEE AFFIDAVIT</HEAD>
<TEXT>
   An attorney for United Technologies Corp. said he has asked U.S.
District Judge John H. Pratt to allow the company to examine a
government affidavit supporting a search warrant that the judge had
issued. The warrant enabled FBI agents to search the Washington
office of Eugene Tallia, a vice president for Washington operations
of the company's Pratt & Whitney engine manufacturing unit. Company
lawyers said they wanted to determine whether the search was proper.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
