<FILEID>AP-NR-06-25-88 0154EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i PM-Salvador-Relief     06-25 0290</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Salvador-Relief,0298</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Church Charges Army Prevented Delivery Of Supplies To Refugees</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SAN SALVADOR, El Salvador (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Representatives from eight
California churches say El Salvador's army stopped them from
delivering food, medicine and fertilizer to resettled refugees in
northern El Salvador.
   Eight representatives of Bay Area churches and synagogues told a
news conference Friday that the 4th Army Brigade blocked their
three-truck convoy on June 16.
   The convoy, which was carrying about $7,000 worth of supplies,
was stopped in Chalatenango, the capital of the northern province
of the same name.
   The supplies, which were bound for the towns of Guarjila and Los
Ranchos, were left in a convent in the town while efforts to
deliver them continued, the church workers said.
   Leftist guerrillas battling the U.S.-backed government of
President Jose Napoleon Duarte maintain a strong military and
political presence in much of Chalatenango province.
   Dean McFalls, a member of the church group and a student at the
Pacific School of Religion in Berkeley, Calif., said the delegation
had obtained permission to deliver the supplies from military
officials in San Salvador before leaving for the region.
   Los Ranchos and Guarjila were evacuated in the early 1980s
because of heavy fighting in the civil war. The towns were
resettled last fall under the auspices of the non-governmental
National Committee for Repopulation. They now have a combined
population of about 1,800.
   Over the past year the armed forces have allowed some relief
shipments to reach their destinations but have held up others.
Military authorities have expressed concern the supplies might end
up in rebel hands.
   People who answered the phone at 4th Brigade headquarters and
the army's public relations office said no one was immediately
available for comment on the blocked convoy.
</TEXT>
