<FILEID>AP-NR-06-25-88 0604EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r w PM-PentagonSpending     06-25 0330</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Pentagon Spending,330</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Pentagon Relaxes Some Spending Limits After Cost-Cutting Freeze</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Pentagon plans to resume offering
contracts for research and consulting work next month but other
restrictions on military spending will remain in effect in order to
hold down costs.
   Deputy Defense Secretary William H. Taft IV on Friday announced
plans to relax a freeze on outside contracting for supplies and
services starting July 1. The freeze had been imposed in May to
limit spending in fiscal 1988, which ends on Sept. 30.
   Taft said Friday he would begin allowing some new contracts to
be awarded for research, development and evaluation work and for
consultant services on July 1.
   But all other restrictions remain in effect, including a ban on
purchases of office supplies, an end to overtime pay and limits on
civilian hiring, Taft said.
   Active-duty personnel and civilian employees also can forget
collecting their Oct. 1 paychecks a day early just because Oct. 1
falls on a Saturday, Taft declared. The Pentagon doesn't want any
extra outlays before the current fiscal year ends, he wrote in a
memo to Pentagon offices.
   The Pentagon's No. 2 executive said he still wanted some
controls on the research and consultant contracts, however,
specifying that ``total obligations during any month of the fourth
quarter may not exceed 75 percent of the average monthly
obligations incurred to date.''
   The ban on new purchases of office supplies and other equipment
will continue to cover everything from magazine and newspaper
subscriptions to TV sets, library materials, recreation equipment,
lawnmowers and furniture, tools, paint, lumber, air conditioners
and fork lifts, he said.
   Also still prohibited is any spending on new leases for cars,
office space or computer equipment.
   The spending restrictions originally were promulgated by Taft to
comply with a deficit-reduction compromise reached last November by
Congress and the Reagan administration. That compromise was crafted
to control government outlays _ the amount of money actually paid
out during the fiscal year.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880625-0029 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-06-25-88 0155EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r w PM-HazardousMail     06-25 0381</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Hazardous Mail,350</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Dangerous Biological Agents To Be Banned From Mail</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The U.S. Postal Service is proposing new rules
to ban germs and dangerous toxins from the mail just as the
military reportedly was planning to increase shipments of such
materials.
   The regulations were announced Friday, but must go through a
formal rule-making process before they take effect.
   The Postal Service said it took the action because of concern
``that some customers are planning increased use of the mails for
sending disease germs or hazardous toxins (etiologic agents).''
   Jeremy Rifkin, an activist who heads the Foundation on Economic
Trends in Washington, hailed the decision as a step toward avoiding
a potential catastrophe. He had petitioned the Postal Service to
ban such shipments.
   Rifkin said he plans to push the Transportation Department to
investigate shipments of dangerous products by private carriers.
   Various products, including biological warfare toxins, have been
mailed in the past under strict packaging and labeling rules, and
postal officials say no problems have occurred.
   But following reports that the Army planed to expand research
facilities in Utah, California Attorney General John Van de Kamp
complained that the need for increased shipments of dangerous
biological products could create a hazard.
   Army officials have told a House subcommittee that they actually
ship very few parcels containing biological items, and those almost
always by private, commercial carrier.
   The packages have been tested and are literally able to survive
an aircraft or highway crash, said Thomas R. Dashiell, director of
environmental and life sciences at the Defense Department.
   While attention has focused on shipments of germs and toxins by
the military, the federal Centers for Disease Control and other
medical establishments also make such shipments, officials report.
   ``Our experience to date seems to support the opinion, expressed
by medical experts, that there is little risk associated with
handling properly packaged etiologic agents,'' Postmaster General
Anthony Frank said in a letter to Rifkin.
   The planned new rules would cover dangerous items, but would not
affect the mailing of blood samples and other such materials being
sent to laboratories for routine medical testing, the Postal
Service said.
   Postal regulations already prohibit the mailing of a variety of
items, including strike-anywhere matches, explosives, fuses, many
poisons, most flammable liquids and certain chemicals.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
