<FILEID>AP-NR-06-25-88 0200EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r w PM-PlantClosing     06-25 0352</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Plant Closing,350</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Showdown Vote Nears On Requirement For Notice Of Plant Closings</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Senate is headed for a showdown vote next
week on a proposal that would require companies to give their
workers advance notice of major layoffs or plant closings.
   Senate Minority Leader Bob Dole, R-Kan., said a GOP amendment
would be proposed Monday to either eliminate the 60-day notice
requirement for layoffs or shorten it.
   Democrats in the Senate on Friday overwhelmingly defeated a pair
of Republican amendments to the legislation.
   Defeated on respective votes of 60-27 and 59-31 were amendments
to make picket line violence during a labor dispute a federal crime
and to exempt from the notice requirements employers who give
laid-off workers 60 days of severance pay.
   After stalling action on the legislation for three days,
Republican leaders agreed Friday to allow a vote late Monday on
their main attempt to derail the notice requirements.
   The notice provision has come before the Senate after being
separated from a trade bill that President Reagan vetoed last month
because it contained that requirement.
   Dole said a GOP amendment would be offered on Monday by Sen.
Nancy Kassebaum, R-Kan. Mrs. Kassebaum has said she supports 60
days' notice in cases of plant closings but not when an employer is
just laying off 50 or more workers, as the Democratic-sponsored
bill requires.
   Democratic leaders have threatened to kill to any chance of
winning enactment of either the advance notice requirement or the
trade bill if Mrs. Kassebaum's amendment is approved.
   ``This is a killer amendment,'' said Majority Leader Robert C.
Byrd, D-W.Va. ``Not only does it kill this bill but it will kill
the trade bill. I've maintained all along that the president
doesn't want a trade bill.''
   Democrats still hope to send the plant closing measure to the
White House by July 4 for an expected veto by Reagan.
   Byrd said Friday he anticipates final passage of the plant
closings bill by the Senate on Tuesday. House Speaker Jim Wright,
D-Texas, has vowed to seek its passage in the House immediately
after the Senate's approval.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880625-0032 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-06-25-88 0207EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r w PM-US-SouthAfrica     06-25 0400</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-US-South Africa,400</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Study Finds US Sanctions Cut Exports To South Africa</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A government study of U.S. sanctions against
South Africa says that nation in the past two years has suffered a
$624 million reduction in exports of sanctioned goods to the United
States and other trading partners.
   The General Accounting Office report, presented Friday to the
Senate Foreign Relations Committee, said exports to the United
States had been cut by about $417 million and that the remainder of
the reduction was in South Africa's exports of sanctioned goods to
19 other countries.
   ``Only in the agricultural products market was South Africa able
to offset losses from U.S. sanctions and to actually increase its
total exports,'' said Allan I. Mendelowitz, an associate director
of the GAO's international division.
   Mendelowitz said that since the enactment of the sanctions over
President Reagan's veto in 1986, South Africa experienced sharp
losses in exports of coal, iron and steel, uranium and textiles.
   ``I think the bottom line, in shorthand, is that sanctions are
working in terms of economic impact,'' said Sen. Paul Simon,
D-Ill., a member of the Senate panel. ``What we cannot know is
whether this will result in a policy change by South Africa.''
   The testimony came as the committee concluded three days of
public hearings on legislation to tighten sanctions against South
Africa by requiring a near-total trade embargo and by requiring all
U.S. companies to withdraw from the country.
   Mendelowitz said that since 1984, 162 U.S. companies have
withdrawn from South Africa and that nine of the 150 companies
remaining have announced their intention to leave.
   Opponents of the new sanctions have raised the possibility South
Africa might retaliate by cutting off exports to the United States
of a list of strategic minerals of vital importance to U.S.
industry.
   Mendelowitz noted the U.S. Bureau of Mines recently reported
there are sufficient alternative sources of supply for manganese,
chromium, palladium, titanium and vanadium but not for platinum and
rhodium.
   The mines bureau also said that cobalt supplies would remain
available from Zaire if new routes for shipping it were developed
to bypass South African railways and ports.
   Other witnesses representing U.S. companies remaining in South
Africa opposed the legislation, contending it would cost the jobs
of thousands of black South Africans and shut down the programs
they have instituted changes
   improve the lot of their black employees.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880625-0033 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-06-25-88 0047EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u a BC-Jazz     06-25 0461</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-Jazz,0481</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Louis Armstrong Music Launches Jazz Festival</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Will stand for PMs.</NOTE>
<HEAD>Laserphoto NY5</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MARY CAMPBELL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   ``For the Love of Louis,'' the concert of Louis
Armstrong's music that kicked off the JVC Jazz Festival at Carnegie
Hall, provided an evening of full of high notes.
   One such high note came from Lionel Hampton and Wynton Marsalis
as they played in duet on vibraphone and trumpet. Dizzy Gillespie
gave us others as he softly improvised on ``I'm Confessin' That I
Love You'' and then sang it, sounding a lot like Louis.
   Clark Terry recalled that Armstrong once advised him: ``You got
to do more singing. People like singing. And you save your
(trumpet-playing) chops.''
   Terry played ``You Rascal You,'' which Sam Theard composed for
Armstrong. Then Terry sang it, imitating Armstrong.
   Dick Hyman organized the Friday night program, conducted and
played piano.
   Master of ceremonies Phil Schaap called Armstrong ``the most
important musician of the 20th century.'' He gave particulars about
Armstrong's recordings, which were then played live on stage.
   The concert's first half represented the Hot Five, Hot Seven and
other small groups that Armstrong made music with in the 1920s and
'30s. Carrie Smith sang some of the songs Armstrong and Bessie
Smith recorded. Trumpeter Ruby Braff played a medley.
   Three members of Armstrong's last band, clarinetist Joe Muranyi,
bassist Arvell Shaw and pianist Marty Napoleon, joined Miss Smith,
trumpeter Jimmy Maxwell and trombonist George Masso for ``Basin
Street.''
   Five trumpeters in the big band after intermission were
impressive. Warren Vache soloed on ``Sunny Side of the Street,''
Jimmy Owens on ``When Your Lover Has Gone'' and Jon Faddis on
``When You're Smiling.''
   A film showed Armstrong telling how he composed ``Someday You'll
Be Sorry'' on a cold night in North Dakota. Randy Sandke soloed on
that. Maxwell soloed as Miss Smith sang ``Mack the Knife.''
   Gillespie, Clark, Marsalis and Hampton returned for ``Ding Dong
Daddy from Dumas.'' Hampton started a nostalgically played encore
of the ``Memories of You,'' the first recording he ever played on,
which was a Louis Armstrong date.
   The evening was a benefit for Queens College, which administers
the house in Queens where Louis Armstrong lived the 30 years before
he died July 6, 1971, and which was willed to New York City. Queens
College intends to turn it into a museum. The college hoped to
raise $80,000 from the evening, which also would benefit its
Armstrong archives project and music scholarships.
   A block of benefit tickets sold for $100 or $250, which included
a dinner afterwards. Festival impresario George Wein announced that
Ruby Braff, Dizzy Gillespie, Lionel Hampton, Wynton Marsalis and
Clark Terry donated their appearances and other musicians rehearsed
for three days for scale.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
