<HEAD>Memorial To Be Built To Lvov Ghetto</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: CLARIFIES that Lvov is in the Ukraine.</NOTE>
<DATELINE>MOSCOW (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A memorial will be built to honor thousands of
victims who perished in the Nazi destruction of Lvov's Jewish
ghetto and in a nearby concentration camp, Tass said.
   The official news agency announced Friday plans for the memorial
in a report on the end of ceremonies marking the 45th anniversary
of the ghetto's destruction by the Nazis and Ukrainian nationalists.
   Lvov is a city in the Ukraine.
   Zigmund Lainer, a survivor from the Lvov ghetto, was quoted as
saying that the Nazis burned bodies and crushed the skeletons of
those who perished at the nearby Yanovsky concentration camp to
hide their crimes.
   ``Very few people survived that inferno,'' Lainer was quoted as
saying. ``But the memory and the truth about the Lvov ghetto still
exist.''
   Tass said city authorities have discussed creating a school and
a synagogue to preserve the Jewish culture that once flourished in
the city.
