<1ST_LINE>r p PM-Jackson     06-25 0308</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Jackson,300</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Jackson Starts Gaining Delegates In Puerto Rico</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAN SEWELL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SAN JUAN, Puerto Rico (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Jesse Jackson, who defeated Michael
Dukakis in a ``beauty contest'' presidential ballot in March, says
he is finally starting to gain some of Puerto Rico's delegates to
the Democratic National Convention next month.
   Although Jackson had won the March 20 primary, the voting was
only advisory. In April, Gov. Rafael Hernandez Colon said he and at
least 53 others in the Puerto Rico delegation would support Dukakis
at the national convention in Atlanta.
   After meeting Friday night with the governor and legislative
leaders, Jackson said he has picked up at least eight of Puerto
Rico's 57 delegates to the Democratic convention since arriving
here Thursday night, and his campaign said he wants at least 17.
   ``What is at stake here is more than the nomination. It's the
future of our country, the future of relations. When we get to
Atlanta, he may very well have more delegates, but I will have more
supporters,'' Jackson told reporters.
   The 3.2 million Puerto Ricans are U.S. citizens who are largely
self-governing but subject to federal laws. They have delegations
at the presidential nominating conventions. But Puerto Rican
residents do not vote in national elections and their
representative in Congress has no vote.
   Jackson said he supports Puerto Rican self-determination. Puerto
Ricans, he said, should ``choose their own form of government with
no interference and without intimidation.''
   He has indicated he supports a transfer of powers from the
United States before a Puerto Rican vote on political status. The
governing party supports commonwealth status, established in 1952,
but wants greater local power.
   Some believe ending legal ties to the United States before
voting on status would virtually rule out statehood. Republican
presidential nominee-to-be George Bush supports statehood for
Puerto Rico.
</TEXT>
