<HEAD>EEOC Notifying Age-Bias Complainants of Mishandled Cases</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   More than 7,500 people who filed age
discrimination complaints with the Equal Employment Opportunity
Commission will be getting notice from the agency that they may
have a second chance to pursue their cases.
   The commission last month sent out the notices to people whose
age discrimination complaints may have been mishandled, EEOC
Chairman Clarence Thomas said Friday.
   ``We blanketed the world with them,'' Thomas said of the notices
during a break in a hearing by the Senate Special Committee on
Aging. ``We did not want to underestimate. We know we overestimated
... We'll make absolutely sure that there are none left hanging out
there.''
   The notices were sent, as required by the Age Discrimination
Claims Assistance Act signed into law by President Reagan on April
7, following revelations that EEOC workers had let hundreds of
cases expire beyond the statute of limitations.
