<1ST_LINE>r a PM-Manigat     06-25 0378</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Manigat,0391</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Manigat Pleads For U.S. Support</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RICHARD COLE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MIAMI (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Haiti's ousted President Leslie Manigat planned to
spend the weekend with friends in Miami before flying to Europe
Sunday in search of the support he failed to find in the Haitian
expatriate community here.
   Manigat, who arrived here Friday with his wife Myrlande and
teen-age daughter Beatrice, said he had not decided where to settle
or what to do in the immediate future.
   Exiled to the Dominican Republic last Sunday when he was
overthrown by Lt. Gen. Henri Namphy, Manigat appealed to Americans
for support in freeing Haiti from the military dictatorship.
   ``Give us your support against the military coup,'' Manigat
pleaded at Miami International Airport. ``Give us your support for
the reestablishment of democracy in Haiti.''
   He said he shared the basic U.S. democratic values and was
overthrown for trying to ``put forward the fundamental principle of
civilian power over the military.'' He also said some in the
military were angered by his fight against corruption and smuggling.
   But local leaders in South Florida's Haitian community, thought
to number up to 100,000, said they would ignore Manigat's visit,
calling him a discarded military puppet installed through a rigged
election.
   ``We could care less about Manigat,'' said Roger Biamby,
president of the Haitian-American Community Association of Dade
County.
   Only about 25 Haitians _ many of them worried family members of
Manigat advisers imprisoned in Haiti after the coup _ showed up at
the airport to greet him.
   Asked why U.S. Haitians did not support him, Manigat noted that
many of Jesus Christ's followers had not supported him at the time
of the crucifiction, but cautioned he was not comparing himself to
Jesus.
   Manigat called on the U.S. to pressure Namphy's government to
release his advisers, whom he said were still being arrested on a
daily basis.
   He ignored shouted questions about his relationship with Col.
Jean-Claude Paul, under indictment here for drug trafficking.
Manigat's decision to side with Paul against Namphy triggered the
coup which once again put Namphy in control of the country, the
poorest in the Western Hemisphere.
   The ousted leader plans to fly Sunday to Rome, where he will
attend a meeting of Christian Democratic party leaders.
</TEXT>
