<FILEID>AP-NR-06-25-88 0325EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i PM-Japan-Panama     06-25 0293</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Japan-Panama,0301</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Japan Says Noriega Government In Panama Not Illegal</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Japan announced today that unlike the United States
it does not believe the government of Panamanian military leader
Gen. Manual Antonio Noriega is illegal.
   ``We have found no evidence that the present government of
Panama is illegal,'' said a Foreign Ministry official, speaking on
condition of anonymity. ``Whether or not their government is legal
is no longer an issue in Panama either.''
   On Thursday, the Japanese ambassador to Panama, Teruyuki Sawai,
met Panamanian Foreign Minister Jorge Abadia Arias for the first
time since Noriega engineered the ouster of former President Eric
Arturo Delvalle.
   On Feb. 25, the military-controlled legislative assembly ousted
Delvalle, who had tried to fire Noriega, commander of Panama's
15,000-member Defense Forces.
   Noriega has been indicted by two U.S. federal grand juries on
drug- trafficking charges. He has successfully resisted U.S.
economic sanctions aimed at forcing him to step down. President
Reagan has consistently called the present Panamanian government
illegal.
   The Japanese official declined to elaborate on Thursday's
meeting, which was held in Panama, saying only that it followed
actions by other countries, including Italy, France, Spain, Mexico,
and West Germany.
   Japan had withheld its official position on Panama, apparently
for fear of antagonizing the United States.
   Panama is a major consumer of Japanese goods. In addition, the
Panama Canal serves as a vital link for Japanese products bound for
the East Coast of America and for agricultural products headed for
Japan.
   Japan, Panama's second largest trading partner after the United
States, maintains a $3.2 billion trade surplus with the central
American nation. In turn, Panama is Japan's largest export market
in Latin America as well as the top recipient of Japanese direct
investment in the region.
</TEXT>
