<FILEID>AP-NR-06-25-88 0333EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a PM-HotelDeath     06-25 0420</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Hotel Death,0433</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Collapse Kills Man In $200-A-Night Manhattan Hotel Room</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RAYNER PIKE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A concrete ceiling weakened by a long-term leak
that had been covered up collapsed on a guest at the Helmsley
Windsor hotel, killing him as he slept in his $200-a-night,
top-floor suite, authorities said.
   The victim, Carmello Liuzzo, 35, of Greensboro, N.C. was buried
under the debris that fell onto and around his bed early Friday.
One 4-foot hunk of concrete about 10 inches thick fell squarely on
his body, said police Lt. Steve Davis.
   Between 1{ and 2 tons of concrete, plaster and cinder crashed
into the small bedroom.
   City Buildings Commissioner Charles Smith said a summons will be
issued to Harry and Leona Helmsley, who head the organization that
controls the hotel. They would be cited for ``failure to maintain a
structurally sound building,'' which could bring up to a $5,000
fine and 30 days in jail.
   ``I think it's clear that they were aware that there had been
deterioration,'' Smith said at a news conference. ``The false
ceiling is evidence that they tried to cover up a badly damaged
ceiling.''
   He said his inspectors found an indentation 3 inches deep and 6
feet across on the roof in which rain and melted snow collected and
leaked into cinder insulation between two concrete slabs.
   Over time, the insulation became heavy and compacted and the
water visibly rusted and deteriorated reinforcement in the lower
slab, he said.
   ``It had not been repaired _ it had been covered up,'' said
Smith. ``Someone did not do their job.''
   The 304-room hotel, which Smith said dates from 1926, is leased
by Winmar Operating Corp., a subsidiary of the Helmsley
organization, said hotel spokesman Doug Hearle.
   A statement issued in the name of Mrs. Helmsley, president of
Helmsley Hotels, said, ``We were shocked and devastated to hear of
the tragedy. ... Our hearts go out to the family.
   ``We have a team of consulting structural engineers conducting
an in-depth examination of the entire building. Until that is
completed, we won't comment on the buildings commissioner's
statements,'' the statement said.
   According to Inspector James McCabe, Liuzzo checked into the
midtown hotel Wednesday with his wife.
   The couple had asked for a $120-a-night room, Hearle said.
Because none was available, they were given a better accommodation
at the same price _ Room 1628, a $200 corner suite with a bedroom,
parlor, pantry and bath, Hearle said.
   Mrs. Liuzzo checked out Thursday, McCabe said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
