<DOCNO> AP880625-0050 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-06-25-88 0433EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i PM-Britain-Iran     06-25 0245</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Britain-Iran,0253</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Briton Held In Iran Pleas For Better Relations</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A British businessman held in an Iranian prison
has issued a plea for better relations between Britain and Iran.
   Roger Cooper's appeal came in a 16-page handwritten letter
released Friday by a parliamentary delegation back from an
unofficial mission to Iran.
   John Lyttle, spokesman for Archbishop of Canterbury Robert
Runcie, said Cooper gave him the letter while he was in Iran. He
passed it on to the four-member delegation, which returned to
Britain on Wednesday.
   The letter, dated June 20, said news of the mission ``filled me
with hope,'' and urged Britain to take the initiative to improve
relations.
   Cooper, 53, has lived in Iran for more than 20 years. He was
arrested in December 1985 and jailed for alleged spying. He is
being held in Tehran's Evin Prison.
   ``Britain is seen as a sly neo-colonialist, `an old fox' much
more skilled than the Americans or Russians in politics _ and
therefore potentially more dangerous,'' the letter said.
   It said Iranians criticized Britain for participation in a
U.S.-led economic blockade of Iran and for supplying Iraq with
materials useful in its nearly 8-year-old war with Iran.
   The letter pleaded for increased aid, trade and cultural
relations with Iran.
   Runcie, leader of the Church of England, arranged the mission's
three-day visit to explore ways of bringing about the release of
Britons in Lebanon who are believed held by pro-Iranian Shiite
Moslem extremists.
</TEXT>
