<1ST_LINE>r i PM-Mao'sGrandson     06-25 0424</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Mao's Grandson,0438</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Mao's Grandson a `Huge Monster' But an Average Student</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BEIJING (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Chairman Mao's grandson might be tall and hefty
but that's the only thing that makes him stand out in a crowd, a
newspaper reported today.
   China Youth News said the 18-year-old grandson of late leader
Mao Tse-tung ``could be considered a `huge monster' when compared
with the average high school student.''
   Mao Xinyu, who stands 5-foot, 10-inches tall and weighs nearly
220 pounds, is the son of Mao Anqing, Mao Tse-tung's only known
living son.
   A report last December said the 62-year-old Mao Anqing, his
wife, Zhang Shaohua, and their only son were living quietly in a
Beijing villa.
   Mao Tse-tung married four times and had nine children, including
a daughter by his last wife, Jiang Qing. He died in 1976. Jiang
Qing is believed alive.
   Detailed reports of the lives of China's leaders and their
families are rare.
   The paper described the high school senior as an amiable and
cheerful youth who gets along well with his classmates and is
treated just like any other student.
   He is fond of history ``perhaps because of the historical legacy
of his forefathers,'' and his best grades are in history class, the
report said.
   Besides his schoolbooks and some historical writings, Xinyu also
likes to read classical novels, historical drama and classical
poetry, it said.
   As he prepares for the nationwide college entrance exams that
will be administered next month, Xinyu is still trying to decide
what to study. He likes history, but thinks law or philosophy might
be more practical, the newspaper said.
   Philosophy is considered practical in China because graduates in
the field are often assigned jobs in poweful propaganda bureaus.
   Xinyu was born Jan. 17, 1970, in the midst of the ultra-leftist
Cultural Revolution, and rarely saw his father for the first six
years of his life, the report said.
   ``However, this has not prevented Xinyu from respecting his
father,'' the report said. Mao Anqing is believed to suffer from
mental illness, but the paper made no mention of his health.
   Xinyu's classmates often discuss their impressions of Chairman
Mao and his mistakes, and Xinyu willingly joins in these
discussion, it said.
   ``Actually, except that he is Mao's grandson, Xinyu's appraisal
of this great historical figure is no different from that of his
classmates,'' the report said.
   Since the end of the Cultural Revolution in 1976, Mao has been
criticized for creating a cult of personality and for leftist
excesses that drove China's economy into the ground.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
