<1ST_LINE>r i PM-Soviet-Party     06-25 0471</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Soviet-Party,0488</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Party Conference to Take Up Freer Economic Competition</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MARK J. PORUBCANSKY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MOSCOW (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Speakers at next week's national Communist Party
conference will plea for greater economic competition in the
state-run economy, an adviser to Soviet leader Mikhail Gorbachev
said.
   Leonid Abalkin, head of the economics institute in the Soviet
Academy of Sciences, called Friday for an ``atmosphere of
competition, winning over the consumer,'' and open competition by
individual enterprises for state orders.
   Reformers have heavily criticized the centrally controlled
system of economic planning.
   However, Abalkin said the country's economic system will be
radically changed beginning in the early 1990s, and those changes
will be discussed at the conference that begins Tuesday.
   Abalkin said several speeches to the conference of 5,000
delegates will be devoted to encouraging economic competition. His
comments represented one of the few signs from officials of a
specific topic to be considered and an indication of the issue's
importance in the eyes of economic reformers.
   The economist is a delegate to the party conference and a key
adviser to Gorbachev.
   Several speeches to the party conference will criticize the
system of government procurement, now accomplished by a vast system
of orders to individual state-run businesses, he said.
   Reforms don't intend to do away with government procurement, but
change ``the ways they reach the enterprises, not the old ways _
command and bureaucratic _ but the method based on competition
between enterprises to win government orders,'' Abalkin said.
   ``I am certain that more than one statement will be devoted to
this question,'' he said.
   He added that satisfying pent-up demand for consumer goods and
services ``will be possible only if the monopolization by the
producer is ruled out and economic competition between individual
enterprises is asserted.''
   Reformers trace many of the Soviet Union's economic problems to
a bureaucratic system of management that stifles local initiative
and ignores market demands.
   Asked about a radical Estonian economic program for the party
conference, Abalkin said central authorities must allow local
officials more economic freedom but be careful not to permit a rise
of nationalism.
   The Estonian platform for the party conference asks central
authorities to give the republic complete control over prices,
wages and investment policy.
   Officials have indicated that the conference will discuss
problems among the more than 100 ethnic groups that live in the
Soviet Union.
   The problems have been highlighted in recent months by unrest in
Estonia and other Baltic republics and a tense dispute between
Armenia and Azerbaijan over control of the Nagorno-Karabakh region
of Azerbaijan.
   The conference, the first since 1941, is to consider a program
put forth by the party's policy-making Central Committee that calls
for party bureaucrats to stop interfering in government decisions
and economic management.
   It also seeks to limit the terms of elected party officials.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
