<1ST_LINE>r i PM-Lebanon-Pollution     06-25 0255</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Lebanon-Pollution,0263</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Official Report: Lebanon's Waters Not Radioactive</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BEIRUT, Lebanon (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Lebanese territorial waters are neither
radioactive nor contaminated by tons of Italian toxic waste that
have been dumped in recent months in this chaotic country, news
reports said today.
   Beirut's daily As-Safir said the Lebanese Health Ministry issued
a report saying the waters were not contaminated after an expert
committee examined samples of sea water Friday.
   A Lebanese businessman imported 2,400 tons of toxic chemical
waste from Italy two weeks ago and some of it was reported dumped
on the Kesrouan coastal strip 20 miles north of Beirut.
   In addition, about 40 barrels inscribed ``Cairo Oil'' and
containing suspicious-looking pink and golden powder were
discovered off the coast of Tyre in south Lebanon, and Tabarja in
the north.
   The two events, combined with an outbreak of skin rashes among
people who swam in the sea, drove the usually stoic Lebanese off
their beaches.
   ``The contents of the barrels, the sea water and fish examined
are not radioactive,'' said the report.
   ``The barrels contain organic brown powder that does not include
any heavy poisonous metallic material,'' it said.
   The ministry qualifed the report in saying it was sending
``maritime biological and geological samples for further
examination abroad to determine whether future risks are
involved.'' It did not elaborate or say where it was sending the
samples.
   The statement urged the Lebanese not to swim in the sea and to
avoid eating fish, pending the outcome of the final report expected
in two weeks.
</TEXT>
