<1ST_LINE>r i PM-HongKong     06-25 0269</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Hong Kong,0276</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>British Envoy Says Chinese Sensitive to Hong Kong Fears</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BEIJING (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Chinese officials are listening carefully to Hong
Kong residents' worries about laws that will govern them when the
colony reverts to Chinese rule in 1997, a British envoy said today.
   Meanwhile, Hong Kong's government announced today that Britain
will increase its share of the colony's defense costs during the
nine years before China takes over.
   In a brief statement, the government said Britain will shoulder
35 percent of defense costs, up from 25 percent under the formula
that expired March 31.
   About 13,000 British soldiers and dependents are stationed on
the colony.
   In Beijing, Lord Glenarthur, Britain's state minister for Asian
affairs, told a news conference that he discussed Hong Kong
residents' concerns with Chinese officials.
   Many in Hong Kong fear the draft of its future ``basic law,'' or
constitution, does not adequately protect civil liberties and could
be changed by the Chinese after 1997 to further reduce freedoms.
The draft was completed in April, and the Chinese legislature was
expected to pass a final version by 1990.
   ``It was quite clear to me that (Chinese Vice Foreign Minister)
Zhou Nan paid careful attention to what I was saying and that the
Chinese government is taking equally careful note of the views
expressed in Hong Kong,'' the British envoy said.
   Britain has ruled the thriving port of Hong Kong, on China's
southeast coast, since 1842.
   The British official also said Chinese leaders expressed support
for the recent decision by Hong Kong's colonial government to
repatriate those Vietnamese boat people not fleeing political
persecution.
</TEXT>
