<1ST_LINE>r a PM-SavimbiVisit     06-25 0405</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Savimbi Visit,0418</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Rebel Leader Defends South African Support</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JAMES MARTINEZ</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MIAMI (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Angolan guerrilla leader Jonas Savimbi's fervor for
stopping communism in his homeland was hailed by Cuban exiles here,
yet his acceptance of arms from South Africa has raised questions.
   Savimbi, head of Angola's UNITA rebels, spoke here Friday as
part of a U.S. tour to drum up support and discuss peace talks
aimed at ending the 13-year civil war with Angola's Marxist,
Cuban-backed government.
   But the burly, personable Savimbi has found himself on a public
relations tightrope. He is cheered for his struggle for democratic
freedom, yet denounced for accepting arms from a government that
openly practices racial discrimination.
   ``I'm not here to discuss the policies of South Africa, which I
condemn. I'm fighting for freedom and you must do it any way you
can,'' Savimbi told a news conference. ``When you are fighting for
your country, you must get help from even the devil himself.''
   Savimbi, who has been criticized by Democratic presidential
contender Michael Dukakis and influential blacks, said that even
American patriots enlisted the aid of European monarchies in the
revolution against the British monarchy.
   ``In a fight for freedom, sometimes you have to look out for
your interests first,'' he said.
   Savimbi said a Cuban troop buildup in Angola clouds the peace
talks that began this week in Cairo, Egypt, the third round of
discussions in two months.
   The United States, which also helps arm the Angolan guerrillas,
is mediating between South Africa and a joint Angolan-Cuban
delegation to resolve Angola's civil war and end South African rule
over neighboring Namibia.
   The talks have so far hinged on South Africa's demand that Cuba
withdraw its troops from Angola as a precondition for Namibia's
independence.
   ``There were 45,000 Cuban troops in March, and now there are
57,000,'' Savimbi said. ``They're not withdrawing; they're
increasing tremendously.
   Savimbi's one-day visit to Miami was sponsored by the
Cuban-American National Foundation, a staunchly anti-communist
group with offices here and in Washington.
   Foundation head Jorge Mas Canosa said a private dinner honored
Savimbi Friday night to show support for his cause but not to raise
money.
   ``He knows he has our support,'' Mas Canosa said. ``We've
provided hospital beds, food and medicine to his troops in the past
and we are ready to do it again.''
   Savimbi plans to meet with President Reagan in Washington next
week.
</TEXT>
