<HEAD>Human Rights Lawyer Shot Dead In Central Philippines</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MANILA, Philippines (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Gunmen killed a human rights lawyer
as he stood with his daughter in his house in the central
Philippine island of Cebu, police reported today.
   Alfonso Surigao, 41, was the second human rights lawyer killed
in the country in a week. Last Saturday, five unidentified men shot
dead Ramon Cura in his home near the U.S. Clark Air Base north of
here.
   The leftwing Partido ng Bayan (People's Party-PNB) said Surigao
had been a candidate in congressional elections last year. He also
chaired the Visayas region chapter of Amnesty International and was
a member of various human rights groups.
   In a statement released today, the party denounced the killing
of the two lawyers and said the incidents ``are part of a
systematic plan to eliminate leaders of legal democratic
organizations.''
   Police said the gunmen entered the house of Surigao in Pardo
district in Cebu, about 360 miles southeast of here, and shot the
lawyer twice in the head. No suspects have been arrested.
