<1ST_LINE>r a PM-TrainDerailment     06-25 0410</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Train Derailment,0419</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Fire Burning Out Again, Some Remain Evacuated</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CROFTON, Ky. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Workers began to dismantle the exterior of a
derailed CSX tanker in preparation for its move to a safe place
today after awaiting the burnout of a toxic fire that prompted the
evacuation of 15,000.
   The fire had died down enough by late Friday to allow workers to
remove the ruptured steel jacket of the car.
   James H. ``Mike'' Molloy, executive director of the state
Division of Disaster and Emergency Services, said a survey team
determined at mid-afternoon Friday that 20 percent of the caustic
white phosphorus remained in the tanker.
   Don Armstrong, a DES spokesman, said plans called for placing
the hull on a flat-bed rail car today and shipping it to a safe
area to remove the remaining phosphorus.
   About 40 families displaced when the tanker derailed Wednesday
night, creating a toxic cloud that forced the evacuation of 15,000
people from eight western Kentucky counties, will be allowed to
return home once the car is removed, Armstrong said.
   Meanwhile, CSX Transportation Corp. conducted a drug test on the
train's engineer, but the results will not be available for several
weeks, said Tim Hensley, a spokesman for CSX. Hensley refused to
identify the engineer.
   The tanker was part of a CSX train that officials say was going
too fast through rural Christian County when 34 of its cars
derailed Wednesday night in a ravine near Crofton. The phosphorus
spilled from the ruptured tanker and burned for more than 12 hours
after the crash.
   Phosphorus inside the tanker reignited Thursday night as workers
righted it and although more toxic smoke billowed over the area,
there were few additional evacuations and no injuries, officials
said.
   The CSX engineer said he did not see a sign marking the section
of the track under a slow order and did not receive a computer
message about it, Hensley said. He said a warning marker was found,
but was not standing.
   ``Our position is ... he failed to receive and comply with a 10
mph slow order,'' Hensley said. ``Whether the fault was on his part
or our part, that really hasn't been determined.''
   He said the wreckage would be put through a battery of tests,
including chemical and X-ray analyses, to determine if there were
equipment or material failures. A tape located in the engineer's
quarters, as well as handling and operational procedures, will also
be reviewed, he said.
</TEXT>
