<1ST_LINE>r a PM-AppalachianHunger     06-25 0610</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Appalachian Hunger,0624</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Congressional Committee Investigates Hunger In Appalachia</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MARTHA BRYSON HODEL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MONTGOMERY, W.Va. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Poor mothers told a congressional
committee investigating hunger in Appalachia that their families
would not have enough food to live on if they didn't grow some of
it themselves.
   Two congressmen, committee staff members and reporters visited
homes of poor West Virginians on Friday before they listened to
experts tell why some people go without food.
   ``The problems (with poverty programs) all originate with the
notion that low-income people are deadbeats, lazy and shiftless
people. This is not true,'' said Milton Ogle, director of the
Appalachian Research and Defense Fund based in Charleston.
   Testifying before the U.S. House's Select Committee on Hunger,
Ogle said much of West Virginia's problem stems from the lack of
money to supplement federal programs. That's because much of the
state's wealth _ its surface land and mineral resources _ is
controlled by out-of-state corporations.
   ``The absentee holders of wealth display an arrogance based on
power that causes our state leaders to crumble and turn to mush,''
Ogle said. ``Thus, the burden of paying for public services falls
disproportionately on low- and moderate-income people.''
   The situation in West Virginia and other rural states appears to
be dire, said Rep. Mickey Leland, D-Texas.
   ``We have heard from mothers in West Virginia that they would
not be able to adequately feed their families if they didn't have
their gardens,'' said Leland, the committee chairman.
   ``For many residents of this state, the outlook for prosperity
in the near future is dismal. Most families don't even think about
how things look down the road because they are exhausting every
thread of energy confronting the day-to-day struggles of making
ends meet. But West Virginians are a proud people and they will
stretch themselves to the farthest limits to survive.''
   Earlier, the committee toured the homes of several residents to
learn how they manage to make ends meet when state and federal
programs are insufficient. Ocie Taylor, a 90-year-old resident of
Oak Hill, told the congressmen she cherishes her independence but
fears that it is threatened by her inability to make ends meet on
Social Security, a modest Veterans Administration pension and the
local Meals on Wheels program.
   ``When I get so I can't wait on myself, I hope the good Lord
takes me,'' Taylor said. ``They want me to come live with my
children, but I'd rather live in my own house.''
   Down the road in Robson, Gwendolyn Cole is having an even harder
time feeding herself and two children, her 3-year-old son and a
6-year-old girl she took in when the girl was abandoned by her
mother.
   Because the little girl's mother is reluctant to allow her to be
adopted, Cole _ who lives on $201 a month in welfare benefits and
$228 a month in food stamps _ has been unable to obtain medical
coverage for the child.
   ``What if she gets sick? I just pray that she don't,'' Cole said.
   Often, Cole's food stamps don't stretch nearly far enough. With
nearly a week remaining before she gets her next allotment of
stamps, she showed visitors a refrigerator virtually empty of
anything except some bread and bottles of water that she has
because her water pipes are broken.
   ``I was working, but now that I've got the kids I can't,'' said
the single mother. The nearest available day care center is in Oak
Hill, 20 miles away, and Cole has no transportation of her own.
   ``Whatever job I could get, I'd have to take the bus, and
getting the kids to day care would be hard,'' she said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
