<1ST_LINE>u i PM-Pope-Holocaust 1stLd-Writethru a0460 06-25 0632</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Pope-Holocaust, 1st Ld - Writethru, a0460,0650</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Papal Message: Christians Also Suffered Under Nazis</HEAD>
<HEAD>AP News Analysis</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: LEADS with 5 grafs to UPDATE with today's comments. PICKS up
4th graf, `In addition ...'</NOTE>
<HEAD>With PM-Pope, Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By KEVIN COSTELLOE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>VIENNA, Austria (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Pope John Paul II has been using his
Austrian visit to emphasize that Christians as well as Jews were
among the victims of Nazi persecution.
   Shortly after arriving in Austria on Thursday afternoon, the
pontiff began drawing attention to the non-Jews who suffered under
Nazi dictator Adolf Hitler.
   The pontiff did not mention Jews during his formal, televised
speech during a Friday afternoon visit to the site of the former
Mauthausen Nazi death camp, angering Austria's chief rabbi by the
omission.
   Today, the pontiff again brought up Christian suffering during a
prayer service in the town of Lorch, 25 miles from the Czech border.
   ``Not far from here is Mauthausen, where Christians, Jews and
others were persecuted for many reaons, including their religion,``
the pope said. ``Their suffering was a gift to the world.``
   In addition to killing six million Jews, the Nazis also killed
hundred of thousand of others, including gypsies, homosexuals,
priests and political opponents.
   On his five-day Austrian tour, the pope appeared to be trying to
make sure the memories of the other victims, especially Christians,
are not forgotten.
   ``Amongst the many who were persecuted for religious, racial and
political reasons were large numbers of Catholics _ priests,
members of religious orders and lay people,'' he told President
Kurt Waldheim and other Austrian politicians Thursday evening.
   John Paul also brought up the issue in a meeting with leaders of
Austria's Jewish community Friday morning as he talked about
inquiries into the causes of the Nazi dictatorship.
   The pope spoke of studies into the ``the Holocaust as well as
martyrdom of the Polish people and other European peoples during
the Nazi era.''
   Many of the Poles who were killed _ though not all _ were Jews.
   John Paul reminded the Jewish community leaders that the Nazi
machine was aimed not only at the Jewish people ``but also against
the faith of those who worship Jesus of Nazareth, a Jew, as the
savior of the world.''
   Then, in an emotional visit to the site of the former death camp
on Friday afternoon, the only victims he mentioned by name were
Polish priest St. Maximilian Kolbe, religious activist Marcel Callo
and two other Catholics.
   He also called attention to ``all people, especially those who,
when World War II was raging in Europe, suffered the torture of
such camps.''
   Austrian chief Rabbi Chaim Eisenberg responded to the Mauthausen
speech by saying: ``A visit to Mauthausen without mentioning the
word `Jews' once is not satisfactory.''
   ``The only Jew he mentions who suffered is Jesus Christ, and he
didn't die in Mauthausen,'' Eisenberg added.
   The pontiff's pronouncements come as some historians have been
promoting revised views of the Holocaust and Nazi atrocities.
   Conservative West German historians in particular are saying
that Nazi horrors should be compared with Stalinist-era mass
killings in the Soviet Union and similar atrocities by totalitarian
regimes.
   The historians' views have angered many Jews, who say they are
denigrating the memory of Jews who died in the Holocaust.
   It is not known whether the pope is versed in this historical
debate.
   However, after condemning the Nazi atrocities at Mauthausen,
John Paul used the phrase: ``Here ... and in so many places under
totalitarian rule.''
   Later in the speech, he added: ``If a machine of destruction
still exists anywhere in the world, tell us, what can our century
pass on to the generations to come?''
</TEXT>
<NOTE>EDITOR'S NOTE </NOTE>
<TEXT>
   Kevin Costelloe, Frankfurt news editor for The
Associated Press, has covered six papal trips in Europe.
</TEXT>
