<1ST_LINE>r a PM-WeatherpageWeather     06-25 0683</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Weatherpage Weather,0701</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Thunderstorms Blow Down Barns, Power Lines</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   A band of powerful thunderstorms sped eastward across part of
the drought-battered Midwest today after unleashing a tornado and
blowing down a barn as record heat cooked America from West Coast
to East.
   The storms pushing across parts of the eastern Dakotas and
Minnesota into northern Wisconsin and western Upper Michigan
prompted severe thunderstorm watches in the latter two states.
   Scattered showers and thunderstorms weakened from east Tennessee
to Georgia and northeast South Carolina, also suffering from the
drought, and widely scattered thunderstorms lingered over southern
Texas and western Louisiana.
   Scattered showers and thunderstorms extended from northern
California to Nevada and the southern Rockies and from south
central Montana to Wyoming and western Nebraska.
   On Friday, the storms triggered a tornado just southeast of
Claire City, S.D., downed power lines there and left eight-tenths
of an inch of rain.
   In Minnesota, strong winds blew down a barn in De Graff and
toppled trees in Roseau. Golf ball-size hail pounded Brainerd and
Ellendale, and smaller hail fell in or near other cities.
   In Georgia, thunderstorm winds blew part of a roof off a house
near Uvalda, knocked down a barn near Eastman, and downed power
lines south of Forsyth and trees in Ailey and west of Thomaston.
Three-fourths of an inch of rain fell in Albany in an hour.
   Showers and thunderstorms diminished Friday night across the
southern Plains, also seared by drought. In the late afternoon and
evening, 2{ inches of rain soaked Broken Bow, Okla., and nearly an
inch fell in Maud, Texas. Streets in and around Laredo, Texas,
flooded.
   Temperature records up to 87 years old were shattered or tied in
43 cities from Oregon to Florida, with the mercury over 100 degrees
in 25 of those cities.
   It was a sizzling 110 degrees in Valentine, Nev., torching the
record for the date of 99 degrees set in 1917 and tying the
all-time high. Other records included 109 degrees in Huron, S.D.,
(99, 1923); 101 in Minneapolis-St. Paul (99, 1952); and 103 in
Paducah, Ky. (99, 1952).
   Bullhead City, Ariz., had the nation's high with 114 degrees.
   Today's forecast called for scattered showers and thunderstorms
from southern Wisconsin to lower Michigan and the eastern Great
Lakes to much of New York and New England, with thunderstorms most
numerous near the Canadian border from New York to Maine; scattered
thunderstorms from Florida and Georgia to the lower Mississippi
Valley and much of Texas, with thunderstorms most numerous along
the central Gulf Coast and southeast Texas; and thunderstorms in
much of the Rockies and parts of California.
   High temperatures were forecast in the 90s to near 100 degrees
over most of the nation; near 105 degrees in parts of Illinois,
Missouri, Kansas, eastern Montana and Utah; near 115 degress in
parts of the desert Southwest; in the 70s and 80s from North
Carolina to New England, with some 60s in Maine and New Hampshire,
and from northern Michigan to Minnesota and in the Pacific
Northwest; and in the 60s and 70s along the Oregon and California
coasts.
   Temperatures around the nation at 3 a.m. EDT ranged from 50
degrees at Houlton and Limestone, Maine, and Atlantic City, N.J.,
to 96 degrees at Phoenix, Ariz.
   Other reports:
   _East: Atlanta 76 hazy; Boston 58 partly cloudy; Buffalo 66
cloudy; Charleston, S.C. 77 foggy; Cincinnati 74 fair; Cleveland 63
fair; Detroit 67 partly cloudy; Miami 78 partly cloudy; New York 61
fair; Philadelphia 59 fair; Pittsburgh 64 partly cloudy; Portland,
Maine 55 cloudy; Washington 65 fair.
   _Central: Bismarck 72 fair; Chicago 82 partly cloudy;
Dallas-Fort Worth 78 fair; Denver 71 fair; Des Moines 82 fair;
Indianapolis 81 cloudy; Kansas City 80 fair; Minneapolis-St. Paul
88 cloudy; Nashville 80 hazy; New Orleans 78 fair; St. Louis 86
fair.
   _West: Albuquerque 66 fair; Anchorage 57 cloudy; Las Vegas 94
partly cloudy; Los Angeles 66 partly cloudy; Phoenix 96 partly
cloudy; Salt Lake City 78 partly cloudy; San Diego 64 partly
cloudy; San Francisco 60 partly cloudy; Seattle 60 fair.
   _Canada: Toronto 61 partly cloudy.
</TEXT>
