<FILEID>AP-NR-06-25-88 0657EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i PM-FijiDeportation     06-25 0411</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Fiji Deportation,0423</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Fiji Deports New Zealand Lawyer For Chiefs, Alleged Gun Smugglers</HEAD>
<DATELINE>AUCKLAND, New Zealand (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A lawyer arrived home today after
he was expelled by Fiji as he tried to represent chiefs charged
with plotting to form a new government and other men accused of gun
smuggling.
   Attorney Christopher Harder, 39, was deported from the South
Pacific island of Fiji and flown to Auckland about 1,300 miles to
the south. He said he had been held by the Fijian military for
three days.
   He went to the archipelago to represent eight chiefs from the
island of Rotuma charged with plotting to break away from the
central government. Sources in Rotuma said men had plotted in May
to declare Rotuma's secession from Fiji, a British colony until
1970.
   Harder also intended to act as attorney for five men of Indian
descent charged after the discovery of Soviet-made weapons on Fiji
earlier this month.
   He said he had arrived Monday and attempted the next day to
arrange a meeting with Fijian military leader Lt. Col. Sitiveni
Rabuka. But his calls went unanswered, he said.
   On Wednesday morning, he said two plain-clothes security men
arrested him at his hotel and drove him to the army barracks. He
said he was not mistreated by authorities.
   Harder did not say whether he had been given an explanation for
his detention and deportation.
   However, he was arrested after he wrote a letter to the local
judiciary objecting to a new security decree that affected his
clients.
   The measures, imposed Wednesday, allow mandatory life
imprisonment for arms smuggling, detention without trial for up to
four years, sweeping powers of arrest and search, and restriction
of freedom of expression.
   New Zealand Prime Minister David Lange on Friday attacked the
measures, saying Fiji had become the South Pacific's first police
state.
   There has been unrest among the majority Indian population of
Fiji following two coups carried out last year by Rabuka, an ethnic
Fijian who said he intended to ensure the rights of his people.
   Ethnic Fijians are outnumbered by Indians in the 715,000
population of the island nation.
   The five men whom Harder wanted to represent are among 21
Fijians of Indian descent, some businessmen, charged after the
weapons _ including hand grenades, machine guns and missile
launchers _ were found. An Australian newspaper has reported that
the cache was part of a plan to overthrow Fiji's government by
shipping arms to its Indian community.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
