<1ST_LINE>r a PM-DriverJailed     06-25 0225</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Driver Jailed,0230</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Man Arrested 11 Times On DWI Charges Gets First Jail Sentence</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW ORLEANS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A man who has been arrested 11 times on
drunken driving charges since 1978 was sentenced to jail for the
first time _ for reckless driving.
   Traffic Court Judge Louis Trent on Thursday revoked Gary Roth's
probation from a reckless driving conviction on April 12 and
ordered him to serve 90 days in jail.
   Roth, 33, had been given a 90-day suspended sentence after the
city attorney's office agreed to allow him to plead guilty to a
reduced charge of reckless driving. He was arrested Feb. 2 on
charges of driving while intoxicated.
   Prosecutors said they did not take Roth to court on the earlier
DWI charge because Roth had refused to take any breath or field
sobriety tests, leaving prosecutors with insufficient evidence.
   Roth's lawyer had assured the court that his client would place
himself in an institution for drug rehabilitation as a condition of
the reckless driving conviction. But testimony Thursday indicated
Roth had failed to do so.
   Since 1978, Roth has been arrested 11 times for DWI but has been
convicted only once following a 1982 accident on the Seabrook
Bridge in which two people were injured.
   He also faces trial on DWI charges stemming from arrests on May
17 and June 6.
</TEXT>
