<2ND_LINE>PM-Angola, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0484,0440</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Southern Africa Peace Talks Resume With Wide Differences</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: LEADS thruout to UPDATE with talks resumed today, no pickup</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By DALIA BALIGH</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CAIRO, Egypt (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Delegates returned to U.S.-mediated talks
today in an effort to bridge deep differences over how to achieve
peace in southern Africa.
   The delegates from South Africa, Angola, Cuba and the United
States faced widely divergent proposals presented in Friday's
opening session, conference sources said.
   The participants are seeking a formula for ending a 13-year
civil war in Angola and ushering in independence to South-West
Africa, or Namibia.
   The leading Cairo newspaper Al-Ahram reported today that the
Cubans offered to withdraw their troops from Angola over four
years, but that the South Africans wanted a pullout in eight months.
   The South Africans and the joint Angolan-Cuban delegation
consulted separately Friday night with Chester Crocker, the U.S.
assistant secretary of state for African affairs. Crocker is acting
as mediator.
   In keeping with a news blackout imposed Friday, the sources said
nothing about whether Crocker's consultations brought the positions
closer for today's second and final day of negotiations. Two
previous rounds of peace talks, in London and Brazzaville, Congo,
failed to achieve settlements last month.
   The conference sources, who spoke on condition of anonymity,
said today's one-hour morning session was meant to enable the
opposing sides to reply formally to each other's proposals. The
delegates also agreed to hold an afternoon meeting.
   South African Foreign Minister R.F. ``Pik'' Botha told reporters
after the morning session: ``We had good, excellent talks.'' But
under the blackout, he and other delegates refused to discuss
substance.
   Botha told reporters Friday that his government was insisting on
Cuban troop withdrawal from Angola as a prerequisite for Namibian
independence.
   At the negotiating table on Friday, Botha demanded that Cuba set
a date for pulling out its more than 50,000 troops from Angola, the
conference sources said.
   South African sources have spoken of a reciprocal military
buildup near the border between Namibia and Angola, with the Cubans
deploying 15,000-17,000 troops and South Africa calling up reserves.
   Angola is demanding an end to South African military and
logistical support for Angolan rebels of UNITA, the National Union
for the Total Independence of Angola. UNITA, which has been
fighting the Marxist central government in Luanda, also obtains
arms from the United States.
   In 1978, the United Nations revoked South Africa's League of
Nations mandate in Namibia and called on the Pretoria government to
relinquish the territory. The resolution also provided that Namibia
be put under U.N. trusteeship pending independence.
</TEXT>
