<HEAD>Playwright-Actor Criticizes Society's Response To AIDS</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Outspoken playwright Harvey Fierstein says that
although he has lost many friends to AIDS, the epidemic has had
some positive fallout.
   ``First, no one can deny any more how many of us there are,''
said Fierstein in the August issue of Playboy. In addition, ``a lot
of gay people are being more supportive of one another than ever
before.''
   Fierstein, who won Tony awards for ``Torch Song Trilogy'' and
``La Cage Aux Folles,'' was scheduled to be among the speakers
today at the unfolding of the New York AIDS Memorial Quilt in
Central Park as part of Gay Pride Weekend.
   ``When you have AIDS, you don't simply have a disease like
cancer,'' Fierstein, a homosexual whose works deal with gay life,
said in the interview. ``To start with ... you're part of a media
event. When you have AIDS, you also have everything that comes with
it ... every nasty, filthy lie that is told about homosexuals.''
   Fierstein, who stars with Matthew Broderick and Anne Bancroft in
the movie version of ``Torch Song Trilogy,'' to be released this
year, said he would like to see more people talking about AIDS,
particularly leaders in the minority community, which also has been
hard hit.
   ``They're not out there educating,'' he said. ``They're very
happy to lay the problem on gays, because everybody knows we're
somebody to kick around.''
