<1ST_LINE>r a PM-AsbestosComplaint     06-25 0386</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Asbestos Complaint,0396</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>EPA: School Is First In Nation To Be Cited Under Asbestos Rules</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By LINDSEY TANNER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Workers chipping away at old floor tiles in the
hallway of a suburban high school sent clouds of dust containing
cancer-causing asbestos into the air, federal officials charged.
   The U.S. Environmental Protection Agency lodged a complaint and
proposed a $5,000 fine against Thornton Township High School in
Harvey, a spokeswoman said Friday. It is the first complaint the
EPA has brought under new asbestos-safety rules that went into
effect in December.
   The complaint says students and other school personnel were
exposed to asbestos fibers during the improper removal of 6,400
square feet of hallway flooring.
   ``We had received several calls from teachers and students and
actually the workers in the school that the tile was being removed
in the hallway and clouds of dust were being raised, and they were
very concerned about it,'' said EPA spokeswoman Nancy Sullivan.
   School officials have until July 11 to respond to the complaint,
which names Thornton High School District 205. The school was
closed Friday afternoon, and officials could not be reached for
comment.
   The violations were discovered during an EPA inspection March 1,
and the school immediately discontinued the flooring removal
project at the agency's request, the EPA said.
   Asbestos, a mineral that has been used in building materials,
can cause lung cancer and other disorders when airborne fibers
enter the body.
   When the tile was removed in February, school officials did not
initially know that it contained asbestos, Ms. Sullivan said.
Later, officials had the tile tested and the presence of asbestos
was confirmed, she said.
   Workers who were not accredited by the government to remove
asbestos ``had sanded, chipped and cut the tiles, releasing clouds
of dust containing asbestos,'' the EPA said in a news release.
   The complaint against Thornton is the EPA's first enforcement
action nationwide under the Asbestos Hazard Emergency Response Act,
the agency said.
   Under the law, which took effect Dec. 14, specific safety
measures must be taken when removing asbestos from elementary and
secondary schools.
   If they decide to contest the complaint, school officials can
seek an informal hearing with EPA officials in Chicago or request a
hearing before a federal administrative law judge, Ms. Sullivan
said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
