<HEAD>13 Killed, 4 Wounded In Hotel Bombing</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: EDITS throughout to UPDATE with 13 killed, other detail and
background; no pickup</NOTE>
<DATELINE>PESHAWAR, Pakistan (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A bomb ripped apart a three-story
hotel in the center of the old city, killing 13 people and wounding
four others, police said.
   Police said four of the dead were Afghan nationals.
   Abdul Ahmed Khan, assistant inspector of crimes, said the blast
was set off by an 11-pound explosive device. It tore through the
second and third floors of the hotel after sunrise, as Moslems were
finishing their morning prayers.
   The hotel ``collapsed just like a sandwich,'' Khan said.
   He said two people died on the way to the hospital after
surviving nine hours beneath the rubble.
   Among the dead were an Afghan woman and her 3-year-old child who
had come to Peshawar for medical treatment, according to Omar Amer,
a Pakistani journalist.
   There was no immediate claim of responsibility for the blast,
but police said they suspected agents of Afghanistan's communist
government.
   ``Previously, they have committed all these things,'' Khan said,
referring to dozens of terrorist bombings over the past two years
in Pakistan. Hundreds of Pakistanis and Afghan refugees have died
in the blasts.
   Pakistan backs Moslem insurgents fighting the Afghan government,
which is backed by Soviet forces who are withdrawing after an
eight-year involvement in Afghanistan's civil war. Peshawar, 30
miles from the Afghan border, is headquarters of the seven-party
guerrilla alliance.
   On Friday, small explosive devices went off outside the
headquarters of two of the rebel groups but there were no serious
injuries, Khan said.
   Until Friday, Khan said, Peshawar had been enjoying a respite
from terrorist bombings, which had become almost a weekly occurence
prior to the signing of the April 14 Geneva accord on the Soviet
withdrawal.
</TEXT>
