<HEAD>Amnesiac Arraigned On Murder Charges, Remembers Identity</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEWPORT, R.I. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A man claiming to suffer from amnesia, who
was arrested on murder charges after a newspaper publicized his
plight, now says he remembers his real name.
   ``I am Mr. Peabody. I remembered,'' Robert Peabody said outside
a New Bedford, Mass., courtroom Thursday after he was turned over
to Newport detectives for transfer to Rhode Island.
   When asked when he remembered his real name and how much else he
recalled, Peabody said, ``I don't have any other comment.'' His
attorney, John Coyne, also wouldn't comment.
   Peabody was arraigned in Newport District Court on Friday in
connection with the death last month of William Capuano, 34, in a
Newport inn where both men had been staying. Judge Paul Del Nero
ordered Peabody held until a July 5 bail hearing.
   Peabody was found at a highway rest stop near Bourne, Mass., May
30 with razor cuts on his arm. He gave his name as Robert
Christopher Anderson, told of being born in California in 1944 but
said he didn't remember his more recent past.
   A story about ``Anderson'' published in the New Bedford
Standard-Times on June 18 led police to investigate and resulted in
Peabody's arrest Wednesday.
   Capuano's bullet-ridden body was found wrapped in green garbage
bags in Peabody's room at a Newport inn May 31. Police said he had
been dead at least 24 hours.
   Police issued a warrant for Peabody's arrest soon afterward but
didn't realize he was the man found in Massachusetts until seeing
the news story and photograph.
   Peabody told the newspaper that he was born July 5, 1944, in
Fairfield, Calif., putting his age at 43. Police say he is 49 and
has lived in the Newport area most of his life.
