<HEAD>Pope Says Suffering Under Nazis A Gift To The World</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: LEADS with 11 grafs to move up reference to pope mentioning
Jewish victims of Nazis and to recast; picks up 7th graf pvs, ``The
church ... '' EDITS thereafter to trim and to CORRECT spelling of
Novarro throughout</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By VICTOR L. SIMPSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LORCH, Austria (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Pope John Paul II today paid tribute to
Jewish and other victims of Austria's most notorious Nazi
concentration camp, saying ``their suffering was a gift to the
world.''
   The Roman Catholic leader spoke after Jewish leaders criticized
his formal speech the day before during a visit to the site of the
former Mauthausen camp, where thousands of Jews were among the
110,000 inmates who perished. The speech omitted any specific
reference to Jews.
   The criticism prompted Vatican spokesman Joaquin Navarro to tell
reporters today that the pontiff had no intention of slighting the
Jews. Navarro said the pontiff mentioned the Jews who died at
Mauthausen during a brief stop at a memorial plaque set up in their
memory.
   John Paul spoke before 80,000 people today in the town of Lorch,
just 25 miles from the Czechoslovak border, on the third day of his
visit to Austria.
   ``Not far from here is Mauthausen, where Christians, Jews and
others were persecuted for many reasons, including their
religion,'' the pope said, referring to his visit to the
concentration camp site.
   He continued: ``Their suffering was a gift to the world.''
   John Paul has been using the current, five-day Austria trip to
discuss various aspects of the Nazi past. The country is marking
the 50th anniversary year of its annexation by Nazi Germany in 1938.
   After his arrival Thursday, the pontiff, despite protests of
some Jewish leaders, met with controversial President Kurt
Waldheim. The Austrian president has faced allegations of
complicity in Nazi war crimes but has denied wrongdoing.
   On Friday, Waldheim received Holy Communion from the pontiff
during an outdoor Mass for 80,000 people in the town of Trausdorf
near the border with Hungary.
   In Lorch, John Paul also addressed the concerns of workers and
farmers in the area. Many of the farmers in the far northern region
are having trouble staying in business, often forced to take second
jobs to make ends meet.
   ``The church stands by you when you have social and economic
problems,'' the white-robed pontiff said during the outdoor prayer
service.
   John Paul frequently has called for respect for workers' rights
and warned about the potential dangers of unbridled,
profit-motivated capitalism.
   The Polish-born pontiff set off a wave of Jewish protest Friday
when he failed to mention Jews during the Mauthausen speech.
   ``The failure of Pope John Paul to make any specific reference
to the suffering of the Jews while visiting the site of the
infamous Mauthausen concentration camp is a matter of deep shock to
the Jewish community,'' said World Jewish Congress executive
director Elan Steinberg.
   ``This, together with the pope's unwillingness to confront Kurt
Waldheim over his Nazi past or address the historical complicity of
Austria in the crimes of Hitler's Germany, are failures that
constitute a tragic lost moral opportunity,'' Steinberg added in a
statement from New York.
   Also faulting the pontiff on Friday was Austria's chief rabbi
Chaim Eisenberg, who leads the country's 12,000 Jews.
   On Friday while at Mauthausen, the pontiff cited only four
concentration camp victims by name, all of them Catholics. However,
he stopped in silence for nearly a minute at a plaque set up in
memory of the Jewish victims.
   Navarro said the pope, standing beside a camp survivor in front
of the plaque, spoke of the Jews and said ``never again'' three
times.
   Navarro said the survivor was supposed to have been wearing a
tiny microphone so that the pope's words could have been heard but
that for some reason officials had removed the device.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
