<1ST_LINE>r i PM-Yugoslavia-Jobs     06-25 0162</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Yugoslavia-Jobs,0168</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Official Says About One_Third Of Labor Force May Lose Jobs</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BELGRADE, Yugoslavia (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Almost one-third of Yugoslavia's
labor force may lose their jobs as a result of the government's
economic austerity program, a trade union leader was quoted as
saying today.
   Dusan Koceljevic made the statement during a session of a
government commission which is preparing economic reforms, the
Belgrade daily Politika reported.
   The government earlier this month began an economic austerity
program to ease Yugoslavia's 170 percent inflation rate and its $21
billion foreign and to steer the country toward a more open market.
   The government also linked wages and employment to the currently
low industrial productivity. As a result, wage cuts of up to 30
percent have been enforced under the new measure.
   ``Because of the restructuring of the economy, 2 million workers
will lose their jobs,'' Koceljevic was quoted as saying.
   About 1.1 million Yugoslavs are unemployed, out of a labor force
of 6.6 million.
