<1ST_LINE>r i PM-Lebanon-Hostages     06-25 0433</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Lebanon-Hostages,0446</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Report: British Hostages To Be Freed Before U.S. Election</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MOHAMMED SALAM</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BEIRUT, Lebanon (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A Beirut magazine reported today that the
Iranian government hopes to influence the U.S. presidential
elections by releasing British hostages close to the Nov. 8 vote.
   The weekly Ash-Shiraa reported that the agreement to release the
hostages emerged during a three-day unofficial visit by four
British legislators to Iran that ended Wednesday.
   ``Reliable Moslem fundamentalist circles have confirmed that
British-Iranian negotiations to free British hostages held in
Lebanon will result (in their release) on the eve of the American
presidential elections,'' the report said.
   The magazine gained international fame when it broke the story
of secret U.S. arms sales to Iran in return for releasing American
hostages in 1986. The magazine's more recent reports on hostage
developments have proved inaccurate.
   The four British legislators returned to London Wednesday saying
Iranian officials offered to use their influence to release the
three British captives in Lebanon.
   Ash-Shiraa said the ``Iranian leadersip was seeking to postpone
the release until late summer so that it will be the biggest voter
in the coming American presidential elections.''
   Ash-Shiraa said the Iranian move of postponing the release
``aims at besieging and embarrassing the official American stand
(of the Reagan administration)'' for failing to obtain the release
of American hostages.
   The United States and Britain had agreed not to negotiate for
the hostages' release. However, France ``negotiated with Iran for
the release of French hostages and that was achieved'' the report
said.
   French diplomats Marcel Fontaine and Marcel Carton as well as
journalist Jean-Paul Kauffmann were released in Beirut May 4.
   Britain's foreign secretary, Sir Geoffrey Howe, on Thursday
denied that Britain was negotiating for the release of Anglican
Church envoy Terry Waite, journalist John McCarthy and teacher
Brian Keenan.
   No group has claimed responsibility for abducting Waite and
McCarthy, although they are widely believed held by fanatic Shiite
Moslem kidnappers affiliated with the Iranian-backed Hezbollah, or
Party of God.
   The magazine report compared the anticipated release to that of
of 52 Americans held hostage in the U.S. embassy in Tehran for 444
days. They were released on inauguration day as president Jimmy
Carter left office.
   ``The aim of the delay was to bring Carter down and the hostages
were only released after a new president (President Reagan) took
over'' the magazine article concluded.
   In all, 18 foreigners are missing and believed kidnapped in
Lebanon, including nine Americans. The longest held is Terry
Anderson, chief Middle East correspondent for The Associated Press.
He was kidnapped March 16, 1985.
 
</TEXT>
