<1ST_LINE>u i PM-Landslide 2ndLd-Writethru   06-25 0653</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Landslide, 2nd Ld - Writethru,a0510,0670</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Rescuers Resume Search With Little Hope of Finding Survivors</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: SUBS 8th graf pvs, ``Three West ...'' to UPDATE number of
missing; picks up 9th graf pvs: Trabzon gov....</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By VEDAT ERDAMAR</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CATAK, Turkey (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Rescue workers aided by search dogs fanned
out over this rain-soaked village today, trying to unearth about
100 people buried by a landslide. Officials said there was little
chance of finding survivors.
   ``I am nearly sure that no one will come out alive,'' said
Wolfgang Krctschemer, head of a 32-member West German volunteer
team from the Rescue Dog Association.
   ``There's very little space for air pockets here, between the
soft earth and the rocks, where someone trapped could breathe. But
we have to go on looking,'' added Klaus Kolter, another member of
the German team.
   Rescue efforts resumed at sunrise today. The search had been
called off during the night after geologists and engineers spotted
cracks in the mountain that could trigger another devastating slide.
   Krctschemer said the rescue workers had located the spot where
the landslide had buried a coffeehouse crowded with breakfast-time
customers on Thursday.
   He said they were trying to reach the coffeehouse by digging
holes from two sides. He said rescuers should be able to unearth
some bodies from the site later in the day.
   Villagers said about 30 travelers were in the restaurant at the
time of the disaster and dozens more were at the roadside waiting
for bulldozers to clear the highway after an earlier rockfall.
   Three West German tourists and 41 Turks were listed as missing.
There were also unconfirmed reports by witnesses that two British
tourists had been in the coffeehouse, but it could not be
determined whether they had been buried in the landslide or had
left before the disaster.
   Trabzon Gov. Enver Hizlan said there probably would be delay in
listing other names because the people involved were in transit.
   Rescue efforts were hindered by new slides that swept clouds of
dust into the air and sent giant boulders hurtling down the wooded
mountainside. A Turkish truck driver and a villager were injured in
separate rockfalls on Friday.
   Another landslide hit an area about three miles away from Catak
today, closing the main highway. No injuries were reported.
   Grieving relatives watched the rescue works, occasionally
kneeling over a hole and looking down with empty eyes.
   ``Do you think anyone can come out alive from there?'' asked
Necati Himtas, whose 20-year-old son was missing.
   A woman wailing and weeping was taken to the mobile hospital
when she fainted.
   Catak, home to 1,000 people, is situated 19 miles from the Black
Sea port of Trabzon on a main highway leading to eastern Anatolia
and Iran.
   The two-lane highway was widened three years ago to handle
increasing truck and tourist traffic, but vilagers said it was not
buttressed properly.
   ``The retaining walls weren't big enough and we started having
landslides, not big ones but enough to block the road,'' said Riza
Yavuz, the village headman.
   Yavuz said the coffeehouse owner had told public works officials
earlier this month that the hillside needed more support or it
would collapse.
   Erkan Omarbeyoglou, Turkey's director of highways, warned that
new cracks had appeared on the same stretch of mountainside,
suggesting another section could be dislodged.
   ``There's a risk that an entire hilltop could come crashing down
in the same area,'' Omarbeyoglou said. He said rescue workers would
have enough warning to evacuate the area.
   The landslide Thursday also destroyed a restaurant, 20 homes and
a high school closed for summer vacation. A stream burst its banks
and flooded another part of the village, including several houses.
   ``I saw a telegraph pole slowly bending over,'' said Gaby
Engler, a 28-year-old West German nurse, who witnessed the slide.
``I heard a noise like an explosion and the whole hillside came
away in front of me.''
</TEXT>
