<1ST_LINE>r i PM-SouthAfrica-Bomb 1stLd-Writethru   06-25 0221</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-South Africa-Bomb, 1st Ld-Writethru,a0503,0226</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Bomb Shatters Restaurant After Patrons Evacuated</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: LEADS throughout to UPDATE with police confirming type of
bomb, other detail; no pickup</NOTE>
<DATELINE>EAST LONDON, South Africa (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A waitress at a beachfront
restaurant today spotted a bomb and led scores of patrons to safety
moments before the device exploded, police said.
   The explosion occurred shortly after midnight at the Papagallo
restaurant on East London's seaside esplanade.
   The bomb, a Soviet-made limpet mine, was discovered by a
waitress who alerted the manager, police said. Police arrived,
evacuated about 90 diners and were in the process of evacuating
people from neighboring hotels when the bomb exploded, less than 20
minutes after it had been seen.
   ``It was a close shave,'' said Maj. Trevor Hayes, a police
spokesman.
   The interior of the restaurant was extensively damaged. No
injuries or arrests were reported.
   There have been more than 20 bombings in South Africa this year,
and police have blamed the outlawed African National Congress
guerrilla movement.
   The group has neither claimed nor denied responsibility for
specific recent bombings but has said it seeks to intensify its
attacks.
   The guerrillas are fighting the South Africa government and its
system of apartheid, which does not permit the 26 million black
majority to vote and racially segregates schools, districts and
health services.
</TEXT>
