<2ND_LINE>PM-Berlin Violence,0234</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Protesters Battle Police Over Land Near Berlin Wall</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BERLIN (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Protesters hurled stones at West Berlin police
early today during a clash over a disputed piece of land near the
Berlin Wall, authorities said. Police used tear gas and water
canons to break up the demonstration.
   Police said one officer was injured when he was struck in the
head by a rock.
   The so-called ``Lenne Triangle'' _ about 10 acres of land
adjacent to the Berlin Wall _ has been the scene of frequent
skirmishes between police and environmental activists, who occupied
the area on May 26 to protest plans for construction of a road
through the area.
   The activists are against the road project because it would go
through a wooded area.
   The property, which 150 protesters continue to occupy, currently
belongs to East Berlin, but will be turned over to West Berlin in
July.
   West Berlin police, who cannot legally enter the property, have
fenced it in to keep more protesters from entering. The activists
tried to tear down the barrier, but police drove them back.
   Police said todays clash began after protesters attacked
officers with stones, bottles, Molotov cocktails and flares.
   East German border troops observed the incident from nearby
guard towers along the heavily-fortified wall that divides the
city, which is surrounded by East German territory.
</TEXT>
