<1ST_LINE>r i PM-SoccerViolence     06-25 0170</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Soccer Violence,0174</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Fourteen Soccer Fans Arrested In Munich Violence</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MUNICH, West Germany (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Police today arrested 14 soccer fans
during violent clashes in downtown Munich before the final of the
European soccer championships, which will pit The Netherlands
against the Soviet Union.
   A Munich police spokesman, who asked not to be identified, said
most of the fans arrested were Dutch. He said a Swiss man and
several West Germans were also in custody after incidents earlier
today.
   Police said those arrested face charges of assault, theft,
resisting arrest and destruction of property.
   Before the clashes, the fans had been drinking heavily in the
city's beer garden district, police said.
   A capacity crowd of 72,000, including 20,000 Dutch fans, is
expected for Saturday's championship game. More than 3,500 police
officers are on duty to try to prevent fan violence.
   A total of more than 800 fans have been arrested as a result of
violence that erupted in many West German cities since the
championship series began June 10.
</TEXT>
