<1ST_LINE>r w AM-DefenseProbe-Hudson     06-25 0641</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Defense Probe-Hudson,630</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Top Pentagon Fraud Prosecutor Made His Name Fighting Pornography</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Defense Probe Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By SUSANNE M. SCHAFER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Henry E. Hudson, the U.S. attorney overseeing
the Pentagon fraud probe, made his name fighting pornography, not
corruption. He is known as ``an aggressive sort of guy'' who isn't
averse to publicity.
   At 41, Hudson is looking at perhaps his biggest case, the
investigation into allegations that defense contractors and
consultants bribed Pentagon officials for information to help win
billions of dollars in contracts.
   He prides himself on ``quality prosecutions, and being firm and
fair.'' Others say he is a dogged prosecutor, almost moralistic in
his zeal.
   Hudson is the top federal attorney in northern Virginia, where
the Pentagon is located and where many of the consultants and
contractors being investigated have offices.
   Although there is a special unit in the Justice Department that
tracks down fraud, it appears that the case went to Hudson because
it was too massive for the Justice unit to handle. Also, the unit's
offices were located in northern Virginia, within Hudson's
jurisdiction.
   Just across the Potomac River from the Capitol, the district
traditionally has been a high-profile one for a U.S. attorney
prosecuting federal cases. Hudson and his assistant, Joe Aronica,
will argue the cases for the government if any charges come to
trial.
   ``There's a certain amount of prestige that comes with the turf.
But Henry is an aggressive sort of guy,'' said Robert F. Horan, the
state attorney for Fairfax County in northern Virginia, in an
interview with the Fairfax Journal.
   Hudson took over the federal prosecutor's job in 1986 and
pledged to improve the office's reputed organization problems and
to put a greater emphasis on cases of national significance.
   As a Virginia state prosecutor, he'd earned the reputation of a
``policeman's prosecutor'' with his crackdowns on massage parlors
and adult bookstores, and his efforts to reduce plea bargains and
increase jail sentences.
   Hudson entered the national spotlight two years ago when
Attorney General Edwin Meese III made him chairman of his
pornography commission.
   The panel drew derision from civil liberties groups, as well as
rave reviews from anti-pornography crusaders, with its 1986 report
that asserted that sex crimes can be linked to hard-core
pornography. The panel's stance represented an about-face from the
conclusion of another government commission in 1970 that there was
no evidence of harm from pornography.
   Among other things, Hudson's panel recommended that Congress
force pornography traffickers to forfeit their profits, and that
video pornography producers be prosecuted for prostitution. A
second conviction under obscenity laws would become a felony
guaranteeing at least a year behind bars.
   Hudson argued at the time that the panel should have taken even
more drastic steps.
   ``I would have preferred that our condemnation of materials
directly affecting behavior be couched in more forceful language,
and that our recommendations for enhanced law enforcement,
particularly with respect to violent and degrading materials, be
likewise more pronounced,'' Hudson wrote.
   The American Civil Liberties Union lambasted the panel as
biased, unfair and its arguments ``intellectually indefensible.''
It accused Hudson of advocating ``extreme measures'' while paying
little attention to privacy and First Amendment rights.
   One member of the panel, Ellen Levine, said in an interview this
past week that even though she strongly disagreed with some of
Hudson's opinions, she thinks he'll ``do as as good a job as he can
possibly do'' with the Pentagon probe.
   ``He has a very dogged personality and a very strong sense of
right and wrong,'' said Ms. Levine, editor in chief of Woman's Day
magazine.
   She said that she did not put much stock in reports that the
attorney was a man who loved being in the headlines. ``He was a
very moral man, if not moralistic, and he'll do his duty,'' Ms.
Levine said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
