<1ST_LINE>u i PM-Iran-Iraq 4thLd-Writethru   06-25 0539</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Iran-Iraq, 4th Ld - Writethru,a0509,0551</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Iraq Says Its Forces Capture Islands</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Recasts throughout to CORRECT spelling of islands to Majnoon,
sted Majnoun</NOTE>
<DATELINE>BAGHDAD, Iraq (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Iraqi army said today it recaptured the
Majnoon islands in another offensive against Iranian positions
inside Iraq. Iran reported heavy fighting in the area.
   A war communique read over Baghdad Radio said the series of
islands located in the Hawayza marshes near the Iranian border was
completely liberated at noon (4 a.m. EDT).
   The report said the elite Presidential Guards took the islands
while troops from the 3rd army corps ``pushed forward to crush the
enemy and its defenses and guns on lands opposite the islands.''
   Iran has occupied the area, located northeast of Basra and about
270 miles southeast of the capital of Baghdad, since 1984.
   The area lies near the border with Iran, and it was unclear
whether Iraqi forces had pushed into Iranian territory. Iraq, in
seeking a cease-fire in the war, has said its troops would not
enter Iran.
   ``Our forces started their advance at 3:45 a.m. toward Majnoon
Island and its surroundings,'' the official Iraqi news agency said
earlier, quoting a communique from the general command of the Iraqi
armed forces.
   ``The resistance of the enemy deteriorated and collapsed due to
the Iraqi heavy fire,'' added the Iraqi report.
   Iran's Islamic Republic news agency accused Iraq of using
chemical weapons in the attack and said heavy fighting was going on
in the swampland.
   The IRNA report, also monitored in Nicosia, said ``substantial
losses and damage have been inflicted on the Iraqi forces and a
number of them have been captured. Heavy fighting reportedlly
continues in the region.''
   The INA dispatch called the operation, codenamed ``Trust in
God,'' the second phase of the Iraqi push to liberate areas
occupied by Iran along the southern border east of Basra.
   The dispatch compared the battle to the April 16 assault on the
Faw peninsula, which ended two years of Iranian occupation in that
area.
   The nearly 8-year-old war had reached a stalemate before the
Iraqis seized the initiative with their lightening assault on Faw.
   The Iraqi's sudden switch from years of static warfare from
behind their formidable defense lines to aggressive attacking
techniques caught the Iranians off guard.
   In May, the Iraqis struck again, driving the Iranians out of the
bridgehead around Salamchah, also east of Basra, in a 10-hour
battle.
   The latest battle was an assault on Mehran last week by the
National Liberation Army of Iran, a group of Iranian rebels backed
by the government of Iraqi President Saddam Hussein.
   Iran claimed the capture of the border city was the work of
regular Iraqi troops, but both Iraq and the Iranian insurgents
denied the claim. The rebel army, following its usual pattern of
inflicting as much damage on the forces of the Ayatollah Ruhollah
Khomeini and then withdrawing, said its forces pulled back across
the Iraqi border on Wednesday.
   The attack on Mehran, 90 miles east of Baghdad, might have been
a diversion to draw Iranian forces away from the southern front
around Majnoon island in preparation for the new Iraqi assault,
according to a Perisan Gulf war analyst who spoke on condition of
anonymity.
</TEXT>
