<1ST_LINE>r w AM-Bakke-Statistics     06-25 0216</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Bakke-Statistics,200</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Minority Enrollment In Medical Schools Rose After Bakke, Study
Says</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Bakke Anniversary Bjt</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   In the decade since a Supreme Court decision
in the Allan Bakke case ended the use of enrollment quotas, the
number of minority students admitted to medical school actually
increased in the United States, according to the Association of
American Medical Colleges.
   Robert G. Petersdorf, president of the association, said that in
1978 it was feared that the Bakke decision, which forbids the use
of special consideration in the admission of minorities, would
cause medical schools to enroll even fewer minorities than before.
   ``The opposite proved to be true,'' Petersdorf said.
   In the first enrollment period after the Bakke decision, 40.9
percent of the minority students who applied to medical schools
were admitted, and minority enrollees composed 8.7 percent of
first-year medical school classes.
   Ten years later, Petersdorf said, the medical schools are
admitting 51.7 percent of the minority applicants and they now
represent 10.2 percent of the entering classes.
   ``The Supreme Court decision actually encouraged affirmative
action goals by allowing the use of race and other determinants in
addition to academic achievement as acceptable admissions
criteria,'' Petersdorf said.
   He said that medical schools began affirmative action steps in
1970 and the Bakke decision ``reaffirmed'' them.
</TEXT>
