<1ST_LINE>r w AM-Bentsen-Banks     06-25 0473</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Bentsen-Banks,480</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Bentsen Says Feds Favoring New York Banks</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JENNIFER DIXON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Federal regulators give New York money centers
with troubled overseas loans more leeway than Texas banks hobbled
by declines in oil prices and a deflated real estate market, Sen.
Lloyd Bentsen, a Texas Democrat and chairman of the Senate Finance
Committee, said Saturday.
   ``The result is that domestic borrowers have greater difficulty
acquiring credit than borrowers like Poland,'' Bentsen said in a
letter urging the chiefs of the Federal Reserve Board, Federal
Deposit Insurance Corp., and the comptroller of the currency to
review their regulatory practices.
   Bentsen said recent data indicate banks must set aside greater
reserves against domestic troubled loans than against troubled
loans to Third World and Eastern Bloc nations.
   ``This favorable treatment by regulators of troubled foreign
loans over domestic loans will crimp credit to domestic
borrowers,'' Bentsen wrote Federal Reserve Chairman Alan Greenspan,
FDIC Chairman L. William Seidman, and Robert L. Clarke, comptroller
of the currency.
   ``This is particularly important to areas like Texas whose banks
hold a disproportionate share of troubled domestic loans,'' wrote
Bentsen. As the state attempts to rebuild its economy, it needs a
``robust and healthy banking system able to provide needed credit
to worthy borrowers ranking from small businesses to ranchers and
farmers.''
   FDIC spokesman Alan Whitney said he and Seidman had not seen the
letter and could not comment on it. But he said regulators were not
being any more stringent on Texas banks than those elsewhere in the
country.
   Rates for reserves set aside for foreign loans depend on a
variety of factors, including the country, the loan and the bank,
Whitney said.
   Lee Cross, an aide to Clarke, said the comptroller shared
Bentsen's concerns about the problems in the Texas economy and
Texas banks, but he wanted to see the figures on which the
senator's letter was based before commenting further.
   Bentsen said FDIC data indicate that an amount comparable to 51
percent of non-performing domestic loans is being held as loan loss
reserves. But calculations by the Joint Economic Committee of
Congress suggest that ``considerably smaller reserves _ only 24
percent _ are being set aside against troubled loans by banks to
Third World and Eastern Bloc nations,'' he wrote.
   ``I think this is unfair and unequal treatment,'' said Bentsen.
``I would much rather have a loan collateralized by an empty
building in Texas than to depend on the commitments of a foreign
communist country like Poland.''
   Bentsen said he was drafting legislation to correct ``that kind
of slanted treatment, favoring the big money banks in New York,
compared to Texas banks.''
   ``It really hurts not just the banks in Texas, but the borrowers
too, because we don't have sufficient capital _ that means for
small businesses, medium-sized businesses,'' Bentsen said.
</TEXT>
