<1ST_LINE>r i AM-CentralBank     06-25 0782</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Central Bank,0803</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Support Growing For European `Federal Reserve' Bank</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ROBERT BURNS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BRUSSELS, Belgium (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Creation of a West European central
bank, an idea that gained little currency in the past, is quietly
emerging as a long-range priority of the 12-nation European
Economic Community.
   The prospect of establishing a U.S. Federal Reserve-style
central bank for Western Europe is expected to be a major topic of
discussion at an EEC summit conference starting June 27 in Hanover,
West Germany.
   But decisions to take the first concrete steps toward a
``Eurobank'' to manage a common monetary policy are not likely in
Hanover, analysts say. Many other related questions, such as
harmonizing tax policies in the Common Market, probably will have
to be settled first.
   Norbert Walter, senior economist at Deutsche Bank in Frankfurt,
says establishment of a central bank for Europe probably is still
``a long way off.''
   Some EEC members, such as Britain, don't like the idea. They
think it would force them to surrender too much national control.
   Prime Minister Margaret Thatcher has not even heeded her EEC
partners' urgings to include Britain in the European Monetary
System, which was created in 1979 to keep European currency values
stable.
   Yet talk of a European currency union is becoming more serious
than just a year ago, when the idea _ which has been discussed off
and on for more than two decades _ was generally dismissed as a
pipe dream.
   ``It is not just utopia, it is not nirvana. It is something that
can be accepted in the Europe of today,'' Walter said in a
telephone interview.
   Many European leaders have come to believe that the EEC's plan
for creating a true common market by 1992 _ one that allows goods,
people and money to freely cross national borders _ increases the
need for a European central bank to cope with less rigid capital
markets.
   This feeling has been reinforced by a June 13 agreement by
European finance ministers to remove national controls on capital
movements by July 1990 in the eight most advanced EEC countries.
The agreement excludes the four countries that have joined the EEC
since 1973 _ Spain, Ireland, Greece and Portugal.
   Spain and Ireland were given a deadline of 1992; Greece and
Portugal have until 1995.
   Gerhard Stoltenberg, the West German finance minister, hailed
the accord as ``a milestone of great importance'' on the path to
unifying the European market and increasing the EEC's global
competitiveness.
   At the Hanover summit, West German Chancellor Helmut Kohl is
expected to propose that a special panel of central bank officials
and other experts from EEC countries be set up to study the central
bank issue.
   ``This is a topic that is clearly gaining pace,'' said Richard
Reid, senior European economist at the London-based investment firm
Philips and Drew.
   The eventual structure of a European central bank is far from
clear, but one idea is to model it after the U.S. Federal Reserve,
with regional representatives and independently appointed governors.
   Kohl is a strong supporter of establishing a true European
monetary union, with a central bank as the linchpin, but the
independent Bundesbank, or German central bank, has been cool to
the idea.
   ``The vision of a European union is most certainly closely bound
with that of a European currency union,'' Kohl told a recent
Frankfurt conference.
   Even though one of the original aims of the EEC was to create an
economic and monetary union, all the member nations still have
their own currencies and set their own policies on interest rates
and money supply.
   An embryonic regional currency, known as the European currency
unit, or Ecu, has been in use since 1979, but mainly as an
accounting device. The Ecu does not exist as a hard currency in
bank notes or coins, except for a special issue of Ecu coins last
year by Belgium to commemorate the 30th anniversary of the founding
of the EEC.
   The Ecu is based on an average of Common Market currencies and
currently is worth about $1.20.
   A European central bank would, in the vision held by many
supporters of an EEC monetary union, be the manager of the Ecu _
much as the Federal Reserve manages the dollar _ by influencing
interest rate levels and controlling the supply of money in the
economy.
   One of the main questions to be settled is whether a European
monetary authority could co-exist with national central banks or
whether it would replace them.
   If this and other complex issues are resolved, European economic
integration will have advanced much further than even the most
ardent European unionists would have believed possible in the early
1980s.
</TEXT>
