<DOCNO> AP880625-0115 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-06-25-88 1234EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a AM-ContraSuit     06-25 0678</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Contra Suit,0697</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Judge Stops Intriguing, Expensive Suit</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RICHARD COLE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MIAMI (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A judge's decision to throw out a $24 million
lawsuit that mixed the CIA, Contras and the Medellin cocaine cartel
has left lingering questions, charges of politics, big bills and
little doubt that litigation will continue.
   Chief U.S. District Judge James Lawrence King ruled Thursday
that the two journalists who filed the suit failed to prove their
allegations that the 29 defendants conspired in a guns-for-drugs
scheme or a 1984 terrorist bombing in Nicaragua.
   The defendants included Iran-Contra figures Richard Secord and
Albert Hakim, Contra leader Adolfo Calero, former CIA deputy
director of operations Theodore Shackley, and retired major general
and anti-communist crusader John K. Singlaub.
   The suit was filed in May 1986, six months before the
Iran-Contra affair became public. Many of the people it brought to
light, such as Secord, Hakim, Calero and Singlaub, have been
indicted or forced to appear before congressional committees
investigating that case.
   The suit involved heroin smuggling from Laos, the ``Phoenix''
assassination program in Vietnam, the Bay of Pigs fiasco, cocaine
smuggling from Colombia, illegal Contra arms running, bombings,
threats, disappearances _ all to push what the plaintiffs believed
was a rabid right-wing ideology.
   On the side of the journalists, Tony Avirgan and Martha Honey,
was the liberal, Washington-based Christic Institute and their
attorney, Daniel Sheehan, a veteran of suits on behalf of radiation
victim Karen Silkwood and against the Ku Klux Klan.
   Both sides say politics was at the root of the case, which was
to go to trial Monday.
   ``I think it was 100 percent political,'' says Singlaub. ``I
think their real agenda is to discredit the intelligence service,
discredit the Reagan administration in general and to discredit
George Bush.''
   The vice president led the CIA at the time Shackley was
allegedly involved in the conspiracy, and later while vice
president, the Christics said, his office was aware of arms
smuggling to the Contras.
   The Christic Institute explanation is a mirror image of
Singlaub's. They say the politics involved was not theirs, but
rather that of the judge who favored the defendants and people in
the government who pressured him to protect Bush.
   ``I believe what has happened here is that this ruling is not a
legal ruling, it's a political ruling,'' said Sara Nelson, director
of the institute. ``The judge didn't want a political drama in his
courtroom before the election.''
   Both sides agree more litigation is in the wings.
   ``I have under active consideration plans to sue Sheehan for
libel,'' said Secord. ``This suit ... has been from the beginning
preposterous. Everyone thinks it's absurd and defaming and
malicious.''
   Sheehan is taking King's decision to an appeals court but says
he would be delighted to be the center of a libel trial. ``We'd be
right back in court with all our witnesses and all our documents,''
he said.
   One reason the defendants are threatening countersuits is to
recover the ruinously expensive costs of attending hearings,
responding to voluminous motions, reading thousands of documents
and taking depositions from hundreds of witnesses. The witness list
submitted for the trial had more than 2,000 names.
   Singlaub said he spent more than $250,000 on his own defense,
and his attorney, Thomas Spencer, said the defendants collectively
spent $1 million.
   It cost the Christic Institute even more, $3 million, according
Ms. Nelson.
   According to the suit, Shackley and others, using drug profits,
assassinated officials first in Vietnam, then Iran, Nicaragua and
other nations.
   The key event in the suit was the May 1984 bombing of a news
conference held by Contra commander Eden Pastora in La Penca,
Nicaragua.
   Three journalists and five Pastora supporters died in the
explosion. Avirgan was hurt and his camera damaged in the
explosion, allowing him to file a civil damage suit under federal
law.
   The suit charged the bombing was arranged by Shackley, Contra
leaders and others angered that Pastora refused to join
anti-Sandinista groups he considered too close to the CIA and
deposed Nicaraguan dictator Anastasio Somoza Debayle.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
