<DOCNO> AP880625-0116 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-06-25-88 1236EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r w AM-WhiteHouse-Economy     06-25 0616</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-White House-Economy,620</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Sprinkel Predicts Clear Economic Sailing</HEAD>
<NOTE>EDs: RETRANSMITS a0593 to correct cycle designator</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By DAVE SKIDMORE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Reagan administration's top economist
predicts robust growth and low inflation will enhance George Bush's
campaign for the White House, but some private analysts say the
outlook isn't all that rosy.
   Conventional wisdom says most people vote their pocketbooks. And
according to Beryl Sprinkel, chairman of President Reagan's Council
of Economic Advisers, ``Prospects for continued prosperity have
seldom been better.''
   The administration is looking for the sixth straight year of
economic expansion, coupled with low inflation, to bolster
Republican chances at the polls this November.
   Sprinkel, who was criticized as too optimistic late last year
when he predicted strong, steady growth for 1988, issued new
projections in the past week that look even better.
   He boosted his prediction of overall economic growth as measured
by the gross national product from 2.9 percent _ the same as 1986
and 1987 _ to 3.5 percent.
   He cut his unemployment rate forecast from 5.8 percent to 5.5
percent and stuck to his estimate of consumer price inflation, 4.3
percent, the same as last year.
   ``This expansion, already in its precedent-breaking 67th month,
now gives every indication of continuing at least through the end
of this administration and on into next year,'' he said.
   Private economists, who six months ago accused Sprinkel of
looking at the world through rose-colored glasses, now concede that
his growth projections then were, if anything, too conservative.
   The lasting shock to consumer buying that economists thought
would come from the October stock market crash never really
materialized and some say even the administration's new and higher
growth estimate is on target, even as they are more concerned about
the inflation outlook.
   The Commerce Department's latest report on GNP said booming
exports and a sharp increase in modernization and expansion
spending by businesses pushed growth to 3.6 percent in the first
quarter of this year after even stronger growth of 4.8 percent in
the last quarter of 1987.
   Private analysts, however, part company with Sprinkel's
prediction that inflation will hold steady at about the same level
as last year.
   Michael K. Evans, head of an economic consulting firm in
Washington, called the inflation numbers: ``Pie in the sky stuff.''
   Donald H. Straszheim, chief economist of Merrill Lynch, said the
economy has ``really done better than anybody has a right to
expect'' in making the transition from consumer-led to
export-driven growth.
   But, he said the administration can't ignore the inflationary
effect of the drought scorching the nation's midsection. Coming
increases in the price of food, which accounts for one-fifth of all
consumer purchases, likely will boost inflation to at least 5
percent, he said.
   Sprinkel agreed the severity of the rise in food prices remains
uncertain, but said he has allowed for temporary increases. He said
that packaging and distribution account for far more of the retail
price of food than crop prices, and argued food prices were
unlikely to add significantly to the underlying inflation rate
because food represents only about 2 percent of GNP.
   However, David Jones, chief economist of Aubrey G. Lanston &
Co., a government securities dealer, said a stiff jolt to food
prices runs the risk of triggering ``inflation psychology'' that
spills over into other sectors of the economy, just as the run up
in oil prices did in the 1970s.
   ``The shading of the administration's estimates on inflation may
involve at least some election-year politics in addition to
economic analysis,'' Jones said. ``What the administration is
trying to do is present a picture of strong economic growth and low
inflation as we come into an election.''
</TEXT>
