<FILEID>AP-NR-06-25-88 1329EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u i AM-CopterCrash Bjt   06-25 0638</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Copter Crash, Bjt,0655</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Marine Copter Crashes Into Mountain, Seven Americans Dead</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto TOK5</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By K.P. HONG</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A U.S. Marine Corps helicopter slammed into a
hillside and burned Saturday while flying in fog near a nuclear
power plant, and all seven Marines on board were killed, officials
said.
   The Sikorsky CH-53D Sea Stallion crashed about 30 minutes after
leaving the U.S. Marine Corps Air Station at Iwakuni, in
southwestern Japan, said Sgt. Nolan Wells of the station's public
affairs office.
   Names of the victims were withheld pending notification of their
families.
   Cloudy skies and dense fog were reported in the area at the time
of the crash on the southwest tip of Shikoko island, but it wasn't
immediately known if the weather contributed to the accident.
   Since 1980, at least 88 people have died in accidents involving
the Sea Stallion, or the later-model Super Stallion, the largest
and most expensive helicopter used by the U.S. military.
   Television footage showed Japanese and American rescue workers
carrying bodies in sacks over terraced rice paddies less than two
miles from a nuclear power station.
   Fog swirled around the hill where the aircraft crashed and
burned, and it appeared to be raining lightly. The wreckage was
scattered over a wide area, according to a local police official
who identified himself only as Sakamoto.
   Japanese aviation law prohibits aircraft from flying over
nuclear power stations and other nuclear-related facilities. There
are about 30 such facilities in Japan.
   The law also says that aircraft which must fly over such
facilities due to bad weather or to avoid a collision, must take
the least hazardous course or altitude.
   A Japanese Defense Agency official said in a telephone interview
that he saw ``little problem'' with the helicopter's flight path.
   ``We noticed the copter took a course several kilometers away
from the plant,'' despite the poor visibility in the area at the
time of the accident, said the official, who refused to be named.
   The Marines were flying to their base at Camp Futenma in
Okinawa, 580 miles away, where they were assigned to Marine Heavy
Helicopter Squadron 402 of the 1st Marine Air Wing, Wells said. The
United States has about 20,000 Marines stationed in Okinawa.
   The Sea Stallion left Iwakuni, about 700 miles southwest of
Tokyo, at 9:50 a.m. and crashed at about 10:20 a.m., Wells said.
   The CH-53D is capable of carrying up to 55 troops or a cargo of
32,000 pounds. The single-rotor, twin-engine aircraft is made by
the Stratford, Conn.-based Sikorsky Aircraft division of the United
Technologies Corp.
   The helicopter has had a series of operational problems and
fatal crashes.
   In November 1985, the military grounded the helicopters after
mechanics in a routine inspection discovered a defect in the
locknut that helps hold the rotor blade assembly to the aircraft.
   Sikorsky's former chief safety engineer alleged in a March 1987
court affidavit that metal mounts on the tail rotor gearbox of the
helicopter have failed or been suspected of failing an estimated 60
times since 1968. Sikorsky attorneys said the man was a disgruntled
former employee who was using internal company documents in
violation of his contract.
   Three Marines died in a Feb. 13, 1987 accident involving a Sea
Stallion helicopter in the Trabuco Canyon area near El Toro, Calif.
   In July 1985, a CH-53D crashed off Japan, killing four Marines.
In May 1985, 17 Marines were presumed killed when their Sea
Stallion crashed into the ocean off Japan's southern coast. And in
March 1984, a Sea Stallion slammed into a mountainside in Seoul,
and all 18 Americans and 11 South Koreans were killed. In 1983,
seven people died in two accidents.
   In addition, five were killed in 1982 in one crash, nine in 1981
in four accidents, and seven in 1980 in four accidents.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880625-0123 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-06-25-88 1338EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r w AM-Democrats-RadioText     06-25 0671</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Democrats-Radio Text,680</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>With AM-Defense Probe</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Here is the text of the Democratic Party's
weekly radio address, as delivered Saturday by Rep. Barbara Boxer
of California:
   This is Congresswoman Barbara Boxer from California. I'd like to
talk to you about the Pentagon scandal, and why Congress is deeply
troubled by it.
   You've heard about scandals before. But this one is different.
   It strikes at the heart of our national security, and, I
believe, was fueled by a consistent message by the Reagan
administration that government is our enemy and big defense
business our friend.
   If the FBI is right, then secret information worth tens of
billions has been traded by military insiders and defense
contractors to line their pockets and undermine the competitive
system that Congress has mandated.
   Why has this happened? I don't agree with President Reagan that
it's ``understandable.'' Do you?
   Or with Defense Secretary Carlucci who says there's nothing
wrong with the system, it's just a few individuals.
   Where is the outrage? Where is the concern?
   The root cause of this scandal was alluded to more than 20 years
ago by a president from the military, Dwight Eisenhower. He warned
about the unwarranted influence of the military-industrial complex,
and the need for ``an alert citizenry'' to protect against it.
   I want you to be an alert citizenry. I want you to know what has
gone on since this administration came to power in 1980.
   First, the military budget increased 100 percent from $150
billion to $300 billion today. Money was literally stuffed into the
Pentagon with too little attention paid to cost or quality _ as if
money alone could buy us security.
   We need a strong defense, but we must control wasteful spending.
   I want you to know that Congress has passed reforms. Each time
we were told by the Pentagon to butt out. But we said it was the
people's business.
   In 1984 we showed them the $7,000 coffee pot and asked for
reform. The Pentagon said that was an isolated incident.
   So we showed them the $600 toilet seat, the $300 no-smoking
sign, the $9,000 Allen wrench. All isolated incidents, they said.
   But we passed legislation to force competition on the $18
billion spare parts budget.
   But we knew there was more _ lots more. We said the Pentagon and
defense contractors were too cozy. The Pentagon said no. But we
passed revolving door legislation, stopping military procurement
officers from retiring and going to to work on Friday for the very
same contractors they investigated on Thursday.
   Over Pentagon objections, Congress passed strong whistleblower
protection for those brave people who speak out about fraud and
waste. This whole scandal unfolded because a whistleblower had the
guts to speak out.
   In 1986, Congress mandated a procurement czar to straighten out
the mess. An honorable man took the job but quit, frustrated that
he was fighting _ and losing _ every time.
   We legislated some good old-fashioned competition, and we said
enough to buying from monopolies.
   But the Pentagon, the contractors, and the administration didn't
like it. They howled.
   They were unabashed in their contempt toward congressional
reforms. They continued to try to water them down, repeal them or
ignore them.
   Now, in this tterrible scandal there has apparently been the
ultimate contempt _ as many as 50 consultants buying secret
information to destroy competition and cheat all of us.
   It is difficult to see six years of bipartisan work foiled by
what one news magazine calls ``a conspiracy of greed.''
   But we will learn from this and you, alert citizens, can help.
   Let us send a message through our votes that we've had enough of
pouring billions into a bottomless money pit.
   Let us send a message through our votes that we want an ethical
and honorable independent procurement system.
   You know, the code name for this FBI investigation is ``Ill
Wind.'' Let's turn this ill wind into winds of change _ for all of
us.
   It's about time, don't you think?
</TEXT>
</DOC>
