<FILEID>AP-NR-06-25-88 1357EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Soviet-Afghanistan     06-25 0509</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Soviet-Afghanistan,0524</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Soviets Says Their Warning on Afghan Pullout Meant As Pressure
Tactic</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ANDREW KATELL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MOSCOW (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A Foreign Ministry official indicated Saturday
that the Kremlin never intended to halt its troop withdrawal from
Afghanistan, as it threatened, and was only trying to put pressure
on Afghan rebel supporters.
   The comments by Deputy Foreign Minister Yuli M. Vorontsov seemed
designed to put to rest speculation that the Soviet Union might
slow or stop withdrawing its troops from Afghanstan because of
alleged violations of the accord providing for the withdrawal.
   He indicated the warnings were directed more at putting pressure
on Pakistan, which supports the rebels, than signaling any Soviet
backtracking.
   ``We are appealing to the conscience of Pakistan's leaders,''
Vorontsov said at a news conference, speaking through an
interpreter. ``We believe that the leaders of Pakistan will realize
their responsibility and that the world's public will help them
take awareness of their responsibilty.''
   Vorontsov, who helped negotiate the Geneva accords, also called
on reporters to investigate alleged Pakistani violations of the
accord, signed April 14.
   The Soviet Union has been complaining almost daily that
Pakistan's arms shipments to guerrillas fighting Afghanistan's
government and that the location of rebel training bases in
Pakistan violate the Geneva accords.
   Vorontsov cited specific examples of alleged U.S. and Pakistani
support for the rebels. He said a Pakistani general, Sarfaz Ahmad,
is in charge of a camp near the village of Kalan, near Islamabad,
where 2,500 rebels are training. American advisers are also at the
camp, Vorontsov said.
   The first Soviet warning of retaliation came May 28, when the
Foreign Ministry said that if Pakistan did not halt ``interference
in the internal affairs of Afghanistan,'' the Soviet Union would
``draw pertinent conclusions with respect to the timetable of the
troop withdrawal and take concrete steps.''
   Under the accords, the Soviet Union began pulling out its more
than 100,000 troops from Afghanistan on May 15 and is supposed to
have half of them out by Aug. 15. The pullout is to be completed by
Feb. 15.
   Soviet leader Mikhail S. Gorbachev and Afghan President Najib
warned after a Moscow meeting on June 13 that Pakistani violations
of the accord would bring ``resolute retaliatory steps.''
   Vadim I. Kuznetsov, deputy head of the U.S. desk in the Soviet
Foreign Ministry, said in an interview the next day that the
warning meant the withdrawing Soviet troops would strike back at
Afghan guerrillas who attack them.
   The United States has been supplying the Afghan rebels with an
estimated $500 million annually in arms and military supplies
channeled through Pakistan. It has vowed to continue the supplies
as long as the Soviet Union keeps up its military support of the
Afghan government.
   The Geneva accords prohibit Pakistani interference in
Afghanistan's affairs. But weapons supply from the Soviet Union is
not banned.
   A separate agreement signed by Moscow and Washington allows them
to continue supplying their respective allies.
   Soviet troops intervened in Afghanistan in December 1979
following a communist coup there the previous year.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
