<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Pope-Protest     06-25 0444</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Pope-Protest,0461</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Protesters Disrupt Performance of Controversial Play `The Deputy'</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Pope, Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By KEVIN COSTELLOE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>VIENNA, Austria (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Protesters disrupted a performance of a
play critical of the Vatican's role in dealing with the Nazis and
said the production was improper during the papal visit to Austria.
   ``This whole play is a just a lie!'' about 50 protesters shouted
late Friday during a performance of German author Rolf Hochhuth's
play, ``The Deputy.''
   Police took two protesters into custody. The incident occurred
on the second day of Pope John Paul II's visit to Austria.
   Hochhuth's play, first performed in 1963 in Berlin, alleges that
then-Pope Pius XII failed to do enough to prevent the Nazi
Holocaust.
   ``If I were writing the play again today, I would not present
the personage of Pope Pius XII so favorably,'' Hochhuth said later
during an informal discussion with the audience. The play already
is very critical of Pius XII.
   The play's assistant director, Hermann Beil, told The Associated
Press in a telephone interview that the demonstrators,
predominantly young people, shouted and used whistles to attract
attention during the performance at Vienna's Burgtheater.
   Beil said some in the audience shouted back at the protesters:
``Out with the Nazis!''
   The actors occasionally stopped to ask for silence.
   About 350 people were in the audience during the disruptions,
Beil said.
   The protesters called themselves ``The Young Friends of the
Burgtheater'' and distributed leaflets calling for the ouster of
theater director Claus Peymann.
   ``Out with Peymann,'' some chanted.
   Peymann himself told the audience later, ``I think it`s great
that a public forum can arise in this theater. Perhaps the theater
today has the function of presenting those questions that politics
no longer deal with.''
   Although critics reacted coolly to the play, it became a hit and
sparked impassioned debate over the Vatican's role before and
during World War II.
   In addition to Hochhuth, many Jewish leaders allege the Roman
Catholic Church failed to do enough to prevent the mass murder of
European Jews. But the current pope has strongly defended the
church's role during the Nazi era.
   John Paul even brought up the subject on the current trip.
   ``The incomprehensible pain, suffering and tears still are
before my eyes and etched deep in my soul,'' the pontiff said
Friday in reference to the Nazi murder of 6 million Jews.
   But he continued: ``It would be clearly unjust and untrue to
charge Christianity with these unspeakable crimes.''
   The theater's production of the play sparked controversy last
March, when it was performed at the time the Austrians were marking
the 50th anniversary of the country's annexation by Nazi Germany.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
