<1ST_LINE>u i AM-Soviet-Protests Bjt   06-25 0674</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Soviet-Protests, Bjt,0694</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Sakharov Speaks Out for Monument To Stalin's Victims</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ALISON SMALE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MOSCOW (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Dissident Andrei Sakharov joined former political
prisoners and intellectuals at a rally Saturday to demand a
monument to victims of Josef Stalin. It was Sakharov's first
appearance at a street rally in more than a decade.
   At another demonstration, about 200 people shouted ``Freedom!
Freedom!'' and ignored police orders to disperse. Police detained
at least three people.
   Sakharov, the Nobel Prize-winning physicist who spent seven
years in exile for speaking out against the Soviet government, told
600 people in north Moscow that a monument to Stalin's victims was
essential to remembering the country's ``tragic history.''
   The rally joined intellectuals who had been jailed or banished
from Moscow during the rule of former Soviet leader Leonid I.
Brezhnev and those who are still trying to get their works past
conformist censors.
   Flanked by a sign showing Stalin on a big black boot and warning
``He is still dangerous,'' Sakharov told a silent crowd that ``if
we have a memorial, we have to think of everybody who died, in the
repression, of hunger ... everybody was a victim.''
   Later, at Pushkin Square in the center of the city, a jostling
crowd of 200 refused to allow police to break up a demonstration by
the alternative political party, Democratic Union.
   They applauded a man who held up a sign saying ``No to the
political police. Break up the KGB.''
   Sakharov, 67, said the Soviet Union's sad past was symbolized by
the December 1986 death in jail of Anatoly Marchenko, a fellow
member of a group monitoring human rights in the 1970s.
   Marchenko's death is thought by some to have hastened the
decision by Soviet leader Mikhail S. Gorbachev two weeks later to
allow Sakharov and his wife, Yelena Bonner, to return to Moscow
from their exile in the closed city of Gorky.
   Others who spoke at the rally included former political
prisoners Sergei Kovalev and Lev Timofeyev, film director Elem
Klimov, historian Yuri Afanasyev and writers Ales Adamovich and
Yuri Karyakin.
   Karyakin told reporters that the rally ``was a beginning. It was
important that there were many young people there.''
   A group of Communist Party members and non-party intellectuals
have collected 30,000 signatures on a petition to a nationwide
party conference to approve a monument to the millions killed in
Stalin's purges. The conference begins Tuesday.
   Groups in the Baltic republic of Latvia and in the Siberian city
of Chita have campaigned for such a monument.
   Klimov and Afanasyev are delegates to the conference and
accepted the petition Saturday, promising to raise the issue of a
memorial if they are allowed to speak at the 5,000-delegate forum.
   Timofeyev called for greater openness about the extent of
Stalin's purges and proposed that Alexander Solzhenitsyn's
chronicle of Soviet prisons, ``The Gulag Archipelago,'' be
published in the Soviet Union.
   Sakharov's appearance at the rally marked the first time he has
taken part in a street protest since he and his wife campaigned for
freedom outside dissidents' trials in the 1970s.
   Sakharov was exiled to Gorky in January 1980 for speaking out
against the Soviet intervention in Afghanistan.
   About an hour after the anti-Stalin rally, which was held with
official approval, the Democratic Union tried to hold a
demonstration on Pushkin Square.
   Police did not intervene at first but later detained Democratic
Union leader Yuri Mityunov and at least two other people, prompting
a shoving match with the crowd of Democratic Union supporters and
onlookers.
   A rally staged by another group, the National Front, was then
allowed to go ahead, apparently because they back official policies
and are not challenging the monopoly of the Communist party.
   Police tried to break up the demonstrations by throwing up a
cordon dividing them, shouting at citizens to move along and
waiting for the rest to disperse gradually.
   Mityunov said earlier the Democratic Union, which was set up in
May, held a sanctioned meeting for about four hours with 1,000
participants in Leningrad Friday.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
