<1ST_LINE>r a AM-People-Magnuson     06-25 0267</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-People-Magnuson,0274</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Former Sen. Warren Magnuson Hospitalized with Heart Attack</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SEATTLE (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Former Sen. Warren G. Magnuson, whose career in
Congress spanned 44 years, has been hospitalized after suffering a
slight heart attack, his wife said.
   Magnuson, 83, was taken to Swedish Hospital by ambulance after
being stricken Friday, said Jermaine Magnuson.
   Hospital spokeswoman Abbi Kaplan said the former senator was
responding to medication Saturday and his condition had stabilized.
   Magnuson suffers from diabetes, a condition which causes poor
circulation. In 1982, three toes on the senator's right foot were
amputated after becoming infected. In 1985, his right foot was
amputated because of circulation problems.
   Mrs. Magnuson said her husband began feeling sick Friday
afternoon and was diagnosed as having suffered a ``slight'' heart
attack Friday evening.
   He had been scheduled to receive the King County Man of the Year
Award from the King County Democrats that night, she said.
   ``His spirits are up,'' Mrs. Magnuson said. ``He always keeps
his sense of humor. He was telling the doctors, `Oh, here you guys
go poking on me again.'''
   Magnuson was first elected to Congress in 1936 and served four
terms, interrupted by eight months' service with the Navy in the
South Pacific during World War II. He won his Senate seat in 1944
and was re-elected five times before being defeated by Republican
Slade Gorton in 1980.
   Over his decades in the Senate, Magnuson rose to the
chairmanship of the Senate Commerce Committee and became the Senate
president pro tempore, third in line to the presidency behind the
vice president and speaker of the House.
</TEXT>
