<1ST_LINE>r a AM-HotPants     06-25 0335</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Hot Pants,0344</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Yeast Infection Remedy Nearly Burns Down House, Authorities Say</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WEST JORDAN, Utah (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A woman following a newspaper story's
advice to yeast infection sufferers tossed her underpants in the
microwave and sparked a fire, authorities say.
   Firefighters rushed to the woman's home in this south Salt Lake
County community of 27,000 on Friday morning and quickly
extinguished the flames, but not before her microwave oven was
destroyed and a nearby wall scorched, said County Fire Chief Don
Berry.
   Berry said when the embarassed woman explained how the fire
started, firefighters were hard-pressed not to laugh.
   ``It's one of those things that `Just when you think you've seen
everything ...,''' Berry said.
   However, Berry said the incident's humorous side was tempered by
its potential for developing into a serious fire if it had not
quickly been extinguished. There were no injuries.
   Berry said the woman, who was not identified, decided to
``cook'' her underpants after reading a news service article in a
local paper quoting University of Florida obstetrics and gynecology
researchers as saying the bacteria responsible for yeast infections
can be killed in a microwave oven in five minutes on the high-power
setting.
   The article emphasized the process only works on cotton
underpants, and also recommended the underwear be freshly laundered
and slightly damp.
   The woman was certain the underwear that caught on fire was 100
percent cotton, but fire officials believe they were probably of an
artificial material. If the underpants were indeed cotton, the
elastic material may have been to blame, they said.
   Berry said that after seeing what happened to the woman's
kitchen, he could not recommend the microwave process. ``I just
wouldn't do it,'' he said.
   The University of Florida article said yeast bacteria can also
be killed by soaking or boiling underwear in bleach, or by ironing.
Common detergents will not kill the bacteria.
   Antibiotics can fight the actual yeast infection, but women tend
to become reinfected, possibly from wearing contaminated underwear,
the article said.
</TEXT>
