<1ST_LINE>u a AM-AMAConvention Bjt   06-25 0534</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-AMA Convention, Bjt,0548</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Doctors To Debate Proposals On AIDS, Medicaid Reform At AMA
Convention</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By WILLIAM C. HIDLAY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Doctors will debate proposals for battling AIDS,
overhauling Medicaid and training a new type of bedside hospital
worker this week at the American Medical Association's annual
policymaking convention.
   Members of the AMA's House of Delegates, which convenes Sunday,
also plan to discuss a proposed ban on selling plastic handguns, a
move to put warning labels on alcoholic beverages and the
association's stand on mercy killing.
   The meeting, which runs through Thursday, is expected to attract
up to 2,000 doctors from across the country. The 420 delegates
represent the AMA's 295,000 members and act as a legislature,
setting policy for the nation's largest organization of physicians.
   The delegates will receive more than 75 reports on problems
ranging from child pornography to the health hazards of clove
cigarettes.
   They also will consider at least 155 resolutions on such issues
as the health risks of tanning parlors and ways to revamp the
nation's Medicare health insurance system for the elderly.
   ``AIDS, of course, is the biggest threatening health problem in
the United States,'' AMA president Dr. William Hotchkiss, a surgeon
from Chesapeake, Va., said last week. ``There is still considerable
debate that I think will take place over the issue of testing.''
   One resolution, proposed by a group of delegates from Ohio,
recommends requiring state and local health departments to contact
the sexual partners of anyone who tests positive for the AIDS virus.
   The proposal also recommends that all immigrants and inmates be
tested for the virus and calls for a national catastrophic health
insurance program for AIDS victims and legislation to protect them
from discrimination.
   The AMA Board of Trustees is proposing a major overhaul of
Medicaid, the nation's program for helping the poor pay for medical
care.
   An AMA report says the program, administered by state
governments, is fraught with ``severe inequities.'' Its calls for
expanding Medicaid to cover an additional 27 million people at or
below the poverty level now excluded because eligibility varies
from state to state.
   A battle may erupt over the AMA trustees' proposal to help
offset the nationwide shortage of nurses by creating a new class of
hospital workers to provide some bedside care to patients.
   Several nurses associations oppose the plan to create licensed
``registered care technologists.'' Under the plan, high school
graduates could begin caring for patients as assistant
technologists with two months' training. They could become basic
technologists with an additional seven months' training and
advanced technologists after nine more months of study.
   Their duties would include bathing patients, giving out
medication and changing bandages.
   ``This is in no way a substitute for nurses,'' Hotchkiss said.
``It is in addition to nurses.''
   Also up for debate are resolutions calling on the AMA to oppose
so-called mercy killing or euthanasia by doctors and ``refrain from
publishing articles which involve the taking of human life''
without stating the group's position.
   The Journal of the American Medical Association was criticized
earlier this year when it published an article by an unidentified
doctor describing how he ended the life of a terminally ill cancer
patient.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
