<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Salvador-Cocaine     06-25 0185</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Salvador-Cocaine,0191</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Cocaine Bust Biggest in Salvadoran History</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SAN SALVADOR, El Salvador (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Authorities confiscated more
than 500 pounds of cocaine after a light plane believed to be from
Colombia made a forced landing during a storm, police said Saturday.
   National Police press officer Vicente Ortiz said the seizure,
made Tuesday, was the biggest in Salvadoran history. He said
several people were under arrest, but he refused to provide their
names.
   The daily El Diario de Hoy, citing police sources, said six
Salvadorans and one Colombian were arrested.
   It said the plane's Colombian pilot landed the single-enging
Cessna during a storm Tuesday on a strip on a farm 40 miles west of
San Salvador.
   Police said the pilot, hampered by poor visibility, knocked down
electrical wires as he came in for a landing.
   Seventeen boxes, each with 30 pounds of cocaine, were
transferred from the plane to a panel truck with a double wall
designed to conceal cargo, they said.
   Authorities said the pilot told them where to find the truck.
They said they believe the cocaine was destined for the United
States.
</TEXT>
