<HEAD>Government Announces Investigation into Sheep Burning</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WARSAW, Poland (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A public prosecutor will investigate a
crew of Polish and Hungarian film makers who burned alive about 30
sheep while making a movie, the state-run PAP news agency said
Saturday.
   The ``barbaric act'' was committed May 23 in the Krzystowka
Meadows near the Tatra National Park in southern Poland near the
Czechoslovak border, PAP said.
   Movie extras from the nearby tourist resort of Zakopane, local
highlanders and firefighters hired by the crew witnessed the
burning of the sheep during the shooting of a scene, PAP said.
   ``The wave of indignation and protests ... is growing,'' PAP
said. A department of the Krakow Agricultural Academy has written
the minister of culture demanding an inquiry to decide ``who should
be punished for this unprecendented act of barbarism,'' it said.
   Newspapers in the Krakow area have been deluged with similar
letters and the Krakow regional prosecutor has launched an
investigation, PAP said.
   The PAP account did not give the name or any other details about
the film being made.
