<1ST_LINE>r i AM-SriLanka     06-25 0230</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Sri Lanka,0235</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Four Tamils Killed in Jaffna</HEAD>
<DATELINE>COLOMBO, Sri Lanka (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The bodies of four young Tamil men who
had been shot through the head and had their hands tied behind
their backs were found in the Jaffna Peninsula, military officials
said Saturday.
   The killings may have stemmed from rivalries among a half-dozen
Tamil militant groups, according to the officials who spoke on
condition of anonymity.
   The bodies were found Friday in Urumpirai, a village five miles
north of Jaffna and about 185 miles north of Colombo.
   The Jaffna Peninsula has been the chief stronghold of Tamil
rebels seeking independence or greater autonomy for their ethnic
minority. Tamils comprise about 18 percent of Sri Lanka's 16
million people.
   Indian peacekeeping troops have been trying to disarm the rebels
for nearly 11 months.
   Many Tamils say they are discriminated against by island
nation's Sinhalese majority, which dominates the government and
military. Sinhalese make up 75 percent of the population.
   The two ethnic groups speak different languages and also are
divided by religion. Most Sinhalese are Buddhists and most Tamils
are Hindus.
   India, Sri Lanka's northern neighbor, has a large Tamil
population of its own. It mediated an accord signed last July that
was aimed at ending the Tamil war in Sri Lanka. However, the main
rebel group has opposed the pact and refused to lay down its arms.
</TEXT>
