<1ST_LINE>r p AM-Jackson     06-25 0364</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Jackson,360</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Jackson Says Puerto Ricans Should Decide Commonwealth's Status</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAN SEWELL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>VIEQUES, Puerto Rico (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Jesse Jackson said Saturday it
should be up to the people of Puerto Rico to settle the debate over
whether their commonwealth should retain its current status or opt
to become a state or for independence.
   Jackson said the Democratic Party platform should support
increased autonomy for Puerto Ricans, but that he wasn't taking
sides in the debate over whether it should no longer be a
commonwealth.
   Jackson, on the third day of his visit to Puerto Rico, met with
religious and political leaders on the island-municipality of
Vieques, where fishermen and activists have complained for years
about U.S. Navy shelling practices.
   He didn't call for the Navy to withdraw from the island or from
giant Roosevelt Roads Naval Station on Puerto Rico's east coast,
but said Puerto Ricans should have the right to make such a
decision. The Navy owns two-thirds of Vieques.
   ``When you are empowered you have the right to make such a
decision,'' Jackson said. ``It's up to the judgment of the people.''
   He said he looks ``forward to the day when Vieques is an island
of peace, when there will be peace exercises and not war
exercises.''
   ``Stop the shelling in Vieques,'' Jackson said at an ecumenical
peace service. ``We must not destroy the fish. We must not
shell-shock the children.''
   U.S. policy throughout the Caribbean should focus on economic
development, respect for self-determination and thwarting the drug
trade, he said.
   ``The Reagan-Bush policy has been one of invasion (referring to
the 1983 U.S. invasion of Grenada) and radical disregard for
self-determination and for human rights,'' he said.
   In the late 1970s and early 1980s there were frequents protests
in Vieques against Navy maneuvers that fishermen said ruined their
fishing and hurt tourism and economic development. The Navy four
years ago agreed to reduce the amount of bombing and maneuvers and
to spur economic development on Vieques.
   ``All the protests are in the past,'' said William Tapia, who
runs the Hotel Carmen.
   However, local officials said unemployment remains high,
reaching 40 percent or 50 percent at times.
</TEXT>
