<FILEID>AP-NR-06-25-88 1632EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a AM-NOWConference     06-25 0411</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-NOW Conference,0423</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>New NOW Strategy Is To Fight Bias At Local Level</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DARREN DOPP</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BUFFALO, N.Y. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A new campaign to get the Equal Rights
Amendment passed won't be limited to lobbying Congress and state
legislatures, leaders of the National Organization for Women said
Saturday.
   The ERA battle also will be fought at Social Security offices,
on college campuses and other places where women are treated
unfairly, NOW President Molly Yard said during the opening session
of the group's national conference.
   ``We need to invent new tactics to protest inequality,'' Yard
told about 500 NOW members.
   NOW has called on its local chapters to stage sit-ins at Social
Security offices to protest unequal distribution of benefits and at
college campuses, where women professors have a hard time getting
tenure and where predominantly male administrators are insensitive
to campus violence against women, she said.
   ``Our only guarantee against these things is to be included in
the Constitution,'' she said.
   ``We must keep the fire burning and keep those who perpetuate
inequality uncomfortable,'' said former NOW president Eleanor
Smeal. ``The way we are going to pass this amendment is not to
worry about what people think of us.''
   The ERA was approved by only 35 of the necessary 38 states
before a 10-year time limit expired in 1982.
   NOW's new campaign for ERA passage officially begins Thursday
with a rally in Washington. The group hopes to give Congress a
petition with 100,000 signatures.
   The group's leaders say the Reagan administration has been
hostile to their cause, so the end of President Reagan's term makes
the time right for passage of the amendment. Recent national polls
indicate as much as 75 percent of American voters support ERA, they
said.
   In addition to more active protesting, NOW will expand its
efforts to get women elected to local political offices.
   Alice Cohan, NOW's political director, said ERA supporters have
learned that they need to put ERA sympathizers in power, ``so them
is us.''
   Fewer than 5 percent of the nation's congressional
representatives and only 15 percent of state legislators are women,
she noted.
   Pat Frank, a Democratic candidate for the U.S. Senate from
Florida, told NOW members that supporting female candidates is
effective even if they don't win. Frank said their campaigns focus
attention on issues such as pay equity, day care and social
services.
   Former congresswoman and presidential candidate Shirley Chisholm
is scheduled to address the conference Sunday.
</TEXT>
