<FILEID>AP-NR-06-25-88 1637EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u a AM-CrashSettlement 1stLd-Writethru a0643 06-25 0698</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Crash Settlement, 1st Ld - Writethru, a0643,0710</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Family Rejects $50,000 Offer, Seeks $6.5 Million From Air Force</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: LEADS with 8 grafs to recast and to CORRECT in 1st and 6th
grafs pvs that lawyer quoted is not involved in Goldbergs' case,
but has experience in other wrongful death cases. Picks up 9th graf
pvs, `Many of...'.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By BETH HARRIS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>INDIANAPOLIS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Air Force's offer of $50,000 to the
parents of a woman killed when one of its jets slammed into a hotel
is an outrage, says a lawyer who is an expert on wrongful death,
but the Air Force says its offer is consistent with state law.
   Indiana law provides little in the way of damage payments when a
single person dies, which the woman's family criticized as
discriminatory.
   Robert and Harriet Goldberg of Indianapolis already have
rejected the Air Force's offer, which doubled the original $25,000
sum, and say they may take the matter to court.
   They had been seeking $6.5 million in damages for the death of
their daughter, Beth L. Goldberg, 30.
   She was among 10 people killed Oct. 20 when the Air Force A-7
fighter jet crashed into the lobby of the Ramada Inn Airport, where
she worked. The pilot, who was from Nellis Air Force Base in
Nevada, ejected from the craft before it crashed and was not
seriously injured.
   Stanley M. Chesley, a Cincinnati-based lawyer who specializes in
multiple death cases, is not involved in the Goldbergs' case but
said the $50,000 offer was ridiculous.
   ``Just because someone isn't married doesn't mean their life
isn't worth anything,'' he said in a telephone interview Friday.
``There's only one way to get a full settlement: Take it to the
courthouse.''
   Under Indiana's wrongful death law, a court can award damage
payments to parents if a minor child dies, and to the spouse or
other financial dependents of an adult who dies. However, only
medical, funeral and estate administration costs can be collected
when an adult dies who had no financial dependents.
   Many of the jet crash victims had dependent families, but Ms.
Goldberg was single.
   ``Based on Indiana law, that's an amount that's consistent in
this type of situation,'' said Maj. Derence V. Fivehouse of the Air
Force aviation litigation section. ``If we did somebody harm, we
pay them what we owe them by state law. That's my mandate.''
   As of Friday, the Air Force had settled 98 of the 108 claims
filed, said Fivehouse. He refused to say what size settlements were
being offered to families of other victims.
   ``Only people with dependents are entitled to love and
affection? She was such a vital part of our family,'' Goldberg said
of his daughter, the oldest of the couple's three daughters.
   ``Indiana law needs to be changed because our wrongful death law
is so archaic,'' Goldberg said. ``I feel we have a moral obligation
to pursue it. Nothing in the way of a settlement is going to bring
our daughter back.''
   Fivehouse said the Goldbergs were given a July 1 deadline to
consider the settlement offer so that the proceedings would not
stall. After Friday, the family will be sent a letter acknowledging
their rejection of the $50,000 offer.
   The Goldbergs then will have six months to continue negotiations
or file suit, Fivehouse said. ``It appears that's what they want,''
he added.
   Goldberg said the family would be willing to lower the claim,
but plans to file a lawsuit if an agreement isn't reached in the
next month.
   The Goldbergs' $6.5 million claim figure was based on the amount
of money their daughter would have made during her career, the
family's emotional devastation and the cost of psychiatric
counseling for Ms. Goldberg's survivors. Ms. Goldberg was a sales
representative at the hotel.
   Chesley has represented families of victims in the 1980 MGM
hotel fire in Las Vegas, Nev., that killed 84 people, and the 1977
Beverly Hills Supper Club fire in northern Kentucky that killed 164.
   Settlements for the claims in the MGM fire ranged from $1
million to $2 million for single individuals and $7 million to $9
million for people with dependents, Chesley said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
