<FILEID>AP-NR-06-25-88 1655EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a AM-BoatsFound     06-25 0564</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Boats Found,0578</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>State Of Arkansas Apparently Owns Old Boats, Lawyer Says</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Drought Week, Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By SCOTT CHARTON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LITTLE ROCK, Ark. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The state of Arkansas apparently has a
claim to five old wooden boats discovered on the bed of the
drought-shrunken Mississippi River, a lawyer who represents the
vessels' four discoverers said Saturday.
   But if the state doesn't claim the boats, which were found last
weekend about 100 yards from the river's Arkansas side, the four
West Memphis men ``would probably have a superior claim over
anybody else,'' said attorney Davis Lofton.
   State Attorney General Steve Clark said Saturday that the state
would likely pursue clarification of ownership of the boats, which
one of the discoverers said may date to the 1840s. ``But it depends
on what the value is. It's not their dollar value that's so
important, but the historical value,'' Clark said, adding that he
was not familiar with the find.
   Don Spears said Saturday that he and three friends found the
boats while walking along river bottom that has become exposed and
cracked because of the drought that has lowered the river 20 feet.
The boats were about a half-mile from the bridge connecting West
Memphis to Memphis, Tenn, Spears said.
   ``It was a total surprise,'' said Spears, 42, adding that he has
long heard tales of the Mississippi concealing sunken boats. ``I
think this needs to be preserved. It's history.''
   The age of the boats hasn't been determined, he said.
   Lofton said his clients also wouldn't mind ``the possibility of
making some money off of it.''
   However, the Abandoned Shipwreck Act of 1987, which President
Reagan signed on April 28, puts boats submerged in navigable waters
in possession of the federal government, in trust for the state in
which the vessels are found, Lofton said.
   A state archaeologist who examined the vessels last week didn't
seem to think Arkansas would be interested in preserving them,
Lofton said.
   ``That's why I want to read this law,'' Lofton said. If the
state decides it doesn't want the boats, his clients ``are
investigating the possibility of dealing with some sort of salvage
company that has the capability of doing this.''
   Spears said he and his friends _ Dick Suiter, Larry Samples and
Chuck King _ were willing ``to just leave this matter up to time
right now,'' to see if the state lays claim to the boats.
   ``This is very valuable,'' Suiter said. ``We're not out to get
somebody to grease our palms. This is something that Arkansas
should be proud of. It could make an archaeological museum that
could bring in millions of dollars in tourist traffic.''
   The Commercial Appeal at Memphis offered a theory Saturday about
how the boats sank, quoting two local amateur river historians,
Kenneth Marquis and Mike Butler, as saying they may have gone down
in a 1918 ice storm.
   The best-preserved of the five vessels may be a coal barge that
dates to the 1880s, the pair said.
   Columnist William Thomas also reported that ``veteran
river-watchers say the wrecks have been exposed before _ last year,
a salvage worker used a torch to cut the metal cleats off one of
the boats.''
   Suiter discounted the ice storm theory. ``If they had been in
this storm, the boats would have been crushed, and they're not,''
he said in a telephone interview.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880625-0154 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-06-25-88 1700EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i AM-PrayerTime     06-25 0231</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Prayer Time,0237</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Watch Tells Moslems When To Pray</HEAD>
<DATELINE>RIYADH, Saudi Arabia (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A U.S. company has designed a
wristwatch that alerts Moslems when it's time to pray and even
shows them the direction of the holy city of Mecca from 120 cities
around the world, a newspaper said Saturday.
   An alarm sounds 10 minutes before each day's five prayer
periods, the English-language Saudi Gazette said.
   The actual time is dictated by the position of the sun,
according to the Koran, Islam's holy book, which also decrees that
the faithful should face Mecca while praying.
   Traditionally, the five daily prayer calls are made by muezzins,
or priests, who summon the faithful from minarets attached to
mosques.
   Nowadays, prayer periods are published by newspapers and
broadcast by radio and television stations in Moslem countries.
   The watch has been developed by Sysorex International, a
computer systems company based in Mountain View, Calif., the
newspaper said.
   The Gazette quoted Abdullah Saadan, the Sysorex agent in the
Middle East, as saying the watch communicates in both Arabic and
English and gives both Gregorian and Hijra, or Islamic calendar,
dates.
   To overcome differences between Moslem scholars over how prayer
times should be determined, Saadan said the times programmed into
the watch have been approved by several Islamic bodies.
   The watch comes in various models ranging in price from $85 to
$115, the newspaper said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
