<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Iran-Canada     06-25 0229</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Iran-Canada,0237</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Talks Under way To Restore Links, Minister Says</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NICOSIA, Cyprus (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Iran's Foreign Minister, Ali Akbar
Velayati, says talks are under way with Canada to normalize
diplomatic relations, the official Islamic Republic News Agency
reported Saturday.
   IRNA, monitored in Nicosia, said Velayati gave no details of the
negotiations with Ottawa but stressed that Tehran wants no
relations with countries that oppose its policies.
   He did not elaborate, IRNA said, but he noted that Iran restored
links with France this month after an 11-month rupture and said
relations with Britain, strained for years, have ``relatively
improved.''
   A British parliamentary delegation visited Tehran last week to
discuss ways of improving ties.
   IRNA said Velayati spoke Friday in an interview.
   Canada closed its embassy in Tehran in 1980 after Canadian
diplomats sheltered several Americans who had escaped from the U.S.
Embassy when it was stormed by Iranian militants in November 1979.
   The Canadians helped smuggle the Americans out of Iran.
   Ottawa has retained diplomatic relations with Iran, with the
Danish Embassy in Tehran handling its interests.
   Philip Engs, a Canadian engineer arrested on spying charges in
Iran, was released in February last year after two months in jail.
   Iran, isolated diplomatically and put on the defensive after a
string of military defeats in its war with Iraq, is making clear
efforts to improve its links with Western states.
</TEXT>
