<FILEID>AP-NR-06-25-88 1732EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u a AM-WeatherpageWeather     06-25 0453</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Weatherpage Weather,0465</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>More Record Highs But Heat Wave Nearing End</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   A cold front brought lower temperatures to the northern Plains
on Saturday after days of record heat, but more than 30 record
highs were posted as the hot air moved across the Ohio Valley.
   Temperatures across the northern Plains were 15 to 25 degrees
cooler than Friday, but there was no relief from the drought across
the region.
   Temperatures across the lower Great Lakes and the Ohio Valley
were 15 to 25 degrees warmer than on Friday. The hottest official
temperature across the lower 48 states was 106 at Elkhart, Ind.
   Relief was in sight as the cold front was moving southeastward
across the Great Lakes and Sunday temperatures were expected to be
in the upper 70s and low 80s.
   High wind toppled trees and power lines in southeastern
Michigan. Nearly 10,000 Detroit Edison Co. customers, including
about 7,000 in Oakland County, were without electrical service
Saturday afternoon, spokeswoman Lorie Kessler said.
   Showers and thunderstorms were scattered across central and
southern parts of Texas into parts of Oklahoma, Arkansas and
Louisiana.
   Thunderstorms also developed over much of the eastern half of
Alabama and northeastern Florida.
   Showers and thunderstorms also were scattered from the central
California coast into much of Oregon and eastern Washington. Some
of the thunderstorms were capable of producing brief heavy rain,
gusty wind and hail over eastern Oregon.
   Showers and thunderstorms moved across parts of eastern New York
state and northern Vermont, dumping more than 1.75 inches of rain
at Peru, N.Y., and more than an inch at Burlington, Vt.
   Thunderstorms developed across parts of northeastern and central
Colorado. A tornado touched down briefly near Watkins during the
afternoon but did not cause any damage.
   Temperatures around the nation at 3 p.m. EDT ranged from 56
degrees at Crescent City, Calif., and Santa Fe, N.M., to 106 at
Elkart, Ind. The low for the day was 40 at Gunnison, Colo.
   For Sunday, scattered showers and thunderstorms were forecast
from New England through the middle Atlantic states and the central
Gulf Coast into Florida. Scattered showers and thunderstorms also
were forecast across the Pacific Northwest to the northern Rockies.
   Highs in the 60s were predicted over northwestern Washington
state; in the 70s along the Pacific Coast into parts of the rest of
the Pacific Northwest, and from the upper Great Lakes through
northern parts of the Ohio Valley into New England; in the mid to
upper 90s from the central Rockies through the central and southern
Plains into much of the Southeast states; between 100 and 110
across the desert Southwest; and in the 80s or 90s across much of
the rest of the nation.
</TEXT>
