<1ST_LINE>r i AM-SoccerArrests     06-25 0253</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Soccer Arrests,0262</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Police Arrest 30 Soccer Fans</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MUNICH, West Germany (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Police on Saturday arrested 30
soccer fans in connection with violent clashes and other offenses
surrounding the finale of the European Championships between the
Netherlands and the Soviet Union.
   A Munich police spokesman said most of the fans arrested were
Dutch. He said a Swiss man and several West Germans were also in
custody after incidents early Saturday.
   Police said those arrested faced charges of assault, theft,
resisting arrest and destruction of property.
   Many arrests followed clashes in downtown Munich, police said.
   Police said 60 drunk fans were turned away from Munich's soccer
stadium before the game.
   The Netherlands won the match 2-0. No major clashes were
reported after the game.
   ``In general, we're satisfied with the situation,'' said a
police official who spoke on condition of anonymity. ``Most of the
fans are peaceful.''
   The rowdies involved in Saturday's early clashes had been
drinking heavily in the city's beer garden district, police said.
   More than 3,500 police officers were on duty in Munich to
prevent massive outbreaks of violence.
   A capacity crowd of 72,000 was on hand for Saturday's
championship game. About 35,000 Dutch fans attended the match.
   Police said they charged eight people with ticket scalping
outside the stadium. The men were offering single tickets at prices
up to $880, police said.
   More than 800 fans have been arrested as a result of violence
that erupted in many West German cities since the championship
series began June 10.
</TEXT>
