<FILEID>AP-NR-06-25-88 1738EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Gulf-Roberts     06-25 0667</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Gulf-Roberts,0689</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Mine-Damaged Frigate Towed Out for Loading Aboard Cargo Ship</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RICHARD PYLE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MANAMA, Bahrain (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The mine-damaged U.S. missile frigate
Samuel B. Roberts was towed out of Dubai Saturday toward a Persian
Gulf island to be loaded aboard a specially built cargo vessel that
will take it back to the United States.
   The 3,600-ton frigate was severely damaged when it hit a
submerged Iranian mine April 14. It underwent preliminary repairs
at a Dubai shipyard and will be rebuilt in the United States, U.S.
officials say.
   The Mighty Servant 2, a 25,743-ton Dutch cargo ship chartered by
the Navy to carry the Roberts, was anchored off Abu Nu'ayr island,
60 miles west of Dubai.
   It was to be partially submerged to allow the frigate to be
floated onto its deck.
   The tricky loading operation was in danger of being delayed by
rough seas, gulf-based shipping sources reported, speaking on the
condition of anonymity.
   Three-foot swells were reported off Abu Nu'ayr, they said.
   Associated Press photographer Greg English said the Samuel B.
Roberts, which nearly sank after the mine ripped a 25-foot gash in
its hull, ``looked normal'' as it was towed from Dubai's busy port
by the tugboat Tornado.
   He said the frigate was about 12 miles from its rendezvous with
the Mighty Servant 2 when the towline was lost, and the frigate
continued under its own auxiliary power.
   Most of the frigate's 225 crewmen have returned to the United
States, but 30 stayed behind to go home with the ship.
   The blast, which wounded 10 crewmen, occurred as the ship tried
to back out of what U.S. officials said was a newly laid minefield
in a main shipping channel 50 miles northeast of Qatar.
   The United States retaliated four days later with attacks on two
Iranian oil platforms, triggering daylong naval clashes in which
six Iranian vessels were sunk or damaged.
   Although Abu Ny'ayr is in an area where Iranian gunboats have
attacked commercial shipping, the sources said a 5-mile ``exclusion
zone'' was in effect around the island.
   Another U.S. frigate, the Elmer Montgomery, was on guard duty in
the area, they reported. English said the Italian frigate Espero
was also in the area.
   The U.S. Navy says the Roberts will go first to its home port at
Newport, R.I., and then to the Bath, Maine, shipyard where it was
launched two years ago.
   U.S. officials denied reports the ship was judged a ``writeoff''
and will be scrapped.
   ``The USS Samuel B. Roberts is going to Bath Iron Works to be
repaired, period,'' said Cmdr. Mark Baker, a Navy spokesman at the
Pentagon.
   His comment followed a report in Britain's Guardian daily
quoting ``foreign naval sources'' in the United Arab Emirates as
saying the ship ``has a broken back,'' with only its electronics
gear salvageable.
   The Guardian said the ship was kept in drydock to ``prevent the
full extent of damage from being revealed,'' possibly leading to
Congress conducting a new inquiry into the U.S. role in the gulf.
   Iran's official Islamic Republic News Agency, monitored in
Cyprus, quoted the newwspaper as saying the ship's return home was
a cover-up to conceal the loss of the $300 million vessel.
   U.S. officials said the day the frigate was mined that its back
was broken by the blast, which wrecked the engine room, triggering
fires and flooding.
   They later said the ship was saved only by the crew's actions
and by its having been at general quarters, with watertight doors
closed, when it hit the mine.
   U.S. officials also said the Samuel B. Roberts was taken to
Dubai because it had a shipyard facility capable of handling the
preliminary repair work.
   Iran has not acknowledged laying the mine.
   But U.S. officials said several other mines found and destroyed
in the area were identical with Iranian mines found earlier in the
gulf. They said the latest ones bore no marine growth, indicating
they had been in the water only a few days.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
