<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Britain-RigCollision     06-25 0239</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Britain-Rig Collision,0244</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Cargo Ship Collided With Gas Rig</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BRIDLINGTON, England (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Canadian-managed cargo ship
Irving Forest collided with the gas drilling rig Glomar Labrador
off Yorkshire, northeast England, and 45 men were evacuated from
the platform, the coast guard said Saturday.
   No injuries were reported in the incident early Thursday, the
coast guard said, and although both the platform and the ship were
damaged, the 6,000-ton coaster Irving Forest was able to continue
on its way to Rotterdam.
   One leg of the drilling platform, under charter to Amoco Oil,
was damaged, but the Daily Telegraph quoted a company spokesman as
saying the rig should be operational again soon.
   The Irving Forest had left Hartlepool, at the mouth of the River
Tees, with a cargo of wood pulp when it struck the Glomar Labrador
at 2:45 a.m. 20 miles off Bridlington, said an unidentified
spokesman for the coast guard marine coordination center in
Bridlington.
   The center summoned a standby boat, the Blue Flame 1, from the
adjacent Rough Gas Field, which took 39 men off the rig while
Humber life boats stood by.
   Six more rig workers were removed later, leaving eight still on
board, the coast guard said.
   The cargo vessel, with 18 crew aboard, was damaged above the
waterline, the spokesman said, and was able to continue to its
destination.
   The Irving Forest, registered in Bermuda, is managed by the
Canadian Kent Line Ltd.
</TEXT>
