<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Nicaragua     06-25 0255</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Nicaragua,0262</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Contras Reject Sandinista Proposal for Sunday Talks</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By FILADELFO ALEMAN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MANAGUA, Nicaragua (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The U.S.-backed rebels on Saturday
refused to return to Managua for peace talks with the leftist
Sandinista government.
   A spokesman for the rebels, known as Contras, said the capital
doesn't have a ``favorable atomosphere'' for negotiations because
the government wants to put too many restrictions on rebel
negotiators.
   The Sandinistas had proposed a four-day round of peace talks
beginning Sunday in Managua.
   As an alternative to another formal round of talks, they offered
to meet with the rebels in Miami to discusss extending the
cease-fire. Contra spokesman Roberto Ferrey said resistance leaders
would reply to that offer on Monday.
   Ferrey said in a telephone interview from Miami that Nicaraguan
Resistance leaders complain the government will not let them meet
with opposition parties in Managua and also wants to restrict
Contra negotiators to their hotel.
   The Sandinistas put similar restrictions on the rebel
negotiators during the previous round of talks, which fell apart on
June 9.
   Despite the breakdown, the Sandinistas said they would maintain
a unilateral cease-fire. The Contras agreed to go along. Since
then, both sides accused the others of violating the fragile truce.
   The cease-fire is to expire at the end of the month.
   The Sandinistas and the Contras began direct, top-level talks on
how to end their nearly 7-year-old war in March. The two sides have
been unable to agree on key points such as democratic reforms in
Nicaragua and Contra disarmament.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
