<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Egypt-SouthernAfrica     06-25 0444</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Egypt-Southern Africa,0459</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Southern Africa Peace Talks to Resume Next Month</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DALIA BALIGH</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CAIRO, Egypt (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Delegates to U.S.-mediated peace talks
trying to settle southern Africa conflicts agreed Saturday to
sponsor another round next month in the United States.
   A communique at the end of two days of talks said the July 11
meeting will be at the ``experts level'' at an undisclosed place in
the United States. It said foreign ministers will not attend.
   ``Further progress was made, and a plan of work was developed
for continuing exchanges at the level of experts to expand on the
progress made in Cairo,'' the communique said.
   It stated the aim of the negotiations as working ``toward a
regional settlement of the conflict in southwestern Africa.''
   The delegates from South Africa, Angola, Cuba and the United
States met Friday and Saturday, seeking a formula to end a 13-year
war in Angola and usher in independence for South-West Africa,
commonly known as Namibia.
   Earlier talks in London and Brazzaville, Congo, last month
failed to achieve settlement.
   In sessions Saturday morning and afternoon, the delegates dealt
with widely divergent proposals presented Friday on how to resolve
the war in Angola and end South African rule in Namibia, conference
sources said.
   About a dozen leaders of the four delegations worked out
communique details in a poolside meeting after full negotiations
apparently bogged down in the hotel conference room.
   The venue for the next talks was apparently the main point at
issue. The Angola-Cuba side was said to be opposed to holding the
next round in an African country like Egypt. They felt South Africa
gained too much politically from having its officials appear where
they normally are barred because of opposition to apartheid.
   South Africa's foreign minister, R.F. Botha, described the
morning's talks as ``good, excellent.'' In keeping with a news
blackout imposed Friday, all delegates declined to discuss
substance.
   Botha told reporters Friday his government was insisting on
Cuban troop withdrawal from Angola as a prerequisite for Namibian
independence.
   At Friday negotiations, Botha demanded Cuba set a date for
pulling out its more than 50,000 troops from Angola, conference
sources said.
   Angola is demanding an end to South African military and
logistical support for Angolan rebels of UNITA, the National Union
for the Total Independence of Angola. UNITA, which has been
fighting the Marxist central government in Luanda, also obtains
arms from the United States.
   In 1978, the United Nations revoked South Africa's League of
Nations mandate in Namibia and called on the Pretoria government to
relinquish the territory. The resolution also provided that Namibia
be put under U.N. trusteeship pending independence.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
