<1ST_LINE>r i AM-NorthernIreland     06-25 0208</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Northern Ireland,0211</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>IRA Says it Used Anti-Aircraft Guns Against Helicopter</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BELFAST, Northern Ireland (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Irish Republican Army on
Saturday said it used high-powered anti-aircraft guns never before
seen in the province to shoot a British army helicopter.
   An IRA statement in Crossmaglen said a 12-man unit used two
12.7mm anti-aircraft guns, three 7.62mm general purpose
machine-guns and rifles Thursday in what it called the IRA's first
successful helicopter downing.
   The outlawed IRA said the British army Lynx helicopter was hit
by armor- piercing and incendiary rounds.
   The Lynx made an emergency landing at Silverbridge in South
Armagh near the border with the Irish Republic and the army said
several rounds had hit the aircraft. One soldier was reported
injured slightly in the rough landing.
   The unit attacked from a hill close to a flight path regularly
used by army helicopters. The IRA men ran with machine guns and a
rocket launcher to finish off their target but could find no trace
of it, the statement said.
   The IRA is believed to have a wide collection of weapons
supplied by Libya for the IRA fight to drive the British out of the
predominantly Protestant province and unite it with the Roman
Catholic Republic of Ireland.
</TEXT>
