<FILEID>AP-NR-06-25-88 1927EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Mexico-Politics     06-25 0494</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Mexico-Politics,0512</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Cardenas Closes Campaign with Giant Downtown Rally</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By SOLL SUSSMAN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MEXICO CITY (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   At least 200,000 supporters of opposition
presidential candidate Cuauhtemoc Cardenas filled the downtown
Zocalo plaza for a massive closing campaign rally Saturday.
   Some polls indicate that Cardenas, candidate of the leftist
coalition Democratic National Front, could finish second to
governing party candidate Carlos Salinas de Gortari in the July 6
election.
   Usually the conservative National Action Party finishes
runner-up to the virtually omnipotent Institutional Revolutionary
Party, or PRI.
   Cardenas, son of the late President Lazaro Cardenas and a
onetime governor of central Michoacan state, broke with the PRI
last year after his Democratic Current campaign for reform from
within was rebuffed.
   He insists he will win, although the PRI never has lost a
presidential election or gubernatorial race in any of Mexico's 31
states since its founding in 1929.
   ``Our victory will be clear and without a shadow of doubt,''
Cardenas told the packed Zocalo.
   ``It can't be hidden. The possibility of an electoral fraud is
in the minds of all Mexicans. We know the evidence of how it is
being prepared,'' he said.
   ``We are struggling for a government of liberties, where we all
might be equal before the law and that no limitation whatsoever
might be imposed on the exercise of the rights of ideas, writing
and publishing, of seeking redress, of transit, of professing
religious belief,'' Cardenas said.
   ``Ours is a clear, defined plan. It is progressive, democratic,
nationalist.''
   Salinas de Gortari and his four opponents are traveling
throughout Mexico in the campaign's closing days. Closing rallies
are set as late as July 2.
   Rosario Ibarra de Piedra, candidate of the tiny Revolutionary
Workers Party called her supporters to the Zocalo on Sunday.
   Manuel J. Clouthier of National Action, known as PAN, attracted
an estimated 30,000 supporters to a closing rally Friday in
Hermosillo, capital of northwestern Sonora state. He plans to hold
his closing Zocalo rally on July 2.
   The fifth candidate is conservative Gumersindo Magana, of the
smallest party competing, the Mexican Democratic Party.
   Cardenas' strong showing prompted an endorsement by Heberto
Castillo of the Mexican Socialist Party. Ballots still will have
both candidates, but votes for Castillo will be counted as votes
for Cardenas.
   Castillo was a featured speaker at Cardenas' Zocalo rally.
   The leftist daily La Jornada estimated on Saturday that the
Zocalo filled to capacity could accommodate 292,297 people. But,
according to the survey done by architects and civil engineers,
none of them would be able to move.
   Most estimates of the Zocalo have been that at capacity it could
hold as many as 1 million people.
   Spectators at Saturday's rally said the plaza, bordered by such
landmarks as the National Palace and the Metropolitan Cathedral,
clearly was filled to capacity and many were standing in
surrounding streets.
   La Jornada's study found that a realistic estimate of a filled
to capacity rally would be 194,865 people.
</TEXT>
