<1ST_LINE>u i AM-Mexico-Blaze 1stLd-writethru a0660 06-25 0632</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Mexico-Blaze, 1st Ld-writethru, a0660,0651</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Death Toll Reaches Seven in Tank Farm Explosion</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: New grafs 1-6 UPDATE with Pemex confirming 7 dead, listing 5
hurt, giving possible fire cause. Picks up 6th graf pvs, Two men .
..</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By CAM ROSSIE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MONTERREY, Mexico (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Three more workers died Saturday from
burns suffered in a fiery explosion at a gasoline supply depot,
bringing to seven the number of confirmed dead in the fire,
hospital officials said.
   The government petroleum monopoly Pemex, which owns the tank
farm, confirmed that seven men died and said five were injured. It
said the blaze may have started when gasoline ``spilled into an
area where soldering work was being done.''
   Neighborhoods surrounding the San Rafael sales agency in
Guadalupe filled up once again as thousands of twice-evacuated
residents returned home.
   Firefighters thought they put out the blazes early Friday and
most residents went home, only to flee again in panic a short time
later when a tank reignited.
   The Constructora Quiroga y Villarreal company was doing
maintenance work on a fire prevention system Thursday when a 2.2
million-gallon gasoline tank exploded and ignited two other tanks.
   It was the second major fire at a Pemex gasoline storage depot
in a month.
   Two men died Saturday of burns at the Hospital 21 in Monterrey,
said Sergio Cardenas, a shift assistant.
   A third man died Saturday at the city's Uiversity Hospital, said
Jose Angel Medellin, an official at the hospital's morgue.
   Company clerk Pedro Salas said 13 workers were accounted for
after having been reported missing after the blast.
   A Pemex news release Saturday said the fire was extinguished at
3 a.m. and ``the security of the area has been totally
re-established.''
   Across from the explosion site, life began returning to normal.
Young boys rode bicycles outside the depot's cement walls. Others
peeked through gaps in the wall to see the charred remains of the
tanks.
   ``It's good to be home,'' said 28-year-old Angel Reymundo
Delgado. He said he spent two nights at one of the emergency
shelters set up after the disaster.
   ``The first night I stayed in a cattle stall so I didn't get
much sleep. But last night was better,'' he said.
   One shelter was at the Guadalupe Exposition Ground, which houses
an annual cattle show and fair.
   Silvia Diaz Martinez, 30, who lives across the street from the
tanks, said she came home to find milk was sour and meat was
spoiled in the refrigerator.
   ``The electricity was off the whole time and didn't come back on
until just after we got home,'' she said.
   Ms. Diaz said she was trapped in her house with her mother,
sister and nephews for several minutes after the explosion as smoke
and fire billowed toward her house.
   No damage to homes was reported.
   Pemex said it set up a special blast investigation team. The
tank farm was temporarily closed for the investigation. Its 23
tanks supplied gasoline and diesel fuel to area gas stations and
other users.
   Witnesses, who spoke on condition of anonymity, said they saw
the top of one tank rupture outward and then collapse. They said
gasoline gushed down the side of the tank and across the ground.
   The witnesses said they suspected the tank may have ruptured
because it was filled far beyond capacity. Pemex has said only
there was a gas leak in a tank. Guadalupe Mayor Adan Lopez said in
an interview that it was his ``obligation'' to ask the state
government to relocate the tank farm because it posed a constant
hazard.
   Pemex closed down a similar tank farm in Chihuahua, capital of
the northern state of the same name, a month ago following an
explosion and daylong fire. No one died in that accident.
</TEXT>
