<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Soviet-Baltic     06-25 0605</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Soviet-Baltic,0624</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Third Baltic Republic Makes Demands For More Autonomy</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ALISON SMALE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MOSCOW (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Intellectuals and Communist officials in the
Baltic republic of Lithuania have followed two other republics in
demanding more autonomy from Moscow as this week's party conference
approaches, the official news agency Tass indicated Saturday.
   The Communist head of the republic of Latvia, meanwhile,
criticized intellectuals who made radical demands for sovereignty
at a stormy meeting of hundreds of writers, artists and scientists
this month.
   A brief report by Tass said a rally of about 10,000 people
called by a group of intellectuals, The Movement To Support
Perestroika, was held in the Lithuanian capital of Vilnius Friday
night.
   Perestroika refers to Mikhail S. Gorbachev's policy of economic
and political reforms.
   Several intellectuals and delegates to the party conference
addressed the crowd, paying ``great attention to the questions of
national culture, language, history and ecology,'' and instructing
delegates what to say in Moscow, Tass said.
   The 19th All-Union Conference of the Communist Party, scheduled
to open Tuesday, will be the first since 1941. Five thousand
delegates will attend.
   A similar meeting in the Estonian capital of Tallinn June 17 is
reported to have attracted 150,000 people, who cheered speeches
demanding the Soviet Union turn into a federation of sovereign
republics.
   Tass did not say if similar demands were raised at the Vilnius
meeting.
   But the Lithuanian Information Center, an emigre group in New
York, said it had learned that a Communist official in Lithuania,
Algirdas Brazauskas, addressed the meeting, calling for a sovereign
Lithuania and for Lithuanian to be made the official language of
the republic.
   The issue of preserving indigenous language and culture in the
Baltic republics has evoked strong emotions as a large number of
ethnic Russians and other ethnic groups migrate into the area.
   The Lithuanian Writers' Union demanded April 4 that
dual-language schools be abolished in the republic and that
Lithuanians outside the republic's borders be taught in Lithuanian.
   Ethnic Estonians are now in a minority in their own republic, a
fact that is fueling concern about the economic, ecological and
other consequences of more than 40 years of Soviet rule.
   The presence of leading Communist party officials at the rally
in Lithuania, as in that in Estonia, indicates that demands in both
republics for more genuine autonomy from Moscow have the official
backing of the party hierarchy.
   However, the head of Latvia's Communist Party, Boris Pugo,
condemned some unofficial groups he accused of taking their cue
from the West.
   In an interview published Saturday in the daily
Sotsialiticheskaya Industriya (Socialist Industry), Pugo said: ``We
cannot close our eyes to the fact that on the background of
perestroika and democratization, recidivists of nationalism and
chauvinism are appearing.''
   ``Some of the so-called `informal groups' are trying to draw
citizens into various actions under speculative, provocative
actions written with the help of Western radio stations,'' Pugo
said.
   He said such groups had been a topic of discussion at a recent
plenum of the Latvian Central Committee that followed the June 1
and 2 meeting of intellectuals in Riga.
   Few details of that meeting have been published in the state-run
media. A report in the weekly Moscow News made clear that debates
had been stormy.
   Pugo said that much of the criticism at the intellectuals'
meeting ``went ahead without the necessary political analysis.''
   A resolution adopted by the intellectuals and published in
Latvia's state-run media June 11 contained a demand to publish the
secret protocol of the Soviet-Nazi pact of 1939. The pact ceded the
three Baltic republics to Moscow, which sent in troops in 1940.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
