<DOCNO> AP880625-0181 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-06-25-88 2110EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a AM-SolarFlares     06-25 0321</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Solar Flares,0332</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Scientists Predict Effects Of Magnetic Storm Will Be Less Intense</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BOULDER, Colo. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A magnetic storm expected to affect global
communications and electric power transmission on Monday may be
less intense than originally thought, scientists said Saturday.
   The National Oceanic and Atmospheric Administration's Space
Environment Laboratory warned Friday about the storm after the
largest solar flare in four years exploded from the sun.
   But NOAA duty forecaster Kent Doggett said Saturday he had
amended his forecast.
   ``We had expected the arrival of energetic protons from the
flare and they did not arrive yet, which makes me suspect that the
amount of energy put out by the flare was not as great as
previously expected,'' he said.
   ``Based on that, I'm not expecting as large of a geomagnetic
disturbance.''
   Mild proton radiation associated with the solar flare had been
expected to reach orbiting spacecraft Saturday.
   Doggett said the level of flare activity was expected to remain
high, but its effects on Earth probably would be felt less strongly
than initially predicted.
   For instance, the magnetic storm had been expected to push
Earth's auroras away from the poles, making the northern lights
visible as far south as the Great Lakes, Boston and England in the
Northern Hemisphere.
   Doggett said Saturday, however, that ``the likelihood of seeing
aurora displays won't be very high, in the continental United
States at least.''
   He said disturbances to electrical power transmission also
probably will be less than expected.
   Officials can't forecast the magnetic storm with certainty,
Doggett said, and the possibility for a strong storm remains as hot
gases and electrically charged particles emitted by the solar flare
hit Earth's magnetic field.
   The phenomenon does not directly threaten life on Earth.
However, it can disrupt shortwave and other communications,
including contact between airliners and ground controllers and
long-distance phone calls.
   The magnetic storm also could cause errors in the orbits of some
satellites.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
