<2ND_LINE>AM-Democrats-Palestinian, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0672,450</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Awad Urges Democrats To Support Two-State Solution in Middle East</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: SUBS 8th graf pvs, bgng: ``But the ...'' to UPDATE with
Jackson camp's proposal being rejected; SUBS 1 graf for grafs 13-14
pvs to UPDATE.</NOTE>
<HEAD>With AM-Democrats-Platform Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By CHRISTOPHER CONNELL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>DENVER (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Mubarak Awad, the American-Palestinian deported
from Israel two weeks ago, urged Democrats on Saturday to call in
their platform for ``a two-state'' solution in the Middle East.
   That would be ``a great victory,'' Awad said at a luncheon
hosted by Margot Kidder, the actress and Jesse Jackson activist, at
the hotel where the Democratic Platform Committee was meeting.
   Awad, an advocate of civil disobedience, urged the Democrats to
address the Palestinian plight in the party platform. Israel
deported Awad on June 13 after 40 days in custody and accused him
of fomenting unrest on the West Bank.
   Awad, a Christian, said he was thinking of converting to Judiasm
if that is the only way for him to get back into Israel and his
native Jerusalem.
   Jesse Jackson has sought to have the Democrats support a
Palestinian homeland in their platform, but Michael Dukakis, the
likely nominee, has resisted.
   The draft platform speaks of ``maintaining the special
relationship with Israel'' while exerting ``new leadership to
deliver the promise of peace and security through negotiations that
has been held out to Israel and its neighbors by the Camp David
Accords.''
   Platform committee member James Zogby, a Jackson adviser and
executive director of the Arab American Institute, offered an
amendment calling for ``peace based on mutual recognition,
territorial compromise and self-determination for Israelis and
Palestinians.''
   However, the proposal was rejected on a voice vote after Sen.
Bob Graham of Florida, speaking for the Dukakis side, said the
party should ``not succumb to the temptation ... of wishing to
impose on other parties what we think the solution should be'' in
the Middle East.
   Awad, 44, who took out American citizenship while a student here
because of visa problems, said he was not discouraged by Dukakis'
refusal to accept the Jackson position.
   Awad said it was ``kind of a political game'' and involves risks
that a President Dukakis could not be expected to take in his first
or second year in office.
   ``I think if at least the platform would say `two-state
solution,' that will be a great victory,'' Awad said.
   Zogby said nine state Democratic parties adopted platforms
endorsing Palestinian self-determination or a homeland. He said
they were: Washington, Vermont, Texas, Oregon, Minnesota, Maine,
Illinois, Iowa and California.
   Zogby noted before the vote that in 1984 a Jackson amendment on
the Middle East drew just 17 votes of support in the platform
committee. Saturday's action was by voice vote, but there were
clearly far more than 17 in favor of the Jackson amendment.
   The luncheon drew Reps. Bill Richardson, D-N.M. and Mary Rose
Oakar, D-Ohio, as well as Richard G. Hatcher, former mayor of Gary,
Ind., and Tony Anaya, former governor of New Mexico.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
