<DOCNO> AP880625-0184 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-06-25-88 2141EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r p AM-Senate-Maryland     06-25 0516</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Senate-Maryland,0529</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>GOP Nominates Foreign Policy Expert for U.S. Senate Run</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOHN ROLL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>GREENBELT, Md. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   State Republican leaders Saturday named
conservative foreign policy expert Alan L. Keyes as the party's
candidate for the U.S. Senate seat held by Democrat Paul Sarbanes,
who is seeking a third term.
   Keyes replaces businessman Thomas Blair, who won the GOP
nomination in the March primary but surprised party officials
earlier this month when he announced he would withdraw from the
race because of unspecified personal and business pressures.
   The special convention of the GOP Central Committee selected
Keyes over Gene Zarwell by a vote of 106-4. Zarwell had finished
well back in a crowded Republican primary this spring.
   In an acceptance speech, Keyes, 37, pledged a vigorous campaign
that would carry a message that ``freedom works.'' In earlier
remarks to the convention, Keyes outlined a philosophy that
government programs are only effective when they empower individual
citizens to solve their own problems.
   Keyes decried what he said was the emergence in the 1960s of a
new liberal philosophy that encourages ``the lie that freedom is a
choice with no responsibility.''
   Keyes' remarks were well received by the party faithful and
seemed, at least for a time, to heal a bitter split in the party.
   ``Keyes' inspiring vision for Maryland's future, plus his
rousing pledge to campaign hard to capture the Senate seat, really
fired up the convention,'' said GOP state Chairman Daniel Fleming.
``With Keyes on the Republican ballot this fall, the Democrats
better not take any voters for granted.''
   Fleming was an earlier backer of Keyes in the days following
Blair's sudden withdrawal announcement. However, other party
leaders mounted a last-minute drive to recruit a better known
candidate. The effort ended late last week when U.S. Rep. Helen
Bentley and a ``mystery'' potential candidate decided not to get in
the race.
   Keyes, a former assistant secretary of state, said he would take
an immediate leave of absence from the American Enterprise
Institute, where he is a resident scholar. Keyes, who has a
doctorate in government from Harvard University, left the foreign
service to serve as an adviser to the presidential campaign of Rep.
Jack Kemp, R-N.Y.
   Most political observers say Keyes faces a long-odds race to
unseat the popular Sarbanes.
   Following his nomination, Keyes held a news conference in which
he supported further aid to the rebels opposing the leftist
government of Nicaragua and funding for the Strategic Defense
Initiative, the ``Star Wars'' space shield proposed by the Reagan
administration.
   Keyes, who is black, said he opposed sanctions against the
white-ruled government of South Africa and the administration's
policy of constructive engagement, policies that he said were a
choice between ``doing the wrong thing or doing nothing at all.''
   Instead, Keyes argued for ``democratic empowerment.'' He
proposed spending $100 million to support black institutions in
South Africa, such as trade unions and professional associations,
to increase the power base of blacks.
   He criticized the U.S. Supreme Court's decision that legalized
abortion, saying that issue should be left to the public to decide.
</TEXT>
