<FILEID>AP-NR-06-25-88 2142EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Cuba-Economy     06-25 0360</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Cuba-Economy,0370</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Cuban Production Fell in 1987</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MEXICO CITY (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Domestic commercial production in Cuba fell
by 3.2 percent in 1987 because of depreciation of the U.S. dollar,
reduced imports and a poor sugar crop, the Cuban government news
agency Prensa Latina reported Saturday.
   In monetary terms, mercantile production was $491.8 million less
than in 1986, the National Bank of Cuba said in a report cited by
the news agency.
   The dispatch, monitored in Mexico City, cited the depreciation
of the dollar against other currencies and government restrictions
against imports from free-market economies for the decline in the
mercantile sector.
   It also blamed a drought that for the third straight year
reduced the sugar harvest, severely affected other crops and
lowered cattle production.
   Sugar production, which Prensa Latina called ``the basis of the
life of the country,'' fell 3.9 percent last year. The sector's
poor performance accounted for 13 percent of the drop in economic
production, it said.
   Non-sugar production suffered a 3.1 percent drop in 1987 because
of a shortage of foreign reserves needed to purchase supplies from
abroad, the bank report said. Imports dropped 20 percent from 1986,
it said.
   Cuba's total foreign trade in 1987 was unchanged from the
previous year. The Prensa Latina dispatch did not provide a figure.
The country's foreign trade deficit shrank by 1.5 percent, it said.
   A severe dollar shortage forced the government to ask Western
creditor nations this year to reschedule its foreign debt over 15
years and ask for a 5-year grace period, according to a National
Bank document made public in March.
   The document, released by Freedom House, a conservative human
rights group, listed Cuba's debt to Western creditors at $5.5
billion.
   World oil sales are conducted in U.S. dollars. The Soviet Union
has been sending proceeds of Soviet oil export sales to Cuba, and
so the dollar's decline in value has hit Cuba's foreign reserves.
   The decline in mercantile production ``did not affect the
quality of life of the population,'' the National bank report said.
Life expectancy for men on the island nation was 72.66 years, and
76.1 years for women in 1987, Prensa Latina said.
</TEXT>
