<FILEID>AP-NR-06-25-88 2155EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i AM-LatinAmerica     06-25 0477</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Latin America,0489</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Foreign Ministers Discuss Latin American Economic Integration</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By SERGIO CARRASCO</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>OAXACA, Mexico (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The foreign ministers from seven leading
Latin American nations opened a weekend meeting Saturday aimed at
increasing regional economic and trade ties.
   The Group of Eight _ including Argentina, Brazil, Colombia,
Mexico, Peru, Uruguay and Venezuela _ also will draw up an agenda
for a summit meeting of their presidents in the fall at the beach
resort of Punta del Este, in Uruguay.
   Only Panama is absent. Its role will be discussed Monday at a
continuation of the meeting in Mexico City, 300 miles north of
Oaxaca.
   Panama was suspended from the group at its last meeting in
February, shortly after military leader Gen. Manuel Antonio Noriega
was indicted in the United States on drug trafficking charges.
Noriega engineered the ouster of President Eric Arturo Delvalle
after Delvalle tried to fire him.
   A Mexican Foreign Ministry statement confirmed that Foreign
Minister Jorge Ritter of Panama will be present at the Mexico City
session, which also will include a review of the Central American
situation.
   The meeting in Oaxaca, a picturesque colonial city in southern
Mexico, is intended mostly to explore ways of trying to build a
Latin American common market, a project which has been discussed
for more than two decades.
   Recent efforts by Argentina, Brazil and Uruguay indicate a
renewed interest in a common market or free trade zone. The three
countries last year signed accords breaking down trade barriers and
increasing trade among them.
   Mexico, Venezuela, Colombia and Peru have shown signs of
interest in the idea of reviving Latin American trade partnership,
spurred mostly by their huge foreign debts which are making dollars
increasingly scarce.
   Mexico is building a huge pipeline for the Argentine government.
   ``Integration is one of the issues we will discuss with great
confidence and a great sense of realism,'' Carlos Perez del
Castillo, secretary of the Latin American Economic System, told
reporters upon his arrival in Oaxaca on Friday night. ``We are
convinced that the solution to our problems will not come from
outside, we have to seek it ourselves.''
   His multigovernment regional organization has been doing studies
on the project.
   Julio Londono, a representative from Colombia, called the
meeting ``very important, because for the first time the directors
of the organizations of Latin American integration (studies) will
be among us.''
   Mexico, Venezuela, Colombia and Panama formed the Contradora
group in 1983 in a so-far unsuccessful effort to find negotiated
solutions to the Central American conflicts in Nicaragua, Guatemala
and El Salvador.
   Argentina, Brazil, Peru and Uruguay joined the Contadora group
three years ago. They since have become known as the Group of Eight
and met in the most extensive presidential summit in Latin America
in more than 20 years last November in the Pacific coastal resort
of Acapulco.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880625-0190 </DOCNO>
