<FILEID>AP-NR-06-25-88 2208EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u i AM-Yugoslavia-Vision     06-25 0227</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Yugoslavia-Vision,0233</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Thousands Converge on Site Where Apparition Was Reported</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BELGRADE, Yugoslavia (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Tens of thousands of Roman Catholics
from many lands converged on Medjugorje on Saturday to celebrate
the seventh anniversary of a reported apparition of the Virgin
Mary, Tanjug news agency said.
   Medjugorje, a village in central Yugoslavia, has become a
religious shrine since 1981, when six children _ four boys and two
irls _ said they saw the Madonna while they were tending sheep on
nearby hills.
   Although the Vatican never formally accepted the Medjugorje
shrine, the pilgrims, including sick and disabled people, have been
gathering each day in the village to watch for the Madonna to
reappear. They also want to listen to the six Yugoslavs, now
adults, communicate with the Virgin Mary.
   About 10 million people from Yugoslavia and abroad have visited
the site.
   ``A large number of today's visitors came from the United States
and Australia,'' said the state-operated Tanjug agency.
   Communist Yugoslavia has a reputation for relative liberalism,
but the idea of thousands of Christians turning the village into a
religious shrine initially caused great apprehension among
authorities.
   After six years of hesitation, however, state-run companies
decided to try to capitalize on the influx of foreign visitors.
   A modern hotel complex, along with hundreds of private inns,
were built to accommodate an unprecedented tourist boom in the
region.
</TEXT>
