<DOCNO> AP880625-0192 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-06-25-88 2215EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u a AM-Drought-HeatRdp 2ndLd-Writethru a0670 06-25 1063</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Drought-Heat Rdp, 2nd Ld - Writethru, a0670,1082</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Drought May Block Sime Fireworks, Mississippi Barges Moving Again</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: SUBS grafs 7-8, `High temperature...five deaths.' with 3
grafs to UPDATE highs, number of deaths; picks up 9th graf pvs
`Chicago public...' SUBS grafs 10-12, `Several Wisconsin...was
hospitalized.' with 4 grafs to ADD Wisconsin fire, UPDATE with
spread of Montana fire; picks up 13th graf pvs, `A grass...'
INSERTS graf after 15th graf pvs `However, the...' to ADD planned
aerial survey of Mississippi; picks up 16th graf pvs, `Some
shippers...' SUBS last graf with 2 grafs to ADD Colorado tornadoes,
UPDATE number of deaths.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By ROGER PETTERSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Alabama's governor asked people Saturday to pray for rain to end
the drought, Milwaukee officials considered whether to forgo Fourth
of July fireworks because of fire danger and barges moved again on
the Mississippi.
   Temperatures hissed to record highs, but not in the same places
as over the past week. Thanks to a cold front, temperatures across
the northern Plains were 15 to 25 degrees cooler than Friday, and
most of the records were in the Ohio Valley, with relief there
expected Sunday.
   The depleted lower Mississippi River was blocked to shipping
again Saturday by barges running aground.
   Showers and thunderstorms were widespread Friday night and early
Saturday across eastern Texas and southern Arkansas into the
central Gulf coast.
   ``I ask that God-fearing people across our state put aside time
next Wednesday to pray that God will send life-giving rain to our
state and our nation,'' Alabama Gov. Guy Hunt, a Primitive Baptist
lay preacher, said Saturday in his weekly radio address.
   A few locations in the middle Mississippi Valley never left the
80s overnight, including Ottumwa, Iowa, at 80 and St. Louis, Mo.,
at 82.
   High temperature records started falling early. It wasn't even
noon when the temperature at Milwaukee passed the previous record
of 95 and kept on rising to a high of 100. Flint, Mich., tied its
record of 94 at 10:45 a.m. and continued on to 101. The mercury hit
100 by noon at Chicago, and reached a record 103, making this June
the first there with three 100-plus days since records began in
1873.
   Peoria, Ill., hit a high of 105 and Fort Wayne, Ind., hit 106,
the second highest reading in the country behind 110 at Phoenix,
Ariz.
   The heat wave has been blamed for six deaths.
   Chicago public health officials said people could use
air-conditioned public libraries and centers for the aging as
cooling shelters Saturday. ``We are monitoring the situation and
will open more shelters if needed,'' said Dr. David Marder, a
health department official.
   Fires fanned by hot, dry winds burned at least 1,200 acres in
south-central Wisconsin, destroying rural homes, chasing campers
from state parks and forcing the temporary closure of a 20-mile
stretch of Interstate 90-94.
   Several Wisconsin communities already have decided to do without
fireworks this year because of the fire threat, and Milwaukee
County officials planned to decide by Monday whether to cancel the
aerial displays, said parks director M. Brigid Sullivan. One show
will go on because the rockets will be shot over Lake Michigan.
   ``This is the first time they have been canceled,'' James Myers,
city clerk in Monroe, Wis., said of the fireworks. ``It's sad. But
it would be kind of sad to see your house burn up too.''
   A forest fire exacerbated by the heat and lack of rain burned at
least 34,000 acres of grass and forest in southeastern Montana and
a small area of western South Dakota. The blaze burned out of
control on its northwest perimeter despite the efforts of 650
firefighters, and Bureau of Land Management officials dropped
earlier forecasts that the fire might be contained by Sunday night.
   A grass and forest fire in northeastern Wyoming was contained
Saturday after burning more than 6,000 acres. Shoshone National
Forest officials in northwest Wyoming said a fire in prime
timberland had burned about 550 acres.
   At Memphis, Tenn., a 30-mile-long towboat and barge traffic jam
on the dwindling Mississippi River was clearing up Saturday. The
river was closed there from Tuesday until a dredge finished
clearing a channel on Friday. Southbound barges were cleared during
the night before northbound traffic was allowed to start through.
   However, the increasingly shallow lower Mississippi was blocked
again when barges ran aground near Greenville, Miss., and Helena,
Ark., and about 20 miles north of Osceola, Ark., Coast Guard Chief
Petty Officer Dean Jones said Saturday.
   On Sunday, Assistant Army Secretary for Civil Works Robert W.
Page is to make an aerial inspection of the river ``because we have
continued groundings that have blocked traffic,'' said David Rich,
a spokesman for the Army Corps of Engineers in Memphis.
   Some shippers are switching to the relatively new
Tennessee-Tombigbee Waterway that runs from Mobile, Ala., to the
Tennessee River which connects to the Ohio River. Barge traffic on
the waterway has increased by 50 percent during the past few days
because of low water on the Mississippi, the Army Corps of
Engineers said.
   Sam Green, a spokesman with the Corps in Mobile, said the
Tenn-Tom is ``pretty well drought-proof,'' and has been unaffected
by the lack of rain. However, it adds distance and is too narrow to
accept the large tows of barges common on the Mississippi and has
never met original predictions of how much it would be used.
   More than 5.75 inches of rain was reported overnight at Leakey,
Texas, and a flash flood warning was issued in Texas for southern
Real and northern Uvalde counties.
   Some parts of Louisiana got more than an inch of rain. ``We need
an inch of rain every week for the next three or four weeks, just
to put the moisture back into the subsoil where it should be,''
said cotton grower Jim Harper of Cheneyville, La.
   Birmingham, Ala., got its first measurable rain in 30 days and
nearby Childersburg had torrential rain that beat down cornstalks,
covered streets and lawns and overflowed from ditches.
   A line of intense thunderstorms blew into Colorado, sent
temperatures plummeting and spawned four tornadoes, including one
that took the roof off a farm building near Loveland. Heavy rain
flooded some intersections in Denver. The heat has been blamed for
four deaths in St. Louis, Mo.; one in Thomas County, Ga.; and one
in East St. Louis, Ill.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880625-0193 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-06-25-88 2221EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u a AM-LawyersCommittee 1stLd-Writethru a0579 06-25 0747</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Lawyers Committee, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0579,0760</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>20 Years of Lawyering for Progess in Civil Rights</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: INSERTS 1 graf after 8th graf, ``A Harvard ...,'' to UPDATE
with Kennedy's speech to committee; picks up 9th graf, ``The
committee's ...''</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By ALAN COOPERMAN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BOSTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Some days, Laura Steinberg works for the Boston
Bar Association's Committee for Civil Rights. Other days, she
opposes it.
   Steinberg and other attorneys at Boston's big law firms have
been moving back and forth across that fence for two decades. On
one side, they butter their bread. On the other, they soothe their
souls.
   The committee, which celebrated its 20th anniversary Saturday,
assigns lawyers to represent black, Asian and Hispanic clients in
discrimination cases. The lawyers volunteer their time, and 26
Boston law firms donate most of the committee's $400,000 annual
budget.
   Those same firms, however, also represent many of the powerful
organizations and individuals that the committee sues. To be sure,
the lawyers follow ethical guidelines intended to prevent conflicts
of interest, and no firm represents both sides in a single case.
   But the irony of Boston's top lawyers and law firms donating
time and money to take on their establishment clients is obvious _
and the committee's staff isn't shy about discussing it.
   ``We've been successful by being part of the establishment, but
at the same time being an organization that continually challenges
the establishment,'' said Barbara R. Arnwine, the committee's
executive director.
   ``It has its awkward and also its amusing moments,'' said
Steinberg, who is simultaneously suing the Boston Housing Authority
on behalf of the committee and defending the city's Water and Sewer
Commission against a suit filed for the committee by another lawyer.
   A Harvard Law School graduate and partner in the firm of
Sullivan & Worcester, Steinberg said she likes taking cases for the
committee because they are often class-action suits involving
``meaty'' constitutional issues.
   ``Twenty-five years ago, there was no Civil Rights Act, no
Voting Rights Act, no Fair Housing Act, and precious little civil
rights,'' Sen. Edward M. Kennedy, D-Mass., told the group at its
anniversary dinner Saturday night. ``The Lawyers' Committee can
point with pride to your indispensable role in the writing of these
laws _ and your equally indispensible role in securing their strong
enforcement.''
   The committee's best-known suit was probably the Boston school
desegregation case of 1972, which resulted in the court order for
racial integration of the city's schools.
   But the group also has challenged hiring practices in the police
and fire departments. It brought a 1976 federal case that
established the obligation of employers to maintain a work
environment free of racial or sexual harassment. It has represented
victims of racially motivated violence. And it has been
particularly active in the fair housing arena.
   John Taylor Williams, a partner in the firm of Palmer & Dodge,
said there are some self-interested reasons why old-line firms may
support the committee _ particularly recruiting.
   ``Whatever people may say about pin-striped lawyers, there are
still a lot of people who go to law school motivated in part by a
desire to bring about social change,'' he said. ``You can often
recruit better lawyers to your firm because they know they'll have
the opportunity to get involved in civil rights cases.''
   But, Williams said, most of the city's big law firms also
recognize that it is ``in everyone's interest'' to keep Boston
``the most civilized city in America,'' and that ``part of being
civilized is not discriminating on the basis of race.''
   Formally named the Lawyers' Committee for Civil Rights Under the
Law, the group was formed by the Boston Bar Association in the wake
of the riots following the assassination of the Rev. Martin Luther
King in 1968.
   It is one of several regional chapters of the national Lawyers'
Committee for Civil Rights, which had been established in 1963 at
the instigation of President John F. Kennedy and Attorney General
Robert Kennedy.
   ``At a time in which there's been a loss of momentum on civil
rights issues in the public sector _ under the Reagan
administration in particular _ the lawyers' committee has
maintained the momentum of the '60s and '70s,'' said Superior Court
Judge J. Harold Flannery, who worked for the committee before going
on the bench in 1984.
   ``Its commitment is more than lip service, more than just
rhetorical,'' he added. ``They have jumped in and done the actual,
nitty-gritty legal work, at considerable risk of unpopularity.''
</TEXT>
