<1ST_LINE>r a AM-Elderly-Prescriptions     06-25 0507</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Elderly-Prescriptions,0524</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Newspaper Probe Finds Elderly Are Victims of Prescription Blunders</HEAD>
<DATELINE>PHOENIX, Ariz. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Two million elderly Americans become ill
or die each year because of reactions to drugs often prescribed
unnecessarily and sometimes taken in potentially deadly doses, a
newspaper reported Sunday.
   The Arizona Republic said it found through a five-month
investigation in 13 states that many institutionalized elderly are
given mind-altering drugs, that thousands have died after getting
wrong dosages and that others were used as guinea pigs in drug
experiments.
   The newspaper said in the first installment of a seven-day
series it had found that about one in every seven doses of medicine
the elderly receive are in error.
   Of the $9 billion people over 65 spend annually on prescription
drugs, about $2 billion is considered unnecessary, the Republic
said, citing federal records.
   Officials have estimated the total health-care bill for wrongly
medicating the elderly at $21 billion a year, the newspaper said.
   Rep. Claude Pepper, D-Fla., chairman of the House Committee on
Aging, called the problem ``a national outrage.''
   `Those figures are staggering,'' Pepper said. ``It shows how
callous some people are regarding the elderly. All they want to do
is placate them until they pass away.''
   In Arizona, some nursing homes have made medication errors more
than half the time they give drugs, the Republic said. The national
Health Care Finance Administration considers a 5 percent error rate
acceptable.
   The newspaper said it also found that:
   _ Some doctors and drug companies around the country used
elderly patients as test subjects for experiments, sometimes
involving new, unlicensed drugs, without obtaining the patients'
informed consent.
   _ Numerous medical studies conducted since the mid-1970s show
the aged have been improperly given tranquilizers, hypnotic drugs
and potent antipsychotic drugs that left thousands severely ill,
hospitalized or dead.
   _ Many thousands of elderly who are overmedicated fall,
suffering debilitating, sometimes fatal injuries.
   _ Most medical schools have inadequately trained doctors,
particularly in geriatric pharmacology and geriatrics.
   _ Many doctors do not want to treat the elderly, nor do they
find it financially desirable to care for them in nursing homes
because of strict federal limitations on Medicare reimbursements.
   _ Despite congressional orders five years ago to do so, many
drug manufacturers still have not tested most of their drugs on the
elderly to determine effects and have failed to recognize the need
for a category specifying geriatric doses in labeling and package
inserts.
   The Republic also said doctors are ignorant of the extent of
medication-related deaths partly because autopsies are rarely
performed on the elderly, leaving physicians often to guess the
cause.
   Don Goddard of Sun City, who founded the senior citizens segment
of the St. Luke's Medical Center chemical-dependency unit in
Phoenix in 1974, estimated that 30 percent of the patients he met
in 10 years directing the program were addicted to prescription
medications. Most were women.
   ``That is the drug problem with older people,'' said Goddard,
84. ``We don't take heroin or cocaine. It would be a news story if
we did.''
</TEXT>
