<2ND_LINE>AM-Iceland, 2nd Ld-Writethru, a0711,0532</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Iceland's Woman President Defeats Woman Rival</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: SUBS 5th graf pvs, She did ... CORRECTING age from 57 to 58;
ADDS background on president, including non-political nature of
office. No pickup</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By ANDRES MAGNUSSON</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>REYKJAVIK, Iceland (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Incumbent Vigdis Finnbogadottir gained
an overwhelming victory over another woman candidate in Saturday's
presidential election in her bid for a third four-year term.
   Poll officials said early Sunday that with 47.3 percent of the
ballot counted, Mrs. Finnbogadottir won about 95 percent of the
vote and her rival, Sigrun Thorsteinsdottir, had the remaining 5
percent.
   The officials said about 75 percent of Iceland's 173,800
eligible voters cast ballots.
   In conceding defeat in a television interview, Mrs.
Thorsteinsdottir said the election had been a great victory for all
``democratic and freedom-loving people in Iceland'' as opposed to
the ``autocratic and monarchist'' supporters of the establishment.
   She did not congratulate the 58-year-old president on her
victory but offered herself as a presidential aide, saying it was
``obvious that (the present) aides are unfit for the job.''
   Sources close to the president, speaking on condition of
anonymity, said they could hardly envisage a situation where Mrs.
Thorsteinsdottir's advice would be sought.
   President Finnbogadottir said in a TV interview she was
delighted b the results and that any incumbent president would be
satisfied with such overwhelming support.
   Final results were expected later Sunday.
   Vigdis, as the president is popularly known among the 250,000
Icelanders, was the world's first democratically elected woman
state president, when she defeated three men in 1980.
   She was re-elected unopposed in 1984 and was host at the
Reykjavik superpower summit in October 1986.
   Mrs. Thorsteinsdottir has been active within the Humanist Party,
which so far has failed to get a representative elected to the
Althing, the world's oldest parliament.
   Mrs. Thorsteinsdottir, 46, ran on a platform of giving the
presidential office a more active role.
   Mrs. Finnbogadottir maintained that the presidency was created
as a ceremonial post and should remain so.
   The president refused to run an active campaign and repeatedly
refused an invitation from her rival to a public debate.
   Real power in Iceland rests with the prime minister, Thorsteinn
Palsson.
   Saturday was the first time an incumbent president has faced a
re-election challenge since Iceland, formerly under Danish rule,
became a republic in 1944.
   Icelandic women recently won greater political power. The
left-wing Women's Alliance _ which made history in 1983 when it
became the first feminist movement in the world to win
parliamentary seats _ doubled its representation to six seats in
last year's general election.
   The Independence Party is Iceland's largest political party and
a dominant force in the three-party coalition government.
   Mrs. Finnbogadottir, a divorcee, was formerly director of the
Reykjavik Theater Company.
   She had no formal involvement in politics when she was first
elected, but was generally regarded as being the preferred
candidate of the Icelandic left, notably because of her opposition
to the United States' military presence in Iceland at the North
Atlantic Treaty Organization base at Keflavik.
   The president is traditionally a non-political figure.
</TEXT>
