<1ST_LINE>r a AM-SavimbiAward     06-25 0466</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Savimbi Award,0479</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Protesters Meet Angolan Leader On Arrival In Mississippi</HEAD>
<DATELINE>FAYETTE, Miss. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Angolan rebel leader Jonas Savimbi
received an award named for a slain black civil rights leader
Saturday but was criticized by anti-apartheid protesters and the
civil rights leader's widow.
   Savimbi, 53, the president of the National Union for the Total
Independence of Angola (UNITA), accepted the Medgar Evers
Humanitarian Award from Fayette Mayor Charles Evers, brother of the
civil rights leader.
   The award ceremony had to be moved inside city hall from the
steps outside to avoid heckling by people protesting Savimbi's ties
with white-ruled South Africa, which supports UNITA's struggle
against Angola's Marxist government and has a policy of racial
segregation known as apartheid.
   ``The Angolan people are not asking for pity, they are asking
for understanding because they have proven themselves good
fighters. We want freedom in South Africa,'' Savimbi said. ``We are
going to do it. We need your support. Give us that support.''
   ``On behalf of all of us freedom loving people in Mississippi
and Fayette, whether they like it or not, we feel that you are our
hero,'' Evers said in presenting the award.
   Myrlie Evers, Medgar's widow, who is remarried and living in Los
Angeles, said Thursday that the choice of Savimbi was politically
motivated and that her late husband would not have approved.
   Medgar Evers was field director of the National Association for
the Advancement of Colored People when he was gunned down in front
of his Jackson home in 1963.
   Earlier Saturday, about 40 protesters shouting anti-apartheid
and anti-Savimbi epithets gathered outside a Jackson motel where
Savimbi had scheduled a news conference. They were met by a
Bible-toting, pro-Savimbi group shouting, ``We are against
communism.''
   Evers failed to calm the protest and eight uniformed Jackson
police officers forced both groups out of the hotel without
incident.
   ``I hate apartheid because apartheid is the black people being
oppressed,'' Savimbi said during the news conference. He added,
however, that he believed ``progress in Namibia and South Africa
depends on peace in Angola.''
   South Africa has refused to withdraw from neighboring Namibia,
in defiance of a United Nations resolution, because of the presence
of Cuban troops in Angola that support the government there.
   ``I am not fighting a South African struggle. I am fighting the
struggle for freedom, for dignity of the black people in Angola,''
Savimbi said.
   Charles Evers compared Savimbi's struggle with that of American
blacks in the 1960s and said his brother would have approved of the
award.
   ``Dr. Savimbi is a man who has fought for freedom,'' Evers said.
``He fought the Russians, the communists and the Cubans. I've been
there. I've seen the work he's done.''
   Savimbi will go to Washington next week and meet with President
Reagan on Thursday.
</TEXT>
