<HEAD>Dukakis Gets 13 Of Final 18 Iowa Delegates</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: SUBS 2nd graf pvs, bgng: ``With the ...'' to UPDATE delegate
totals to show Dukakis has delegates previously uncommitted.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By TOM SEERY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>AMES, Iowa (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Massachusetts Gov. Michael Dukakis, who
finished third in Iowa's precinct caucuses more than four months
ago, picked up 13 of 18 delegates elected Saturday at the Iowa
Democratic Convention.
   With the 13 new delegates in his camp, Dukakis had 49 members of
the state's 61-member delegation, while Jesse Jackson had 12.
   After launching the Democratic presidential nominating process
with the state caucuses in February, Iowa on Saturday became the
last state in the nation to complete its slate of delegates to the
Democratic National Convention in August.
   Iowa Democratic Party Chairwoman Bonnie Campbell told delegates
at the party's state convention that the state has ``a process that
all of us should be proud of, and those who might like to see Iowa
quietly slip by the political wayside will not be so lucky.''
   Ms. Campbell has promised to lead the fight against any move to
push Iowa from its first-in-the-nation status.
   Jesse Jackson, who finished second to Dukakis in the nationwide
delegate count, has said he will push for a new system to give
larger states a greater voice in the early nominating process.
   Some Democrats in other states have grumbled that Iowa does not
deserve to kick off the party's nominating process because the
state has not been carried by a Democratic presidential candidate
since 1964.
   ``While our caucuses have had more than their fair share of
criticisms, we have shown the world that Iowa is a place where
candidates can come to talk with real, live people about building a
better world, rather than spending big money on television campaign
commercials,'' Ms. Campbell said.
</TEXT>
