<FILEID>AP-NR-06-25-88 2317EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a AM-BareBreasts     06-25 0307</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Bare Breasts,0315</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Women Bare Their Breasts in Rochester Park For Third Consecutive
Year</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RANDOLPH PICHT</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ROCHESTER, N.Y. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   About 30 women removed their shirts in a
city park and bared their breasts for several hours to protest a
state law allowing men, but not women, to remove their shirts in
public.
   It was the third year in a row for the protest, which is
becoming an annual rite of summer.
   ``We intend to continue this until the law is changed,'' said
Ramona Santorelli, a protest organizer. ``This is a day to
celebrate the acceptance of women going shirtless.''
   Bare-chested women played softball and volleyball, and lounged
in the sun at Genesee Valley Park.
   Santorelli launched the effort three years ago after a security
guard ordered her to put a shirt on while she was sunbathing in an
uncrowded city park.
   The first protest in 1986 attracted a large crowd of gawkers and
hecklers who taunted the seven women who removed their shirts and
were arrested.
   The women were acquitted of misdemeanor charges, but their
victory was a partial one. Judge Herman Walz ruled it was
permissible for the women to remove their shirts in public as a
form of protest, but said it would be illegal for any other reason.
   Last year, about 25 women bared their breasts and enjoyed their
picnic without interruption from onlookers or the police. Saturday
was a repeat of that experience.
   The event was a bit befuddling for Patrick Massaquoi, a native
of Liberia attending a family reunion in a picnic shelter near the
topless women.
   ``Looks to me what you have over there is Western society
degenerating,'' Massaquoi said. ``In Africa, this is the custom and
native way and you can understand it. But what's good for Africa is
not necessarily good for Rochester.''
</TEXT>
