<FILEID>AP-NR-06-25-88 2318EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a AM-Deaths 1stLd-Writethru a0683 06-25 0563</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Deaths, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0683,0579</2ND_LINE>
<NOTE>Eds: AMs separates moved as a0694 on Marta Abba, a0689 on
Hemingway.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Marta Abba</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MILAN, Italy (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Marta Abba, a leading Italian stage
performer of the 1920s and `30s and the favorite actress of
Sicilian playwright Luigi Pirandello, died on her 88th birthday
Friday after suffering a stroke.
   Abba entered Milan's drama school when she was 15 and began her
career in 1923 with the stage company of director Ettore Paladini.
She drew acclaim the following year in Virgilio Talli's production
of Chekhov's ``Gabbiano.''
   In 1925, she became the lead actress for Pirandello, who won the
1934 Nobel Prize in literature and is considered a top figure in
20th-century European theater.
   She became his lifetime companion and Pirandello wrote several
plays specifically for her, including ``Come Tu Mi Vuoi'' (As You
Desire Me) in 1930.
   Pirandello died in 1936. Two years later, Abba married an
American, S.A. Millikin, grandson of a Cleveland steel baron,
retired and settled in the United States.
   After the marriage broke up, she moved back to Milan in 1953,
returning briefly to the stage. She had been on the board of the
Institute of Pirandello Studies and Contemporary Italian Theater
since 1962.
</TEXT>
<BYLINE>Byra Hemingway</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>KETCHUM, Idaho (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Byra L. ``Puck'' Hemingway,
daughter-in-law of author Ernest Hemingway and mother of actresses
Mariel and Margaux Hemingway, died Friday at her home after an
extended illness. She was 66.
   Mrs. Hemingway, the wife of author, businessman and outdoorsman
Jack Hemingway of Ketchum, was born in Pocatello. She worked as a
secretary during World War II on the U.S. Army Corps of Engineers'
Alcon Highway Project and later worked as a purchasing agent for
Sun Valley Co. and United Airlines.
   She married Jack Hemingway, son of the Nobel Prize-winning
author, on June 25, 1949, in Paris. The couple settled in Ketchum,
where Ernest Hemingway committed suicide in 1961.
</TEXT>
<HEAD>Alexander Primm</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ST. LOUIS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Alexander T. Primm III, former general manager
and senior vice president of the Pulitzer Publishing Co., publisher
of the St. Louis Post-Dispatch, died Friday following a heart
attack. He was 73.
   Primm began with the Post-Dispatch in 1936, serving the
newspaper in various capacities for more than 40 years before he
retired in 1979.
   In addition to his duties with the Post-Dispatch, Primm was a
vice president and director of KSD-TV while the St. Louis station
was owned by Pulitzer. He also held high positions with other
Pulitzer media companies.
</TEXT>
<HEAD>Lucy Rush</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SEATTLE (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Lucy Rush, longtime star of Safeway Stores
commercials, died Friday of head injuries suffered when she was
struck by a ladder that fell from a passing truck. She was 40.
   Ms. Rush did as many as seven commercials a week for the grocery
chain and appeared at many store openings, and all three of her
children appeared on commercials with her at one time or another,
said her agent, Lola Hallowell.
   Born in St. Paul, Minn., she graduated from Harvard University
and sought acting opportunities in New York, but returned to
Minnesota. There, she met her husband, Mark, when auditioning for
an acting job.
   They married in 1972 and moved to Seattle, where her husband got
a job as stage manager for the Seattle Repertory Theater.
   She is survived by her husband, her mother, two sisters and a
brother and three children.
</TEXT>
