<HEAD>Report: Bess Myerson Signed Confession</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Bess Myerson signed a confession admitting she
stole more than $40 worth of merchandise from a Pennsylvania
department store, according to a published report.
   The former Miss America and television personality has pleaded
innocent to the May 27 shoplifting charge filed after she allegedly
left the Hills department store in South Williamsport with nail
polish, earrings, shoes and batteries.
   South Williamsport Police Chief Charles Smith said Myerson had
signed a confession on a department store form, the Daily News
reported in its Sunday editions.
   The newspaper said investigative reports indicate Myerson, 63,
was caught in the store parking lot with goods stashed in her
pocketbook and a shopping bag.
   The newspaper said Myerson, a former New York City cultural
affairs commissioner, begged store guards to let her off, saying,
``Can't I please just pay for the stuff?''
   ``You don't understand. I'm already in so much trouble, and I
have to go to federal court,'' she reportedly said.
   Myerson has been charged with trying to influence the judge in
the divorce case of her boyfriend, contractor Carl ``Andy''
Capasso, who is serving four years in prison on a tax evasion
conviction.
   The newspaper said the confession was witnessed by two people.
   The confession also noted that she was carrying $160 at the
times of the arrest and that she is worth an estimated $16 million,
the Daily News said.
   Myerson's attorney, Scott Gardner, who said he expects his
client to be exonerated in the case, did not return several calls
to his office, the newspaper said.
