<FILEID>AP-NR-06-25-88 2334EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Egypt-US     06-25 0587</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Egypt-US,0608</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Military Refuses Comment on U.S. Smuggling Charges</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CAIRO, Egypt (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Egyptian military on Saturday refused
comment on allegations that two Egyptian army colonels were
involved in a plot to export illegally U.S. technology for
sophisticated missile and other systems.
   Cairo newspapers reported the U.S. charges in their Sunday
editions, but did not mention that two of the suspects were army
colonels. The state-run media ignored the story.
   ``All I have is, no comment,'' Defense Ministry spokesman Col.
Nagy el-Tohamy told The Associated Press by telephone.
   The Al-Ahram newspaper, a frequent conduit for government policy
statements, was the only paper with editorial comment on the case.
It characterized the suspects as innocent victims swept up in an
attempt to damage relations between the United States and Egypt.
   U.S. Ambassador Frank G. Wisner said U.S.-Egyptian ties were too
vital to be damaged by the affair.
   ``I think there is a very important relationship between the
United States and Egypt and problems can be managed,'' Wisner said.
   The state-run Middle East News Agency did not report the story
for 15 hours after it broke.
   Its eventual dispatch from Washington quoted the Washington Post
for its information, but didn't mention the army colonels or a
military transport plane the U.S. Justice Department charged was
being used to smuggle contraband out of the country.
   The official Cairo Radio ignored the story all day Saturday, as
did Egyptian Television in its evening English, French and Arabic
newscasts.
   U.S. Attorney David Levi told a news conference in Sacramento,
Calif., Friday night that the two Egyptian officers and three
Americans illegally routed sensitive military material to Europe
and the Middle East without required export licenses.
   One of the Americans cited is an Egyptian-born rocket expert who
allegedly received $1 million ``from Egyptian sources'' for his
role, a fact also omitted from Egyptian press reports.
   Neither of the military men were arrested. Levi said Col. Hussam
Yossef was in Austria, and Col. Mohamed Abdella Mohamed was
detained but released after claiming diplomatic immunity.
   Egyptian press reports did not name the men but said one worked
in the purchasing office of the Egyptian Embassy in Washington.
   In its front-page commentary, Al-Ahram said the Justice
Department announcement of charges was unclear, imprecise and
incomplete. ``There is a serious attempt aimed at harming the
Egyptian-American relations in the first place,'' Al-Ahram said.
   ``We all know that the American market is open, where people buy
and export all strategic items and other things ... Some people may
not think of getting prior exporting permission, since the goods
could be bought freely.''
   The smuggling ring was charged Friday with illegal export and
money laundering, and conspiring to ship hundreds of pounds of a
substance called carbon-carbon, or carbon composite, to Europe and
Egypt.
   The special carbon material, developed in the United States, is
used extensively in high-speed aircraft, missiles and rockets
because it has a low visibility level to radar and is heat
resistant.
   The carbon is on the federal restricted list, and requires
special licenses to be exported.
   ``It is not the manner of Egyptian institutions to violate the
rules, carry out espionage operations or steal secret military
documents from the Pentagon or anywhere else,'' Al-Ahram said.
   Al-Ahram denied a plane was flown to the United States to bring
back contraband. ``Many Egyptian planes arrive in the United States
to carry military equipment that Egypt gets from America,'' the
newspaper said.
   Egypt receives about $1.3 billion a year in military aid from
the United States.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
