<1ST_LINE>u w AM-Boeing-Aloha     06-25 0472</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Boeing-Aloha,460</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Report: Boeing Warned Aloha Of Corrosion Problems Prior To Breakup
Incident</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Aloha Airlines was warned five months before
the in-flight breakup of one of its jets that the airline had 10
planes with significant corrosion problems and needed a new
maintenance program, according to a published report.
   The Washington Post reported in its Sunday editions that the
Seattle-based Boeing Co. urged Aloha to replace corroded fuselage
panels on its four most heavily flown jets, including the Boeing
737 involved in the April 28 accident.
   Boeing also urged the airline to take the planes out of service
in the spring for permanent repairs, inspections and to complete
all deferred maintenance, the Post said, citing documents that it
said are part of the government investigation into the incident in
which a section of the plane's roof ripped off during flight.
   In a Nov. 13 letter, Boeing advised the airline: ``Aloha has a
high-frequency flight schedule and operates in a highly corrosive
environment. These factors certainly contribute to the corrosion
and fatigue damage observed on the two airplanes surveyed.
   ``This as well as the practice of repainting the airplane before
and during inspections, deferring repairs and@or making temporary
instead of terminating (permanent) repairs, contributes to our
mutual concerns,'' wrote Boeing.
   The manufacturer also urged Aloha to develop a new maintenance
program that would assure thorough and frequent inspections as well
as preventive maintenance on Aloha's aging planes, the Post said.
   The recommendations were made after a team of Boeing engineers
visited Aloha last fall to collect data for its aging fleet
research program, the newspaper said, quoting from a 150-page
document.
   The document consists of Boeing's November maintenance
evaluation and dozens of recommendations, as well as listings of
the highlights of September, October and January inspections of
three older Aloha jets. The report also includes material
describing Boeing's findings in the aging fleet survey program.
   Aloha President Maurice Myers said of the documents, ``By their
very nature, these documents would be expected to be critical and
to recommend changes.''
   He told the newspaper that Boeing's engineers had overlooked
many aspects of Aloha's operations, which led them to draw
erroneous conclusions.
   The document has become part of the National Transportation
Safety Board's investigation of the accident. The agency's hearing
into the cause of the accident will focus not only on Aloha's
maintenance program, but also on Boeing's responsibility.
   Boeing did not share the information with the government until
after the accident even though the Federal Aviation Administration
had asked to be apprised of progress on the research at Aloha, said
the Post.
   According to the Boeing report, the newspaper said, seven of
Aloha's 10 jets were more than 15 years old and three of Aloha's
jets had flown beyond the 75,000 flights originally envisioned as
the lifespan of the 737.
</TEXT>
