<1ST_LINE>u w AM-Obit-Schumm     06-25 0225</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Obit-Schumm,210</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Retired Newswoman, Government Spokeswoman Dead at 66</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Ruth Frances Schumm, a retired newswoman,
government spokeswoman and congressional press aide to former
President Lyndon B. Johnson, died of cancer Saturday at George
Washington University Hospital. She was 66.
   Miss Schumm, who had operated her own real estate investment
business since the mid-1960s, was a press aide to Johnson from
January 1959 to February 1963. During that time, Johnson was a
Texas senator, Senate majority leader and vice president.
   She had joined his staff as an assistant press secretary and
worked out of Johnson's Capitol Hill offices and with the Senate
Democratic Policy Committee.
   She subsequently spent three years with the Peace Corps, where
she was an information specialist, before retiring from the
government in 1966. Since that time, she had managed her real
estate investments.
   A native of Dallas, Miss Schumm moved to Washington in 1944 and
spent three years with the National Institute of Public Affairs and
Co-op magazine. She also worked for the Washington bureau of the
Philadelphia Record for a short time.
   From 1947 to 1959, she was a reporter with the Washington bureau
of the Dallas Morning News. She covered the Texas delegation on
Capitol Hill and hearings before the Supreme Court and various
regulatory bodies.
   Survivors include a sister, Emily Jane Overton of Hemet, Calif.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880625-0210 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-06-25-88 2353EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u a AM-MultipleShooting 2ndLd-Writethru a0684 06-25 0551</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Multiple Shooting, 2nd Ld - Writethru, a0684,0562</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Two Dead, Four Wounded in Rampage at Warehouse
^Eds: Subs grafs 10-12 `Flenaugh, who ... the victims.' with five
grafs to UPDATE with police saying gunman may have aimed at
victims; employee saying guard always carried a gun</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CONCORD, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A security guard accused of shooting up
the warehouse where he worked mumbled complaints about his job as
he fired on co-workers, killing two and wounding four, police and
witnesses said.
   Sebron Flenaugh Jr., 45, was arrested without incident at his
home by Oakland police Friday night about three hours after the
rampage at the Micropure Inc. warehouse. The company distributes
household water purifying kits.
   Witnesses told police that a man dressed in a guard's uniform
and brandishing a handgun had followed an employee through a door
and into the warehouse, where he started shooting on the shipping
dock. There were 21 telemarketing people working in the building at
the time.
   The gunman used .357-caliber revolver carrying six rounds,
Concord police said.
   ``I was sitting at the break table,'' said Lisa Patton, 19,
``and he just walked in and started shooting my friends. I ran and
called police.''
   `Everybody was screaming and running,'' said 17-year-old
Germaine Reyes, who was in the shipping room when the shooting
started. ``I hit the ground and went under the table.''
   Throughout the shootings, workers said the gunman uttered barely
audible curses, several times complaining of either a ``lousy job''
or a ``crummy job.''
   After the shootings the guard went out the back door, got into
his car and drove away, witnesses told police.
   Seventeen-year-old Jennifer Hollis of Martinez, who was hit in
the chest and abdomen, died Friday night on the operating table at
John Muir Medical Center in Walnut Creek, hospital spokeswoman
Sandra Ryan said. Jim Disney, 19, of Concord died about five hours
later at the hospital after surgery on stomach wounds.
   Flenaugh, who was not authorized to carry a weapon on the job,
was an employee of Wells Security Systems in Danville, which had
assigned him to the Micropure warehouse, said Concord Police Lt.
Jim Jennings.
   Micropure worker Joseph Hall said Flenaugh ``always carried a
gun'' while he was working. Hall said the guard did not conceal the
weapon.
   Micropure employees said Flenaugh had worked at the company
about 18 months and was a loner.
   Police Lt. Jim Webster on Saturday said Flenaugh had a ``casual
but congenial'' relationship with the victims.
   Webster added that ``indications at this point are that he aimed
at these specific people. Why? ... I don't know.''
   Flenaugh hadn't provided police with any motive, Jennings said.
``Possibly he was depressed, but we're not sure what set him off,''
he said.
   He said Flenaugh would be booked for investigation of murder and
five counts of assault with a deadly weapon.
   Micropure workers described Flenaugh as ``friendly'' in the
past, and said they liked him enough to ask him to join them for
beer and pizza. He always declined, however, they said.
   One of the injured was taken to Muir with a superficial back
wound. The other three victims were taken to Mount Diablo Hospital
in Concord, where all were reported in stable condition Saturday.
   Micropure employs about 45 people in the one-story building
where the shootings occurred.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
