<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Soviet-AfghanVeterans     06-25 0379</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Soviet-Afghan Veterans,0387</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Veterans Waiting Days For Tickets Home</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MOSCOW (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Soviet soldiers returning from Afghanistan are
forced to wait days and pay black market prices to get home as the
summer vacation rush pushes the country's transport system to its
limits, it was reported Friday.
   Two reporters of the official news agency Tass recounted trips
around railway stations in Moscow and airports in different regions
where Afghan veterans were standing in long lines to get home.
   One group waited three days at a Moscow station trying to get to
Simferopol, the main town in the Crimea, one of the Soviet Union's
prime vacation regions, TASS said.
   The reporters quoted the group as saying cashiers in the Uzbek
capital of Tashkent, where many soldiers land on their way home
from Afghanistan, were asking for the equivalent of $170 or
demanding foreign currency coupons to sell airplane tickets to
Moscow.
   Some veterans then have to wait in the capital penniless,
leaving only once they are sent money from home, Tass said.
   A soldier identified only as Sergei Pavlov told the reporters he
was lucky enough to have a commander who made return reservations
in advance for his unit. But he complained bitterly about a
three-hour wait in 113-degree heat at the Tashkent airport to clear
customs.
   ``I'll admit, we expected some other kind of welcome,'' Pavlov
was quoted as saying.
   The Tass report quoted a senior Defense Ministry official as
saying the situation had improved in recent days. The official said
the army was doing everything it could to clear the backlog at
railway stations and airports.
   The jam is worsened by regular soldiers returning home on summer
leave and conscripts finishing their two-year compulsory military
service, the official was quoted as saying.
   Domestic flights on the state-run Soviet airline, Aeroflot, are
almost always sold out, even in winter. In summer, trains to the
south where many of the country's 284 million people take vacation
are jammed full.
   The Soviet Union is estimated to have had about 115,000 troops
in Afghanistan. Under an accord negotiated in Geneva, Soviet troops
began pulling out of Afghanistan May 15. Half the force is
scheduled to be back home by the end of August, with the withdrawal
completed by next Feb. 15.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
