<1ST_LINE>r i AM-BRF--Britain-Crash     06-25 0148</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-BRF--Britain-Crash,0152</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Pilot Barely Escaped From Burning Jet</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   An aerobatics pilot made a spectacular escape
Friday by activating his ejector seat a second before his jet
caught fire while accelerating for takeoff.
   Squadron Leader Peter Collins, deputy leader of the Royal Air
Force's Red Arrows flying team, fell a few hundred feet to the
ground on his parachute. He suffered only minor back injuries.
   His Hawk aircraft was one of a formation of four taking off in
an aerobatics display at Scampton air force base in Lincolnshire,
northeast England.
   Collins, 34, ejected as smoke began pouring from the jet,
soaring to safety above a fireball that enveloped the aircraft.
   The RAF said it was investigating the cause of the accident.
   The Red Arrows only recently renewed their displays following
several accidents since last October in which one pilot died and
four jets were lost.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
