<FILEID>AP-NR-06-25-88 0559EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Britain-Gulf     06-25 0432</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Britain-Gulf,0445</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Joint European Gulf Minesweeping Task Force Formed</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   British, Dutch and Belgian ships will form a joint
minesweeping task force to keep the Persian Gulf clear for merchant
vessels, the British government announced Friday.
   The flotilla is the first joint European task force in the
region since the Iran-Iraq war began in September 1980. It will not
increase the number of mine sweepers the three nations already have
in the gulf.
   Ian Stewart, armed forces minister of state, notified Parliament
in a written message Friday that five minesweepers already in the
gulf _ three British, one Dutch, one Belgian _ will begin joint
operations July 1.
   Their movements will be controlled by a separate British vessel
under command of a Royal Navy officer, a Ministry of Defense
spokesman said. The commander will be assisted by a Belgian or
Dutch staff officer.
   ``The arrangements for cooperation between the Royal Navy and
other Western navies in the gulf remain unchanged,'' Stewart said.
   Naval units from the United States, Soviet Union, France and
Italy also patrol the region, offering protection to their own flag
merchant vessels. The United States recently broadened its role to
allow its warships to intervene in attacks on neutral shipping.
   Iran attacks neutral vessels in retaliation for Iraqi raids on
its own shipping lanes. The Iranians have also been accused of
sowing mines.
   The Western navies have co-ordinated their efforts in recent
years to keep the strategic waterway open, but have retained
separate commands.
   Last month, Stewart said Soviet proposals to form a single
U.N.-sponsored task force in the gulf ``would be very difficult to
put together ... in practical terms.''
   The British, Dutch and Belgian governments have been engaged in
discussions ``for some time'' about bringing their minesweepers
under joint control, the Ministry of Defense spokesman said,
speaking on condition of anonymity in keeping with British practice.
   The planned withdrawal of a Belgian command vessel from the area
July 1 ``strengthened the case for full co-operation,'' the
spokesman said.
   The new task force will patrol the area north of Bahrain, the
spokesman said, under the protection of a destroyer and two
frigates from the Royal Navy's Armilla patrol.
   The operation is code-named ``Calendar'' after the successful
mine clearance of the Netherlands' Scheldt estuary after World War
II.
   A spokesman for Jane's Publishing Co., which produces the
authoritative ``Jane's Fighting Ships,'' said vessels from the
Western navies in the region currently number 52.
   There are 27 American vessels in the gulf and north Arabian Sea,
a spokesman for the U.S. Department of Defense said in Washington.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
