<1ST_LINE>r a AM-US-Angola     06-25 0366</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-US-Angola,0378</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Angolan Rebel Leader Defends South African Support, Denounces
Apartheid</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Angola</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JAMES MARTINEZ</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MIAMI (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Jonas Savimbi, the U.S.-backed leader of a
guerrilla war against Angola's Cuban-supported government, on
Friday defended taking help from South Africa.
   ``When you are fighting for your country, you must get help from
even the devil himself,'' said Savimbi, head of the National Union
for the Total Independence of Angola, also known as UNITA.
   Savimbi spoke here before a group of anti-communist Cuban exiles
as peace talks continued to end the 13-year civil war.
   Democratic presidential contender Michael Dukakis and American
black leaders have denounced Savimbi for taking arms from South
Africa, but he says he is misunderstood.
   ``I condemn apartheid, but I support freedom,'' Savimbi told a
news conference. ``I'm not here to discuss the policies of South
Africa, which I condemn. I'm fighting for freedom and you must do
it any way you can.''
   Savimbi said the current buildup of 57,000 Cuban troops in
Angola clouds the peace talks that began this week in Cairo, Egypt,
the third round of discussions in two months.
   The United States, which also helps arm the Angolan guerrillas,
is mediating between South Africa and a joint Angolan-Cuban
delegation to resolve the war and end South African rule over
neighboring Namibia.
   Angola's Marxist government is demanding an end to South African
military aid to the UNITA rebels, while South Africa is is
demanding that Cuba withdraw its troops from Angola as a
precondition for Namibia's independence.
   ``There were 45,000 Cuban troops in March, and now there are
57,000,'' Savimbi said. ``They're not withdrawing, they're
increasing tremendously.
   ``We don't want to be recolonized by Castro,'' said Savimbi, who
once fought to help free Angola from colonization by Portugal.
   Savimbi's one-day visit to Miami was sponsored by the
Cuban-American National Foundation.
   Foundation head Jorge Mas Canosa said a private dinner was
planned in Savimbi's honor Friday night to show support for his
cause but not to raise money.
   ``He knows he has our support,'' Mas Canosa said. ``We've
provided hospital beds, food and medicine to his troops in the past
and we are ready to do it again.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
