<FILEID>AP-NR-06-25-88 0042EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a AM-BishopsConference     06-25 0549</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Bishops Conference,0567</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>AIDS, Women's Issues Top Agenda At Gathering Of Bishops</HEAD>
<DATELINE>COLLEGEVILLE, Minn. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Three peace groups planned an
all-night prayer vigil as about 250 Roman Catholic bishops gathered
Friday for a national conference to consider AIDS, women's issues
and the morality of nuclear war.
   On Saturday the bishops are to debate and vote on a report about
the morality of U.S. nuclear policy.
   Pax Christi of Minnesota, Benedictines for Peace from St. Joseph
and Collegeville, and Franciscans for Peace of Little Falls planned
the vigil to coincide with discussions on the morality of U.S.
nuclear policy.
   The report on nuclear policy is the result of two years of work
by a bishops' committee commissioned as a follow-up to their 1983
peace pastoral.
   The committee is recommending that its ``conditional
acceptance'' of nuclear deterrence be retained, according to a
pre-conference news release.
   The bishops received a letter Friday from Gen. James Abrahamson,
director of the Strategic Defense Initiative Organization, who
wrote of his fears that some of conference's recommendations might
be based on inaccurate information.
   ``Specifically, I wish to challenge some of the arguments which
attempt to substantiate the final recommendations ... which, if
left unchallenged, will certainly perpetuate the cloud of
misunderstanding that surrounds SDI and its promise of a moral
deterrence to nuclear war,'' he said.
   The session at St. John's University in south-central Minnesota
is the fourth meeting in six years of the National Conference of
Catholic Bishops.
   About 280 of the bishops also discussed Friday the first draft
of a pastoral letter on the concerns of women in church and society.
   ``It is one thing to read a report on the reactions of women to
the first draft of this pastoral,'' the Most Rev. Joseph Imesch
told the conference. ``It is quite another thing to hear women
voice their concerns personally.
   ``The mere fact that men were writing a pastoral letter about
women caused considerable skepticism for a number of people,'' said
Imesch, bishop of the Joliet, Ill., diocese. ``We dared not presume
what women thought or felt.''
   The 100-page document is the result of three years work by a
committee of six bishops and seven women. The committee met with 25
national Catholic women's oganizations and heard from 75,000 women
who participated in forums in 100 dioceses, and at 60 colleges and
45 military bases across the country.
   The document also explores Catholic tradition and proposes ways
of addressing the concerns within the framework of the teachings of
the church.
   A majority of women love the church, the report said. Many are
comfortable with their treatment in the church, but many others
want more participation. Some saw their exclusion from the
priesthood as unjust.
   The document doesn't address the issue of the ordination of
women to the priestood, but it calls for a study of allowing women
to become deacons.
   The majority praised the church's stance on abortion, but many
questioned its teaching on contraception.
   The document, which calls sexism a sin, also insists that men
take their responsibility in the areas of sexuality, procreation
and parenthood seriously.
   After hearing the concerns of other bishops, Imesch said the
document might need a major revision but he still hoped the bishops
could act upon it as scheduled for their November 1989 meeting.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
