<NOTE>$Adv08</NOTE>
<NOTE>For Release Weekend Editions, July 8-10, and Thereafter</NOTE>
<HEAD>Actress Dyana Ortelli Avoids Hispanic Stereotypes</HEAD>
<NOTE>With LaserPhoto</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By JERRY BUCK</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Television Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Dyana Ortelli is perfectly comfortable as the
center of attention, which, as it turns out, she usually is.
   All eyes turn when Ortelli, who stars in the syndicated comedy
``Marblehead Manor,'' enters a room. She's as hard to miss as a
cockatoo in a flock of sparrows.
   Her dark hair is teased into punk spikes. She is dressed all in
black: bolero jacket, bra, miniskirt, boots and gloves. The bra is
festooned with multi-hued bows. The gloves are covered with buttons
of every size and color. Her fingernails are painted a vivid
orange. Her earrings are tiny, multi-colored abacuses.
   Ortelli laughed. ``I play Lupe on the show, and Lupe is just an
extension of myself,'' she said. ``She's the cook, but she's a
little weird. Her regular uniform is accessorized by the most
colorful things you ever saw. I describe her as a cross between
Carmen Miranda and Cyndi Lauper. Once, she even wore a hat with
bananas in it.''
   Ortelli's 8-year-old son, Humberto Ortiz, also appeared on the
comedy as Lupe's son, Elvis. ``After they signed him, they wanted
to change his name to Jesus,'' she said. ``I said every other
Hispanic on television was named Jesus. Elvis was really the kind
of name Lupe would give her son.''
   They also played mother and son in the movies ``Born in East
L.A.'' and ``Three Amigos'' and in a Pepto-Bismol commercial.
Ortelli also appeared in ``La Bamba.''
   ``Marblehead Manner,'' a farce set in a millionaire's mansion
near Boston, was part of a five-night package of syndicated
comedies NBC ran on its owned-and-operated stations in the
half-hour before prime time. The NBC stations did not renew most of
the comedies, including ``Marblehead Manor,'' because of
disappointing ratings. The show is syndicated elsewhere and
currently in reruns.
   It also stars Paxton Whitehead as the butler, Phil Morris as the
chauffeur, Rodney Hudson as the handyman, Michael Richard as the
gardener, and Linda Thorsen and Bob Frazier as the millionaire
couple.
   ``Most of the characters were pretty normal, but Michael was the
weirdest,'' she said. ``We were always misinterpreting people and
situations. We'd turn things around and create new situations. We
were always solving problems that didn't need solving.''
   She said the thing she loved about playing Lupe was the freedom
she had to make her different from the Hispanic stereotypes. ``She
dressed in her own way and she acted in her own way,'' she said.
   Ortelli was born in Mexico and grew up in Texas. Her father is
an anesthesiologist at a Laredo hospital. She attended private
schools and as a child was cast in a bilingual children's series in
Austin, Texas. Her oldest brother danced with the Berlin Ballet and
is currently makeup man for the Berlin Opera.
   ``When I was in school my first cousin, Paulina, and I made a
pact to become actresses, and whoever was successful first would
help the other out,'' she said. ``She's doing well in Mexico City
as a singer and on a soap opera. She wants to come to the United
States. I wish I had a variety show so I could have her as a
guest.''
   Ortelli lived in London and Scotland for two years while her
husband studied abroad. They have since divorced.
   She moved to Los Angeles after returning to this country and was
almost immediately cast in the stage play ``Zoot Suit.'' Her maiden
name was Elizondo and her married name was Ortiz. She combined them
to make Ortelli.
   ``When I came to Los Angeles I found out for the first time that
I was a member of the Hispanic minority,'' she said. ``My agent
said I could play only Hispanic roles and that I had to change my
looks to look Hispanic. She said my hair had to be black, straight
and parted in the middle. She's no longer my agent.
   ``My first audition was for the girlfriend of a gang member. My
first speaking role on television was as a non-Hispanic nurse on
`Cagney & Lacey.' I thought sure after they cast me they'd change
her name to something Hispanic, but they didn't.''
   Her complaint is that Hispanic roles are usually downscale. ``I
say get us out of the barrios and into the condos,'' she said.
``I'm not in a position to choose my work. I wish I could. If I'm
offered a week's work as a cocaine dealer I'll take it. I just ask
for a balance. You can't expect every Hispanic to be a
professional, but you can have a balance.''
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv for Weekend Editions, July 8-10</NOTE>
