<2ND_LINE>BC-Week's Business, Adv 25-26-2 Takes,0770</2ND_LINE>
<NOTE>$adv 25</NOTE>
<NOTE>$adv 26</NOTE>
<NOTE>For Release Weekend Editions June 25-26</NOTE>
<HEAD>Pointer Sisters And Lollipops Enliven Computer Biz</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By PETER COY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Computer companies face an awful dilemma each
time they introduce a new product _ to bore the audience with bits
and bytes, or gag it with glitz.
   This past week, just when cool and dry seemed to be the trend, a
pair of multimillion-dollar events showed that computer companies
still love show biz.
   On Monday, Compaq Computer Corp. unveiled two personal computers
by filling a New York stage with electronic music and athletic
ballet dancers in shiny, multi-colored body suits.
   A day later, International Business Machines Corp. announced new
mid-sized computers with an Academy Awards-style show beamed by
satellite to 100,000 people across the United States _ the biggest
such broadcast ever by a private company.
   Larry Ford, an IBM executive, gamely followed a script that had
him receiving a lollipop, a loan approval and a toy soldier's hat
from actors portraying grateful IBM customers.
   At first it seems incongruous for computer makers _ the vanguard
of the rational age of high technology _ to be falling back on
pyrotechnics and emotional appeals.
   But then again, people are people, and no one gets a big charge
out of hearing someone in a suit drone on about 48-bit
addressability or 82385 cache memory controllers.
   ``We punctuate the straight business message with a little
glitter, like the machines rising out of the floor, to make it a
little more warm and a little less formal,'' said Bert Reisman,
IBM's assistant group executive for the Marketing and Services
Group.
   Glitter is second nature to Compaq, which in 1985 hired the
Pointer Sisters to dance on a huge model of its Portable 286
singing, ``I'm So Excited.''
   Still, the Houston-based computer maker wants to be taken
seriously.
   ``It's not just that we're interested in throwing a party,''
said James D'Arezzo, Compaq's vice president for corporate
marketing. ``The bottom line is, you're trying to capture mind
space: of the press, the analyst community and most of all your
authorized dealers.''
   Yes, but how much glitter is too much glitter?
   ``We've got event-inflation, I think,'' complained Esther Dyson,
editor and publisher of Release 1.0 newsletter and a veteran of
uncounted product introductions.
   ``I really hate the ones where they give you 10 minutes of rock
music in the dark,'' she said. ``My basic feeling is, if I want to
see dancing I'll buy a ticket and go with a date.''
   IBM, with more than $50 billion in annual revenue, must be doing
something right. But some people who attend its shows say they have
gone from dull to slightly embarrassing.
   Bill Machrone, editor-in-chief and publisher of PC Magazine,
cringes in memory of an event last year at which IBM executives
fumbled through a supposedly impromptu and humorous interchange
with Jamie Farr and Bill Christopher, the former ``M-A-S-H''
characters.
   ``It's painful to watch, but IBM, I think they think they're
really rocking and rolling when they do this,'' Machrone said.
``People are afraid to tell them otherwise.''
   That's a slightly harsh assessment, said Nora F. Gildea,
director of marketing for Ideassociates Inc. of Billerica, Mass., a
company that does business with IBM.
   ``It was OK. Everybody sort of laughed wryly in our group.
You're talking about seasoned customers who've been to a lot of
these things.''
   Commodore International Ltd. introduced its Amiga three years
ago by having Andy Warhol take a digitized image of Blondie's
Deborah Harry and use the computer to ``paint'' her picture live on
stage at New York's Lincoln Center.
   Compaq once made its chief executive Rod Canion appear from
nowhere on stage in a blaze of light. It was especially
entertaining because Canion is the ultimate straight man.
   ``I think he sleeps in his suit and tie. So that was a magical
moment,'' Ms. Dyson said.
   Apple Computer Inc. has gotten quiet after a run of
announcements that included lowering its Apple IIgs from the
ceiling into a blaze of lasers and dry ice.
   Once Apple revved up a sales or dealer meeting with a version of
``Ghostbusters'' featuring dancers in radiation suits, Macintoshes
strapped to their backs, singing ``Blue Busters.''
   Apple spokeswoman Marlene Williamson said Apple has been
concentrating lately on networking and communications products that
aren't suited to media blitzes. She vows Apple will be back with a
splash when the time is right.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>MORE</NOTE>
