<DOCNO> AP880625-0226 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-06-25-88 0629EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>a f BC-WeeklyBonds Adv25-26   06-25 0715</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-Weekly Bonds, Adv 25-26,0741</2ND_LINE>
<NOTE>$adv 25</NOTE>
<NOTE>$adv 26</NOTE>
<NOTE>For Release Weekend Editions June 25-26</NOTE>
<HEAD>Bond Prices Follow Rising Dollar</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By SKIP WOLLENBERG</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Bond prices danced to the dollar's tune this
past week, and the results gave bondholders reason to smile. But
what is going to happen when the upbeat music ends?
   ``The dollar is on a temporary run, and if you want to join the
party, you had better belly up to the bar quickly before they quit
serving free drinks,'' said Robert Brusca, economist for Nikko
Securities International in New York.
   When the dollar stops rising, Brusca said chances increase that
bond prices are going to slip and interest rates will edge higher.
   The dollar climbed sharply this week after the major industrial
nations meeting in Toronto reaffirmed their support for stability
of the dollar in foreign-exchange markets.
   As the dollar rose, foreign investors decided dollar-denominated
securities looked even more attractive, and their buying ignited a
powerful rally in Treasury notes and bonds.
   On Wednesday, prices of the bellwether 30-year Treasury issue
climbed $18 for every $1,000 in face value while its yield skidded
to 8.91 percent from 9.08 percent the previous evening.
   By midday Friday, prices were up another $5 for every $1,000 in
face value for the week and yields fell to 8.86 percent compared
with 9.09 percent at the end of the previous week.
   But one question facing bond investors at the end of the week
was what will happen if the dollar's climb runs out of steam? The
analysts say it may force the market to focus again on economic
fundamentals. And there is wide disagreement on what the
fundamentals show.
   Harold Nathan, chief economist for Wells Fargo & Co. in San
Francisco, said he finds evidence of solid growth in the United
States and abroad that will generate gains in inflation to the
detriment of bond prices.
   ``It's my belief that this rally is going to be short-lived and
it's not a trend,'' he said. ``Rates will head generally higher
with sporadic rallies like this last one creating volatility along
the line.''
   By the end of the year, Nathan expects the 30-year Treasury will
yield about 9.9 percent, or a full percentage point higher than its
current level.
   Nikko's Brusca said he sees some negative signs for the bond
market _ industrial production remains strong, factories are
operating near full capacity and industrial commodity prices such
as aluminum, zinc and nickel are rising. That could push inflation
higher, possibly prompting the Federal Reserve to encourage higher
interest rates.
   He expects the long Treasury's yield will rise to 9.75 percent
before settling down to about 9.5 percent at the end of the year.
   But Mickey Levy, chief economist for First Fidelity
Bancorporation in Philadelphia, said he finds mixed evidence on the
strength of the economy in the latest economic reports, and expects
a slowdown is imminent.
   This past week, for instance, the government reported a 2.2
percent decline in durable goods orders for May and said the
economy grew at a 3.6 percent rate in the first quarter after
adjustment for inflation, down from its 3.9 percent growth estimate
a month earlier.
   Levy said he expects long-term rates to fall to 8.75 percent by
the end of the year and 8 percent by the middle of 1989 as a
reduction in capital spending leads to a broader economic slowdown.
   Elliott Platt, research director for the investment firm
Donaldson, Lufkin & Jenrette Securities Corp., is even more
optimistic about chances for lower rates.
   He said he thinks a moderation in economic growth over the next
few months will send long-term rates to the 8 percent to 8.25
percent range by fall.
   Platt worries about the impact that the drought may have on the
economy, but it isn't the concern you might expect. While he
expects the drought to push food prices higher, he doesn't think
the increase will add much to overall inflation.
   Platt is more concerned about the psychological damage that
higher food prices may have on consumers' willingness to spend, a
key factor in keeping the economy growing. ``Once they see food
prices increase, we may have a break in consumer confidence,'' he
said.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv Weekend Editions June 25-26</NOTE>
