<FILEID>AP-NR-06-25-88 0616EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>d f PM-EconomyRdp     06-25 0412</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Economy Rdp,0427</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Personal Income, Spending Up Modestly in May</HEAD>
<NOTE>EDS: For Saturday PMs</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   The consumer spending boom could slow this summer, some
economists said after the government reported a modest increase in
personal spending and personal income for the month of May.
   A rise in the dollar on Friday helped the bond market, but
stocks slipped. Most grain prices retreated in response to
scattered showers, while energy futures prices dropped.
   The Dow Jones average of 30 industrial stocks fell 5.33 points
to 2,142.96, finishing the week with a gain of nearly 2 percent.
   The dollar's rise carried it past key psychological resistance
points to levels against many major currencies not seen in eight
months.
   In New York the dollar rose to 130.53 Japanese yen from 128.62
yen on Thursday. The dollar rose to 1.8155 West German marks from
1.7850 late Thursday.
   The Commerce Department said Friday that personal income rose
0.3 percent last month following a 0.1 percent gain in April.
   Meanwhile, personal consumption expenditures, which include
virtually everything except interest on debt, rose a moderate 0.5
percent in May following a 0.4 percent increase in April.
   John Hagens, an economist with the Wefa Group, a Bala Cynwyd,
Pa., consulting firm, said, ``I think basically our biggest concern
is how weak consumer spending is. ... The income growth is simply
not there to support much growth, particularly given higher food
prices expected because of the drought,'' he said.
   Through the first five years of the six-year economic expansion,
consumer buying has fueled the growth. Now, analysts are looking
for exports and sale of equipment to businesses to drive the
economy.
   Americans' disposable income _ what they have left after paying
taxes _ shot up 1.5 percent in May, after a 1.0 percent drop in
April that was the largest decline in a year.
   The drought-driven rally in most grain and soybean futures
markets stalled as scattered showers forced skittish traders to
pause for a look at reality, analysts said.
   Prices yo-yoed on the Chicago Board of Trade but finished mixed
with only oat futures continuing the sharply higher trend
established earlier in the week.
   On other exchanges, precious metals futures fell sharply;
livestock and meat futures were mixed; energy futures slipped; and
stock-index futures retreated.
   ``This thing has more lives than a cat. It kept coming back and
coming back,'' Victor Lespinasse, a trader with Dean Witter
Reynolds Inc., said of the grain market's erratic performance.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
